National Electricity Statistics
<H1>OVERVIEW OF THE NSW POWER SUPPLY SYSTEM</H1>

<P>
Development of the New South Wales power supply system has resulted
in location of the state's main generating stations close to the
coal fields from which they draw their fuel. Electricity is delivered
to major usage points via an extensive high voltage transmission
network (grid).
<P>
The advantages of this approach are that vast industrial power
complexes are removed from population centres, and the associated
problems of fuel haulage and provision of other major services
(water supply etc.) do not affect urban environments. As well,
it is much cheaper to transmit electricity than to transport vast
quantities of coal.
<P>
The state's overall power needs at any one time are met jointly
by all operating power stations on the grid. The stations pool
their electricity output. No one power station serves a particular
area.
<P>
Large, long-distance transmission lines are an integral part of
the philosophy on which the New South Wales supply system has
been built and are essential to economic and efficient bulk power
delivery.
<P>
These power lines have some undesirable aesthetic characteristics
but the alternative, a large number of smaller power stations
and transmission lines within cities and towns across the state,
would be self defeating, both environmentally and economically.
<P>
Nearly all the electrical energy used by the people and industries
of New South Wales is produced and transmitted in bulk, by Pacific
Power (The Electricity Commission of New South Wales). The remainder
is produced by a few small councils and privately owned generating
plants, some of which sell surplus production to the state supply
system.
<P>
A deregulatory trend, encouraging greater competitive input to
the system from the private sector, is expected to have significant
long-term impact.
<P>
Localised delivery of electricity to consumers in more than twenty
regions of the state is carried out by distributing authorities
which are closely attuned to the special needs of their district.
<P>
The New South Wales supply system could be likened, in business
terms, to a manufacturer/wholesaler, distributor/retailer arrangement
where Pacific Power is the main manufacturer/wholesaler and your
local electricity council is the distributor/retailer, i.e., the
people from whom you purchase your electricity.
<P>
As a marketable energy source (commodity if you like), electricity
is unusual. It must be manufactured at the instant it is needed.
When a light is turned on, the supply system must immediately
produce the additional power. Unlike most commodities, electricity
cannot be drawn, as required, from a reservoir or storage area,
except in a very small way from storage batteries.
<P>
This, of course, results in a constantly changing demand on the
supply network as electrical equipment and lighting is turned
on and off throughout the day, and presents supply authorities
with logistical problems unique to the electricity industry.
<P>
In New South Wales a sophisticated Data Acquisition and Control
(DAC) system is used to constantly evaluate and regulate the combination
of generating plant in service to ensure the changing power demand
is met with a maximum of economy and efficiency.
<P>
Supervision and overall control of the performance of the state's
supply network is carried out at Pacific Power's control centre
at Carlingford in Sydney.
<P>
An emerging national approach to electricity supply planning envisages
stronger interconnections between eastern state supply networks,
and competitive, cross-border interchange.
<P>
State and private generating authorities would compete for markets
anywhere within the interconnected system. For example, a privately
owned generating plant could contract to supply a customer in
another state (if the price was right) by paying a &quot;delivery&quot;
fee for use of the interconnected grid.
<H1>ELECTRICITY AUTHORITIES SERVING NEW SOUTH WALES</H1>

<P>
PACIFIC POWER (The Electricity Commission of New South Wales)
is the major authority responsible for generation and bulk transmission
of electric power, reliably, economically and safely throughout
the state. Pacific Power is the registered business name of The
Electricity Commission of New South Wales.
<P>
THE OFFICE OF ENERGY provides broad oversight of the energy industry,
including electricity supply. The Office also administers electrical
safety rules and their implementation as well as the operations
of local electricity distributing councils. Electricians are licensed
by the Building Services Corporation.
<P>
ELECTRICITY DISTRIBUTING COUNCILS are responsible for all aspects
of safe and economical local electricity supply to industrial,
commercial and domestic consumers within their particular region.
There are some 25 distribution authorities serving all parts of
New South Wales.
<P>
THE SNOWY MOUNTAINS HYDRO ELECTRIC AUTHORITY is a Commonwealth
Statutory Authority responsible for operation and maintenance
of the Snowy Scheme as a whole. The scheme is under the regulatory
guidance of the Snowy Mountains Council which oversees water releases
for irrigation and hydro generation.
<P>
THE ELECTRICITY COUNCIL OF NEW SOUTH WALES acts as a forum for
co-ordination of initiatives within the New South Wales electricity
supply industry and provides industry advice to the government.
Members of The Council represent the distributing authorities,
Pacific Power, The Office of Energy, Department of Local Government,
The Local Government Electricity Association and the Labour Council
of NSW.
<H1>PRODUCING ELECTRICITY</H1>

<P>
Electricity for widespread commercial and domestic use is almost
invariably produced by a generator. Storage batteries are an exception.
In these, a chemical reaction produces electricity.
<P>
The means by which the generator is driven varies widely throughout
the world, and is largely dependent on the natural energy resources
available.
<P>
A generator has a magnetised rotor as its core, spinning within
a surrounding shell of coils (usually copper) called a stator.
The stator coils intersect the spinning magnetic fields of the
rotor, inducing an alternating electric current into the coils.
<P>
Producing electricity is, in effect, an energy conversion process,
from one basic form of energy into electrical energy.
<H2>Using coal for electricity generation</H2>

<P>
In New South Wales, the main energy source for electricity generation
is black coal. There are abundant reserves available at reasonable
cost. New South Wales, and Australia generally, produce relatively
cheap electric power by world standards...one of the country's
few competitive advantages.
<P>
The coal is burnt in the furnace of a boiler to produce steam
at very high pressures and temperatures. The steam is directed
onto the blades of a turbine (imagine rows of finely bladed windmills
on a common shaft). The spinning turbine is directly coupled to,
and drives, the generator. (See Diagram One).
<H2>Other energy sources for electricity generation</H2>

<P>
A nuclear power station operates on the same basic principles,
except that the heat to produce steam is created by nuclear reaction
rather than by burning coal. Capital costs are very high and Government
legislation prevents development of nuclear power stations for
electricity generation in New South Wales.
<P>
In a hydro power station, the energy from falling water spins
the turbine which drives the generator. Vast quantities of water
are needed for large scale power production. Mainland Australia
has very limited hydro power potential, much of which has already
been realised.
<P>
A gas-turbine power station is one in which combustion gases at
very high pressure and temperature (rather than steam) are used
to spin the turbo-generator. A mixture of compressed air and vaporised
liquid fuel (or natural gas) is ignited in a combustion chamber
to produce the high pressure gas stream which drives the turbine.
<H2>Diagram One - Energy sources used to generate electricity
</H2>

<P>
New South Wales has a number of small gas-turbine units in its
system but, because of their high operating costs, they are mainly
for emergency use (they quickly reach their maximum generating
capacity). Additional, strategically located, gas-turbine stations
are being considered for short term operation during periods of
high electricity demand (in much the same way as the Snowy Mountains
power stations are used).
<P>
Wind energy can be used to drive a turbine which, in turn, is
coupled to a generator. In this case the turbine is often like
a large aeroplane propeller. New South Wales is researching suitable
locations.
<P>
In some cases, tidal and wave flows can be harnessed to provide
energy, but again, to drive the same basic generator. The large
tidal changes needed for successful development of a tidal power
station do not occur in New South Wales. Wave patterns are the
subject of research.
<P>
Solar energy can be used to both produce electricity or to reduce
the demand for electric or other energy forms.
<P>
One form of solar power station (solar thermal station) focuses
the sun's rays to collect heat energy which, again, produces steam
to drive a turbine/generator.
<P>
Solar collectors commonly found on roof tops collect and focus
energy from the sun's rays to heat water supplies, thus reducing
the demand for other energy forms... a desirable outcome from
a greenhouse point-of-view.
<P>
Photo-voltaic cells convert the sun's energy directly into an
electric current. These are the subject of extensive research
in New South Wales and will probably be providing useful supplementary
power to homes and factories by the turn of the century.
<H2>New technologies for electricity generation</H2>

<P>
There are a number of other emerging combinations of modern technology.
Many of them are environmentally friendly and of high efficiency.
These are likely to play a part in the future provision of electrical
energy for New South Wales.
<P>
Most of these still fall within the general principle of harnessed
energy driving a generator, which will continue as the basis for
nearly all of our electricity production in the medium term future.
<P>
Some of these new technologies are:
<P>
FLUIDISED BED COMBUSTION, where a wide range of fuels including
low grade coal or coal wastes, sewerage sludge etc. are burned
as a fluid mix in a special furnace to produce steam, again, to
drive a conventional generator.
<P>
COMBINED CYCLE GENERATING PLANTS, where hot exhaust gases from
a gas turbine generating unit are utilised to operate an associated
steam turbine generator, thus achieving a better overall efficiency.
<P>
MAGNETOHYDRODYNAMICS, where extremely high temperature gases are
expanded within a magnetic field to directly produce an electrical
current. This technology is still very much in the experimental
stage.
<P>
Another technology, already in small scale practical use, is the
<P>
UTILISATION OF METHANE GAS (an unfriendly greenhouse gas), from
compressed refuse dumps or coal seams, as fuel for gas-turbine
generators or reciprocating engine driven generators.
<P>
CO-GENERATION, is not so much a new technology as one on which
much greater emphasis is being placed for efficiency reasons.
This technique involves the use of waste heat from industrial
process plants for power generation or vice versa.
<H1>DISTRIBUTING ELECTRICITY</H1>

<P>
The concept of producing electricity at or near the basic energy
source depends on a large scale transmission network to move bulk
quantities of electricity efficiently to strategic demand centres
throughout New South Wales.
<P>
This distribution network must also provide, as far as economically
practicable, for alternative routing of supply to these demand
centres in the event of interference or damage (usually lightning)
to a major power line.
<P>
The &quot;backbone&quot; of this network is an extensive 330 000
volt grid running between the northern and southern borders of
New South Wales and extending into the near western regions. Superimposed
over this are sections of a developing 500 000 volt grid which
will interlink major cities or demand points with major power
stations. There is also an interwoven 132 000 volt system from
which supply usually passes to local distributing authorities.
<P>
The New South Wales bulk supply network and the Victorian and
South Australian systems are interconnected for mutually beneficial
interchange of electricity supplies.
<P>
Introduction of the national grid concept will involve strengthening
interconnections and perhaps the inclusion of Queensland and Tasmania
in a South and East Australian National Grid.
<P>
Electricity, when produced at a power station, passes through
a transformer to raise voltage for efficient long distance transmission.
At delivery or transfer points around the network the voltage
is lowered, again through transformers (in substations), for local
distribution through council networks.
<P>
A typical example of power station to household supply voltages
would be:
<P>
Power station generation at 23 000 volts, stepped up to 500 000
or 330 000 volts (in a transformer) for initial transmission across
the state. The voltage would be stepped down (again in a transformer)
for more localised delivery via 132 000 and 66 000 volt lines.
Retail distribution is usually handled at 33 000 and 11 000 volts
finally reaching smaller end-users at 415 and 240 volts.
<P>
Though power ultimately arrives at the point of use through street
lines and small local transformers, the end user, in reality,
is totally dependent on the very big transmission lines, often
some distance away.
<H2>Diagram Two - From Power Station to You</H2>

<P>
Pacific Power has service centres strategically located throughout
New South Wales and carries out regular aerial and ground patrols
to inspect and maintain the substations and transmission lines
of the bulk supply network. Distributing councils have similar
emergency and routine maintenance provisions within their individual
retail networks.
<P>
Future development and expansion of the state's main transmission
grid is entirely dependent on any increase in demand for electricity
at growth centres.
<P>
Today's environmental climate demands that any such development
undergo the most rigorous scrutiny to both justify need and ensure
environmentally harmonious construction.
<P>
No generally applicable technology exists as an alternative to
transmission lines. High-voltage underground cables cost up to
twenty times as much as overhead lines and, because they are technically
limited to sections about 20 kilometres in length, are only used
in high density urban or city areas.
<P>
These days, transmission lines are positioned, where the topography
permits, below the skyline, and blended into the countryside by
painting structures, dulling conductors and colouring insulators.
<P>
Electromagnetic fields associated with the state's biggest power
lines are well within standards laid down by the World Health
Organisation and often significantly less than those experienced
in common domestic situations.
<H1>PEOPLE AND THE POWER DEMAND</H1>

<P>
Nearly half the electricity consumed in New South Wales is for
industrial and commercial purposes. Rural consumption is about
two percent and miscellaneous uses such as public lighting and
railway traction account for about five percent. The remainder
is used by domestic consumers.
<P>
Electricity travels from power station to power point at the speed
of light, about 300 000 kilometres a second. Effectively, activation
of a single switch anywhere in the state has an instantaneous,
though minute, impact on the interconnected power supply network.
As power is turned on, the system, collectively, experiences an
increase in &quot;load&quot; and vice versa as power is turned
off.
<P>
The state's consumption of electric energy is, in effect, something
of a measure of economic activity while the instantaneous demand
is a barometer of the collective activities and habits of the
community. It reflects peaks of industrial activity which, when
added to domestic cooking, heating and lighting needs, usually
results in an annual maximum demand occurring during winter months
on a working day at about six pm.
<H2>Diagram Three - The Daily Power Demand Curve</H2>

<P>
A cold, bleak, or wet evening, on a day of the week when industry
normally works overtime, is the usual combination of factors which
sends the power demand to the year's &quot;high&quot;.
<P>
Summer demands are generally less, but industrial and commercial
demands continue and special factors, such as a growing air conditioning
load, can actually increase demand in some areas.
<P>
Even special community events such as sporting activities or very
popular TV programmes show up as power demand fluctuations, but
not always in an expected way.
<P>
There may be a rise in demand during the commercial break of a
high-rating TV show (rather than a fall) due to widespread use
of electric jugs for tea making. There is always a significant
fall in demand during the running of the Melbourne Cup. Many TVs
and radios are turned on, but this demand increase is more than
offset by a big decrease in industrial load as plant and machinery
are turned off.
<P>
Economic and efficient control of the state's power network under
these constantly changing conditions thus requires the best technology
and human skills available.
<H2>Electricity Tariffs</H2>

<P>
Two separate sets of prices apply to the electricity supply industry
in New South Wales, a Bulk Supply Tariff for the wholesaling of
electricity by Pacific Power to the various distributing authorities,
and Retail Tariffs for retail supply by distributing authorities
to their customers (the community generally).
<P>
Different retail tariffs apply to different groups or classes
of customers.
<P>
Domestic Tariffs and Off-peak Tariffs apply to residential customers.
General Supply Tariffs or Time-of-day General Supply Tariffs are
usually applicable to small business customers (commercial and
industrial). Larger business customers are usually on a Demand
Tariff or Time-of-day Demand Tariff.
<P>
Special end-use tariffs such as Irrigation Tariffs, Process Heating
Tariffs etc., are also available to business customers.
<P>
For large electricity intensive industries, such as aluminium
smelters, special contract tariffs can apply. These tariffs usually
have special features such as &quot;interruptibility&quot; agreements,
which can give Pacific Power the right to interrupt power supplies
for limited periods of time. This provides a valuable &quot;buffer
margin&quot; in cases of short-term emergencies (generator repairs
etc.) on the state's power supply system.
<P>
Supply industry restructuring, the introduction of a national
grid and wholesale electricity market could positively influence
electricity pricing during the 90's and beyond.
<P>
The evolving electricity market will function like other commercial
commodity markets, encouraging open access to the grid and free
trade in bulk electricity for private generating companies, public
utilities and private and public electricity customers.
<P>
In effect, a private generating company might sell electricity
to a bulk customer in another state. The contract between supplier
and purchaser would pay the grid a &quot;delivery&quot; fee.
<H1>UNDERSTANDING ELECTRICITY</H1>

<H2>Magnetism and Electricity </H2>

<P>
Commercial generation of electricity relies on the principles
of magnetism and magnetic fields. The biggest example of a magnetic
field is that which links the earth's north and south magnetic
poles, and on which navigational compasses depend.
<P>
If a piece of conductive material (like copper wire) is passed
through the magnetic field of say, a bar magnet, a tiny electrical
impulse (a movement of electrons) occurs in the wire. If the wire
is passed back through the field, the electrons move in the opposite
direction. This is the very basis for the production of alternating
current electricity.
<H2>Diagram Four - The Production of an Electrical Current</H2>

<P>
To produce commercial quantities of electricity, coils of copper
conductor are grouped in a stationary housing around a spinning
electro-magnet (to intersect the magnet's lines of force). Alternating
electric current is induced into the coils (windings) as the alternate
magnetic fields pass through them. The &quot;shell&quot; of coils
is called a stator. The spinning electro-magnet is the rotor (imagine
a cylinder divided, along its length, into north and south poles).
The combined unit is a generator, sometimes called an alternator.
<P>
The flow of electrons is called the current. The rate of their
movement back and forth (alternating current) is the frequency,
usually expressed in cycles per second (50 in Australia) or &quot;hertz&quot;.
All generators linked to the supply network are synchronised to
a single frequency. This is carefully maintained within one-tenth
of a hertz.
<P>
Electric time is controlled by the system frequency. Minute fluctuations
in frequency are monitored to keep the cumulative variation of
electric time within a maximum of 3 seconds of standard time.
The variation in New South Wales is usually held to about one
and a half seconds.
<P>
Electricity must flow in a circle (circuit) from the generator
back to the generator. This principle is best understood if electricity
is thought of as a fluid, the generator as a pump and the conductor
as a pipeline. If the pipeline is closed off the fluid will not
flow, no matter how powerful the pump. However, if a closed circuit
of pipes is established and say, a &quot;water wheel&quot; incorporated
in the circuit, the fluid will flow and the wheel will turn (i.e.
work will be done using the energy of the moving fluid).
<P>
Diagram Five - Electrical Energy must flow in a circuit to do
work . . .
<P>
Similarly, a light bulb in a electricity circuit will draw energy
for its operation from the flow of electrons in the circuit.
<P>
There are many intermediate steps between a power station generator
and a household light bulb in a commercial electricity undertaking.
<P>
If the conductor is again thought of as a delivery pipeline, the
walls of the pipe would set up a resistance to the passage of
fluid. A long, narrow pipe would create a lot of resistance over
its total length. So it is with electricity through a conductor.
But, rather than use an expensive large conductor, electricity
is boosted to a high pressure to achieve delivery with minimal
losses. This is done in a transformer.
<P>
A transformer has two coils of wire around an iron core. One coil
comes from the generator circuit and magnetises the core. The
second coil, on the other side of the core has more turns (in
a step-up transformer). The electro-magnetic field of the incoming
circuit induces an electric current to flow in the second coil,
but at a higher pressure (voltage) because of the greater number
of turns in the coil (windings). A step-down transformer works
in the reverse way.
<H2>Diagram Six - How a Transformer Works</H2>

<P>
The current handling capacity of a transformer is usually expressed
in kilovolt-amps (kVA) or megavolt-amps (MVA) and is known as
the &quot;rating&quot;.
<P>
Voltage then, is a measure of electrical pressure. Amperage is
the rate of flow (think litres per second in fluid terms) and
wattage is the resultant force of delivery or power, i.e. volts
x amps = watts.
<P>
Power (watts) multiplied by time is energy or the work done by
an electric current. This, in turn, leads to a usage measure of
watt-hours (kilowatt-hours in metering terms). A kilowatt is a
thousand watts. A megawatt is a thousand kilowatts (or a million
watts) and a gigawatt is a million kilowatts. A kilowatt-hour
is a thousand watts of electricity used for one hour, (e.g. a
100 watt light bulb used for ten hours would consume one kilowatt-hour
of electric energy).
<P>
In a normal power supply system then, electricity is generated
at a certain voltage and flows at a certain amperage to a step-up
transformer where the voltage is boosted for efficient long distance
transmission. At the other end of the transmission line the voltage
is reduced in a step-down transformer, usually in a substation,
where the flow is divided and sent in several directions on lower
voltage and amperage &quot;feeders&quot; (transmission lines).
<H2>Diagram Seven - Electricity Generation and Transmission</H2>

<P>
The process is repeated to the final point where, in the case
of Australian systems, a pole-top or local transformer provides
household supply which, in domestic terms, is at 240 volts and
up to 10 amps giving a maximum power point supply of 2400 watts.
If greater quantities of electricity are required, a second &quot;phase&quot;
can be connected to provide supply at 415 volts. (Three phases
are normally used in a major supply system to achieve a more economic
delivery of energy to larger users).
<P>
Direct current does not have the same cyclical flow as alternating
current (i.e. there is no frequency wave) and is ideal where a
smooth and wide range of speed control is required for special
motor driven applications (electric trains are a good example).
However, because direct current cannot be stepped up or down in
voltage by a transformer, a widespread d.c. distribution system
would be very complex and costly. If required, for special situations,
direct current is usually transmitted as a.c. and converted to
d.c. near the point of delivery by a rectifier.
<P>
Substations are, in effect, junction points in the supply system
which incorporate transformers, circuit breakers (i.e. large switches),
capacitors, sometimes rectifiers and other equipment. These are
points where the supply characteristics are changed and redirected.
<P>
Circuit breakers are very big switches often with the special
ability to extinguish the electrical arc associated with the opening
of a high-voltage switch in a circuit carrying a high current.
As well, they are designed to activate automatically and isolate
a section of the network if an abnormal condition is detected.
<P>
Bus-bars are simply common connectors (frequently steel, galvanised
iron or aluminium tube, or stranded copper wire) which link electrical
equipment. They are used extensively in substations and switching
stations.
<P>
Capacitors help improve, in certain &quot;load&quot; conditions,
the amount of energy which can be delivered at a given voltage.
<P>
Static Var Compensators are a sophisticated form of capacitor
with much broader and precise control capabilities.
<H1>ELECTRICAL TERMS AND MEASURES</H1>

