<P>
G (giga-) multiplies by 1 000 000 000
<P>
Note the distinction between symbols for quantities and abbreviations
of electrical terms. For example:
<P>
MW (megawatt) symbols, no stops = one million watts
<P>
mA (milli-ampere) symbols, no stops = one thousanth of an ampere
<P>
amp. written with a stop to indicate that it is an abbreviation
of the
<P>
word ampere
<H1>MAJOR POWER STATIONS SUPPLYING NEW SOUTH WALES</H1>

<H2>Introduction</H2>

<P>
Nearly ninety five percent of the state's electricity needs is
supplied from coal burning power stations.
<P>
The remainder comes from hydro sources, mostly the Snowy Mountains
Scheme.
<P>
(There is a very small, occasional contribution from the Pacific
Power's standby gas-turbine plant).
<P>
Most of the state's power stations are sited close to their fuel
or energy source. Coal-fired stations are near coal bearing areas.
Hydro stations are, of course, near suitable bodies of water.
<H1>BAYSWATER</H1>

<P>
Bayswater Power Station is a coal burning station located about
15 kilometres south east of Muswellbrook in the Upper Hunter Valley,
and some 250 kilometres north of Sydney along the New England
Highway.
<P>
The station was completed in 1987 and has a capacity of 2640 megawatts.
There are four steam driven turbo-generators each with a capacity
of 660 megawatts.
<P>
Bayswater produces over a quarter of the state's electricity needs
and burns about six million tonnes of coal annually. Most coal
is mined nearby using &quot;open cut&quot; techniques. A small
amount comes from underground mines.
<P>
A large proportion of the station's coal needs is delivered by
direct conveyor, reducing the need for costly and environmentally
undesirable road haulage.
<P>
Bayswater has a recirculating cooling water system which relies
on four large concrete cooling towers. Apart from the station's
general domestic consumption, water needs are limited to make-up
supplies only. Make-up water is drawn via the Hunter River from
Glenbawn Dam. Supplementary supplies are pumped over the mountains
into Glenbawn Dam from Pacific Power's own water supply system
on the Barnard River to the north.
<H1>LIDDELL</H1>

<P>
Liddell Power Station is also in the Upper Hunter Valley, a few
kilometres north of Bayswater and on the shores of man-made Lake
Liddell. It shares some of the local power production infrastructure
with its neighbour station.
<P>
Liddell was completed in 1973, has four 500 megawatt steam driven
turbo-generators and is also a major contributor to the state's
power network.
<P>
The station uses about 3 million tonnes of coal annually, delivered
mostly from the same sources as Bayswater and mostly via the same
conveyor network.
<P>
Water for cooling is circulated through the station directly from
Lake Liddell. Cooling towers are not required. Make-up water is
also drawn from the Hunter River.
<H1>ERARING</H1>

<P>
Eraring, another coal burning power station, is on the western
side of Lake Macquarie about 15 kilometres south of Toronto and
is, in most respects, a sister station to Bayswater.
<P>
It has the same generating capacity (2640 megawatts) and almost
identical power plant (4 x 660 MW units) to that of its younger
relation. The most noticeable difference is that Eraring has no
cooling towers. Cooling water is circulated through the station
from Lake Macquarie via a canal and tunnel system.
<P>
Eraring Power Station was completed in 1984 and usually burns
well in excess of 5 million tonnes of coal annually, delivered
to a large extent, by direct conveyor or private road from local
underground mines.
<P>
Make-up fresh water supplies are from the Hunter District Water
Board system.
<H1>VALES POINT</H1>

<P>
The first portion of Vales Point Power Station was the forerunner
of New South Wales power stations with conveyor-linked &quot;captive&quot;
coal mines and was originally built in the early sixties.
<P>
The station is on the southern end of Lake Macquarie about 20
kilometres north of Wyong.
<P>
It now has two modern 660 megawatt turbo-generators. These were
the first to be installed in Australia, and are almost the same
as those at Bayswater and Eraring. Installation of these units
was completed in 1979.
<P>
Vales Point is a significant contributor to the New South Wales
power network. It can burn some 2.5 million tonnes of coal annually,
supplied to a large extent from conveyor linked underground mines.
<P>
Cooling water is circulated via a canal from Lake Macquarie. Fresh
water make-up supplies come from the Wyong water supply system.
<H1>MUNMORAH</H1>

<P>
Munmorah Power Station lies just a few kilometres to the east
of Vales Point and was completed in 1969.
<P>
The station was originally built with a capacity of 1400 megawatts,
but in recent years its four 350 megawatt turbo-generators have
been re-rated to 300 MW and two of them put into storage, giving
the station a current operating capacity of 600 megawatts.
<P>
Munmorah can burn up to 1.5 million tonnes of coal annually. This
is mostly conveyor delivered from nearby underground mines. There
is also a coal conveyor interchange facility with Vales Point.
<P>
The station draws its cooling water from a dedicated canal link
between Lake Munmorah on its northern side and Lake Budgewoi to
the south. Make-up fresh water supplies come from the Wyong water
supply system.
<H1>WALLERAWANG</H1>

<P>
Wallerawang Power Station is on the western coalfields about 15
kilometres west from Lithgow along the Mudgee Road.
<P>
It has two 500 megawatt turbo-generators giving the station an
installed capacity of 1000 MW. These two units were commissioned
in 1976 and 1980.
<P>
Wallerawang draws its coal supplies from nearby underground mines.
The station burns up to 2 million tonnes a year which is delivered
by road transport, mostly over a private road.
<P>
Wallerawang, as an inland station, uses cooling towers for its
circulating water cooling system. Make-up water is drawn from
an adjacent dam which in turn is replenished from Lyell Dam, a
major storage area developed by Pacific Power some 16 kilometres
downstream on the Coxs River to serve both Wallerawang and Mount
Piper Power Station (some 10km to the north).
<H1>MT PIPER</H1>

<P>
Mount Piper Power Station is the western coalfields equivalent
of Bayswater and Eraring power stations, though half the capacity
(1320 megawatts) of its sisters. It is on the Mudgee Road about
25 kilometres north west of Lithgow.
<P>
Mount Piper, a coal burning station, has two 660 MW turbo-generators
of the same type as the northern stations. It can burn about 3
million tonnes of coal each year from nearby underground mines.
<P>
The station has two large concrete cooling towers to cool circulating
water. Make-up water will be drawn from Thompsons Creek Dam and
Lyell Dam on the Coxs River.
<P>
Diagram Eight - Cross-section of a coal-fired power station
<H1>HYDRO POWER STATIONS</H1>

<H2>The Snowy Mountains Scheme</H2>

<P>
The Snowy Scheme supplies most of the five or six percent of hydro
electricity used annually by New South Wales and is by far the
biggest single hydro-electric undertaking in Australia.
<P>
Development of the scheme by the Commonwealth government started
soon after World War II and extended over nearly three decades.
It was planned primarily as an irrigation scheme with secondary
hydro-electricity benefits.
<P>
The scheme has a high generating plant capacity (3740 megawatts)
but is operated on a strictly limited basis. Water release through
the power stations is carefully managed to consider irrigation
requirements. New South Wales is entitled to two-thirds of the
electricity produced by the scheme after a small allowance for
Commonwealth Government use. Victoria gets one third.
<P>
There are seven power stations in the Snowy Mountains,
<P>
Tumut 1 (4 x 80 MW units),
<P>
Tumut 2 (4 x 70 MW),
<P>
Murray 1 (10 x 95 MW),
<P>
Murray 2 (4 x 137.5 MW),
<P>
Blowering (1 x 80 MW),
<ADDRESS>
Guthega (2 x 30 MW). 
</ADDRESS>

<P>
Tumut 3 is the biggest with six 250 MW turbo-generators. Three
of these generators can also operate as pumps to send water uphill
in those night periods when low cost electricity is available.
In the day time the water is then used again to generate electricity
avoiding the use of higher cost generators.
<P>
The great advantage of the scheme is that it can supply New South
Wales and Victoria with large amounts of electricity for short
periods of time, vital in coping with emergencies and daily peak
demands.
<P>
A further advantage is that hydro plant can be producing at full
capacity within minutes of start-up. Thermal plant must undergo
a warm-up period of many hours.
<P>
The Snowy Scheme is, thus, an ideal complementary contributor
to the New South Wales supply network.
<P>
Other NSW hydro stations
<P>
Pacific Power has a number of small hydro power stations in its
system, all with the same limitations and advantages as the Snowy
Scheme.
<P>
There are stations at:
<P>
Kangaroo Valley (2 x 80 MW units),
<P>
Warragamba (1 x 50 MW),
<ADDRESS>
Hume, near Albury (2 x 25 MW) shared with Victoria, 
</ADDRESS>

<P>
Burrinjuck (2 x 5 MW),
<ADDRESS>
Keepit, near Gunnedah (1 x 6 MW) and 
</ADDRESS>

<P>
Brown Mountain, near Bega (4 MW).
<P>
Other small privately-owned hydro stations are being developed
in some areas where suitable water resources are available.
<P>
Diagram Nine - Cross-section of a hydro power station
<P>
GAS-TURBINE STATIONS
<P>
Pacific Power also operates a number of small gas-turbine units
as a strategic component of its system. They are at:
<P>
Koolkhan near Grafton (1 x 25 MW, 3 x 23.4 MW),
<P>
Eraring (4 x 25 MW) and
<P>
Liddell (2 x 25 MW).
<P>
National Electricity Statistics
<P>
Australia uses upward of 130 000 gigawatt hours (130 000 million
kilowatt hours) of electrical energy each year to power its industries,
and its commercial, domestic and rural sectors.
<P>
The following graph compares state by state consumption of electricity
and shows the proportion which is produced from coal, water, natural
gas or other basic energy sources (left column of each state group).
The Australian Capital Territory is supplied through the NSW system.
<P>
The adjoining right-hand column for each state group shows the
quantity of black or brown coal burned by the particular state
for electricity generation. Brown coal (Victoria, South Australia)
has a lower heat energy content than black coal, so it takes more
brown coal than black coal to produce a kilowatt hour of electricity.
<P>
Diagram Ten - National Electricity Consumption
