<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Greenhouse Effect</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#6b238e"
ALINK="#00ff00">

<HR>
<H3> UNDERSTANDING THE &quot;GREENHOUSE&quot; PROBLEM</H3>
<HR>

<H4>THE GREENHOUSE EFFECT . . .</H4>

<P>
It is beyond any doubt that:
<UL>
<LI>the concentrations of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere have
increased over recent years and are still increasing.
<LI>the increased concentrations of greenhouse gases will have
some effect on the earth's climate.
</UL>

<P>
. . . WHAT IS IT?
<P>
The earth, and all other bodies in our solar system, are exposed
to radiation from the sun. During the day, this radiation heats
the surface of the planet.
<P>
At all times, but more noticeably during the night, the planet
re-radiates energy back into space and this causes a drop in temperature
on earth.
<P>
Large variations in temperature do not occur because a blanket
of GREENHOUSE GASES mainly trap a lot of this re-radiated energy.
<P>
Without this &quot;Greenhouse Effect&quot; the average temperature
on earth would be about -18 degrees celsius compared with a present
average of +15 degrees celsius and life on earth, as we know it,
would not exist.
<P>
The Greenhouse Effect is essential to our very existence, but
like all things, too much of a good thing is dangerous.
<P>
The concern about the Greenhouse Effect relates to an increase
in the amount of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere which are,
in effect, closing the &quot;window&quot; for the outgoing radiation.
This then causes an increase in the average temperature of the
earth which, in turn, will lead to climatic changes.
<P>
The principal greenhouse gases are:
<MENU>
<LI>Water vapour
<LI>Carbon dioxide
<LI>Methane
<LI>Nitrous oxide
<LI>Chlorofluorocarbons (CFC's)
<LI>Ozone
</MENU>

<P>

<P>
THE CAUSES
<P>
Fundamentally, the increase in each of these greenhouse gases
is caused by an increasing population working towards an increasing
standard of living.
<P>
Fifty years ago the world's population was about 2 billion - now
it is 5 billion. We are living longer and consuming more.
<P>
By the year 2000 the population will probably exceed 8 billion.
<P>
When searching for a solution to the greenhouse problem it is
pertinent to examine the activities of man which contribute to
the problem. They are:
<UL>
<LI>Release of methane and nitrous oxide from agriculture.
<LI>Deforestation.
<LI>Burning of fuel for transport.
<LI>Release of CFC's from refrigerators.
<LI>Urban pollution.
<LI>Burning of coal.
<LI>Burning of gas.
</UL>

<P>
Some of these activities are necessary to support the worlds population
and the quest for an improved standard of living as we know it.
<P>
We should remember that the Greenhouse problem has no geographical
or political boundaries. We all contribute to the problem (although
to differing degrees) and none of us are insulated from its consequences.
<H1>HOW DO WE COMBAT THE PROBLEM?</H1>

<P>
There are fundamentally three choices:
<UL>
<LI>do nothing
<LI>plan to adapt to the likely climate change
<LI>initiate preventative actions to slow the rate of change
</UL>

<P>
The &quot;do nothing option&quot; means, just ignore the problem
and hope that it will go away.
<P>
This option hardly bears consideration.
<P>
The second option &quot;plan to adapt&quot;, has some attraction,
but the question is ADAPT TO WHAT? Despite the lack of precision
in trying to forecast the future climate, wherever the costs are
not excessive, our planning should recognise the likely climate
changes due to the Greenhouse Effect.
<P>
The third option is to initiate reduction or mitigating strategies.
<PRE>
TABLE ONE - Global Greenhouse Gas Contributions from Man's Activities
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Typical Activities 			Greenhouse Gas 		Contribution
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Wet agriculture, ruminants 		Methane 		18%
natural gas, landfills,
coal mines
Oil for transportation, 		Carbon dioxide 		16%
industry
Coal 					Carbon dioxide 		16%
Refrigeration, 				CFC's 			15%
air conditioning
Deforestation 				Carbon dioxide 		12%
Gas 					Carbon dioxide 		 9%
Cultivated soils, combustion 		Nitrous oxides 		 8%
Urban pollution 			Ozone 			 6%
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Sources: CSIRO, 1989 and others
</PRE>

<H1>WHAT MITIGATION MEASURES ARE BEING CONSIDERED?</H1>

<H2>Agriculture</H2>

<P>
Scientists, recognising that domestic animals produce 20% of all
methane, are experimenting with special diets which, it is hoped,
will result in a reduction of methane from this source.
<H2>Deforestation</H2>

<P>
There has been a lot of debate on the contribution of deforestation
to emissions of carbon dioxide and methane, with special attention
to the vast areas of land being cleared in South America.
<H2>Release of CFC's</H2>

<P>
In the 1987 Montreal protocol, the signatory countries, of which
there are now 52, agreed to try to reduce tha amount of CFC's
released into the atmosphere by 50% by the end of the century.
<H2>Burning of Fossil Fuels</H2>

<P>
This area is seen to be the area of human activity most amenable
to change. The reasons for concentrating on the burning of fossil
fuels are:
<UL>
<LI>the burning of fossil fuels represents about 50% of the addition
to the greenhouse effect.
<LI>population pressures will not allow the agricultural sources
to be considered as vigorously.
<LI>fossil fuel use is linked with other environmental problems
eg. acid rain in Europe and North America, and ozone in urban
atmospheres.
<LI>in Australia, 27% of the total energy consumption is associated
with transport of which 77% is for road transport.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
GREENHOUSE AND THE ELECTRICITY INDUSTRY
<H2>Where does Australia fit into this scene?</H2>

<P>
On a per capita basis, Australia is the fifth highest contributor
of carbon dioxide from fossil fuel combustion. 
<P>
However, in terms of total carbon dioxide emissions,our contribution
is very small.
<P>
The whole of Australia contributes 1.3% of the total carbon dioxide
generated world wide. The NSW share
<P>
is 0.4% while the NSW electricity industry contributes 0.2%.
<P>
TABLE TWO - Selected International Carbon dioxide Emissions from
Fossil Fuels
<P>
--------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
Country   Level of Emissions (%)
<P>
--------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
United States of America  24.0
<P>
USSR    19.0
<P>
China     8.7
<P>
Japan     4.7
<P>
W. Germany    3.9
<P>
United Kingdom    2.9
<P>
Canada     2.2
<P>
India     2.1
<P>
Mexico     1.6
<P>
South Africa    1.4
<P>
Australia     1.3
<P>
Netherlands    0.8
<P>
Belgium     0.6
<P>
--------------------------------------------------------------
<H1>ELECTRICITY INDUSTRY MITIGATION ALTERNATIVES</H1>

<P>
Although the contribution of electricity to the overall greenhouse
effect is a small proportion of the total, the industry is actively
looking at ways in which it can reduce this contribution.
<H2>Carbon dioxide Removal</H2>

<P>
Firstly, the carbon dioxide could be removed by planting sufficient
trees to absorb it.
<P>
It would require 2 million hectares of rapidly growing vegetation
(trees) to remove the carbon dioxide generated by the power stations
in NSW. But, once the trees mature they no longer absorb carbon
dioxide and will need to be replaced. But the mature trees can
neither be burned since that will generate carbon dioxide nor
left to rot since, even worse, they will generate methane. They
must either be used for building or alternately buried so the
carbon is locked up.
<P>
Alternatively, it is technically feasible to remove carbon dioxide
from power station exhaust gases, however it is estimated this
would more than double the cost of electricity and create additional
environmental problems.
<H2>Energy Efficiency and Demand Management</H2>

<P>
The amount of carbon dioxide released is directly related to the
amount of electricity generated and so energy efficiency and conservation
are an effective means of reducing the greenhouse effect.
<P>
There are a number of ways that this could be introduced:
<UL>
<LI>Public campaigns
<LI>Electricity pricing strategies
<LI>Promoting energy efficiency at the point of end use
<LI>Promoting energy efficiency in generation and transmission
</UL>

<H2>Higher Efficiency Generating Plant</H2>

<P>
Natural gas-fired turbines produce 30% less carbon dioxide per
kWh than the equivalent coal fired plant and so, from the greenhouse
point of view, there is a definite advantage in using gas turbines
for electricity generation.
<P>
With the use of combined cycle plant, where gas turbine exhaust
gases are used to raise steam for a conventional turbine, the
reduction in carbon dioxide is about 50%.
<H2>Cogeneration</H2>

<P>
The combined production of heat and power by industry can provide
energy efficiencies of 70% to 80% - twice that of coal-fired power
stations.
<H2>Renewable Energies</H2>

<P>
About 5% of the energy sold by Pacific Power comes from renewable
sources - mainly hydro. But the real issue is - can we expand
the use of renewable energy sources and thus reduce our emission
of carbon dioxide?
<P>
Lets look at the various alternatives:
<P>
Hydro - There is a possibility of developing
<P>
around 300MW of additional hydro plant in
<P>
NSW. A number of small hydro projects are
<P>
being pursued. Larger projects have been
<P>
studied but are considered environmentally
<P>
sensitive.
<P>
Wind - This form of generation will have a role to
<P>
play in providing electricity for the NSW
<P>
system in the future.
<P>
Wind turbines of 300kW capacity are considered
<P>
viable for commercial wind farms of 5-10MW.
<P>
Such wind farms in appropriate locations would
<P>
occupy about 3-4 sq. kms of land and provide
<P>
power at about twice the current cost of coal-
<P>
fired power stations.
<P>
Solar - There are presently two methods of generating
<P>
electricity from solar energy:
<UL>
<LI>SOLAR CELLS (photovoltaic) where electricity is generated
from solar energy. The cost of energy from such a system is at
least five times the cost of energy from coal fired stations.
<LI>SOLAR THERMAL CONVERSION where solar energy is used to heat
an intermediate fluid which is then, in turn, used to power a
heat engine. This has been demonstrated in facilities of up to
30MW in California and requires very large areas of land. Alternatively,
solar thermal systems may have greater potential as domestic installations
for hot water and space heating requirements.
</UL>

<P>
Tidal - There is little or no opportunity to utilise
<P>
tidal power in NSW.
<H3>Wave Power -</H3>

<P>
It is unlikely that wave power could be a viable option in NSW.
However, Pacific Power is currently assessing this technology
with a view to carrying out a survey of prospective sites.
<P>
Biomass - Biomass consumption (ie. the burning of wood or
<P>
the conversion of biomass into an intermediate fuel such as ethanol)
is often cited as a means of limiting the emission of carbon dioxide
and may be a viable option in some cases.
<P>
Nuclear - Development of nuclear energy is expensive and
<P>
presently prohibited in NSW by law. Pacific Power is maintaining
a watching brief on nuclear power.
<H3>Methane Drainage -</H3>

<P>
In addition to the methane generated by agricultural pursuits,
methane is also emitted from coal mines and municipal waste dumps.
Electricity generation using this fuel is the focus of a number
of current initiatives in New South Wales.
<H1>PACIFIC POWER INITIATIVES</H1>

<UL>
<LI>studies to measure the level of community awareness about
greenhouse and to assess the cost the community would be prepared
to pay in social and economic terms to reduce the emissions of
greenhouse gases.
<LI>scenario planning to analyse the consequences and our possible
responses to limits being placed on carbon dioxide, either by
way of taxes or by legislation.
<LI>provision of speakers to explain the &quot;greenhouse effect&quot;
and to listen to the opinions of customers and the general public.
<LI>sponsorship of research into climate modelling and other greenhouse
issues.
<LI>studies of wave energy resources in New South Wales
<LI>support for research into solar energy
<LI>support for research into electric vehicles and mobile batteries
<LI>planning for the development of gas turbine and combined cycle
plant
<LI>encouragement of end use efficiency
<LI>ongoing planting of large numbers of trees around its establishments.
Nearly a half-million were planted in the eighties.
<LI>studies of likely sites for wind farms with the object of
developing such farms where they can be shown to be economically
justified.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
For further information contact:
<P>
Pacific Power Community Relations
<P>
GPO Box 5257
<P>
Sydney NSW 2001
<P>
ph: (02) 268 6800
<P></P>
