<H2>CHAPTER 2</H2>

<H3>NEW TECHNOLOGIES IN POWER GENERATION </H3>

<H4>Non-Renewables</H4>

<H5>Introduction</H5>

<P>
Developments in power station technology in the past have focused
mainly on improving the overall economics of the industry. This
on the one hand has led to an increase in the size of power station
machines in order to reduce the specific cost of construction
and operation per unit energy produced. Coal-fired power stations,
which play the most important role in the generation of electricity
in most industrialised countries, commonly operate with outputs
of around 500-800 MW(e) per machine of which multiples of 2, 4
or 6 are most often constructed. On the other hand, it is increasingly
important to maintain generating capacity whilst reducing the
amount of fuel being consumed through efficiency measures.
<P>
The efficiency of large coal-fired steam cycle power stations
with an output of 660 MW(e) is now 35-37% (HHV higher heating
valve). Reaching 38% or even 40%, the most recent power stations
are now approaching the limit in both technical and economic terms.
The steam driving the turbine in this case has a temperature of
about 540 degrees Celsius, and pressure of around 16 MPa. Any
further increase in temperature or pressure would improve efficiency
only slightly but would result in a disproportionate increase
in costs to build such facilities.
<P>
In the following sections, new and alternative technologies which
utilise 'non-renewable' energy sources are discussed. Development
of all of these technologies are well under way worldwide, with
many technologies already seeing commercial returns. The high
efficiency of these new processes is one of the major driving
forces in their development and with efficiencies of greater than
50% expected, as well as excellent environmental control, more
and more of these installations are finding application in today's
energy markets.
<MENU>
<LI>2.1 Fluidised Bed Combustors (FBC)
<LI>2.1.1 Introduction
<LI>Fluidised bed combustion is a technology developed for the
combustion of a wide range of variable quality fuels and wastes.
The fluidised bed can be fuelled with low quality coals through
to washery wastes and sewage sludge, wastes from municipal dumps
and even used scrap tyres. Materials which have typically been
viewed only as wastes, in the past, and for which large disposal
projects have been implemented, may in the near future be providing
us with a cheap, useful source of energy for conversion to electricity.
<LI>The fluidised bed, Figure 2.1, is essentially a holding vessel
containing a mixture of predominantly inert material. The composition
of material in the bed can consist of up to 99% non-combustible
material, mainly ash and limestone, the limestone providing an
important advantage in pollution control. The 'mixed' bed is supported
by a uniformly perforated base plate through which air is supplied
for two main purposes:
</MENU>

<P>
. as a source of oxygen for combustion in the bed;
<P>
. as the fluidizing agent by effectively lifting the
<P>
bed at a minimum air velocity (known as the
<P>
fluidizing velocity) and hence thoroughly mixing the
<P>
fuel and inert materials as though they were fluids. This
<P>
provides intimate contact of fuel and oxygen and ensures
<P>
efficient combustion.
<P>
A bed consists of about 1% coal (up to a maximum of 3%) and 99%
glowing ash and additives. Even when the fuel used is of very
inferior quality, this large volume of red-hot material (reaching
temperatures of up to 850 degrees Celsius) ensures stable and
uniform ignition for as long as fluidised air is supplied to the
unit. Yet another benefit is that fluidised bed combustors do
not involve any slag formation even when high-ash coal is being
burnt, since the ash components neither melt nor sinter in the
relatively low temperatures prevailing in the bed. This is particularly
important where the ash fusion temperature is relatively low and
if used in conventional combustion systems would cause 'slagging'
and 'fouling' of boiler tubes in the higher temperature furnace.
<P>
Although the fluidised bed can utilise a broad range of fuel types,
this is not the only benefit to be gained from implementing this
technology for power generation. The environmental benefits of
a fluidised bed combustor are also significant.
<P>
Environmentally a fluidised bed combustor allows the operator
to maintain levels of atmospheric pollutants, sulphur dioxide
and oxides of nitrogen at low levels well within emission limits.
When fuel to be combusted, by nature, contains impurities which
will produce these pollutants in conventional combustion systems,
fluidised bed combustion can be employed as an alternative to
avoid:
<P>
. the high cost of installing additional, special
<P>
equipment for their removal;
<P>
. the cost associated with a reduction in overall
<P>
plant efficiency normally associated with pollution
<P>
control systems; and
<P>
. overall, a more complicated process.
<P>
This in turn should reduce the overall cost of the electricity
produced and hence the cost being passed onto consumers.
<P>
Removal of sulphur originating in the fuel which would otherwise
be oxidised to sulphur dioxide, is achieved by the addition of
limestone to the bed. As the bed operates at temperatures in the
region of 700-850 degrees Celsius, limestone ensures optimum binding
of the sulphur present. More than 95% of sulphur is removed in
this way.
<P>
Combustion temperatures of less than 850 degrees Celsius in the
bed also aids in reducing the amount of oxides of nitrogen formation
to lower levels. Conventional coal fired power stations operate
with temperatures typically in the range 1400-1500 degrees Celsius.
In this temperature range oxides of nitrogen is readily formed
from organic nitrogen within the coal as well as atmospheric nitrogen,
and hence methods must be employed for its control e.g. 'low oxides
of nitrogen' burners. The oxides of nitrogen level from a fluidised
bed combustor is typically reduced by 75% below that of an equivalent
size pulverised coal-fired boiler.
<P>
Figure 2.1 - Fluidised Bed Combustor (FBC)
<MENU>
<LI>2.1.2 Atmospheric Fluidised Bed Combustor (AFBC)
<LI>The most basic design of the fluidised bed is known as the
atmospheric fluidised bed. Heat is transferred from the fuel combustion
to steam tubes submerged within the bed as well as in the flue
gas pass. Because of the intimate contact between the tubes and
the bed, heat transfer is up to five times greater than that which
occurs with the exiting flue gas. The steam generated in the tubes
is then used to drive a steam turbine and generator for the production
of electricity. Typically these facilities can be constructed
up to 60 MW(e) in size.
<LI>The minimum velocity of fluidising air (this also being the
combustion air) is of the order of 0.8-1.0 m/s with the maximum
being about 3 m/s. At low load, the bed is designed such that
steam tubes become exposed (ie. the bed shrinks) and heat transfer
from the bed is reduced. At high load, high velocity, the bed
increases in height hence covering the tubes and increasing steam
production. If the bed is completely shut down, steam tubes are
fully exposed and the combustion is smothered. In this situation,
the mass of the bed retains its heat for several hours allowing
easy start up when desired.
<LI>The state of the art today is a further development of the
atmospheric fluidised bed to a circulating process in order to
improve the efficiency of combustion and reduce gaseous emissions.
<LI>2.1.3 Circulating Fluidised Bed Combustor (CFBC)
<LI>In the circulating fluidised bed the flue gas moves at speeds
of 5-8 m/s carrying with it tons of silica sand, lime and ash
up the roughly 40 m high combustion chamber, together with the
coal (or whichever fuel is being employed). This material which
is carried along with the gas stream is separated in a cyclone.
Inside the cyclone the gas is forced into a swirling motion, throwing
solid particles to the outside walls of the cone shaped collection
unit. The solids are delivered to a hopper to be returned to the
combustion chamber. The recirculation of fly ash has a positive
influence on the process by improving overall combustion efficiency
(over 99% carbon burnout for all fuels), better utilisation of
the limestone in absorbing sulphur dioxide and by cooling the
fluidised bed by up to 50 degrees Celsius. Reducing the temperature
by this amount helps to maintain optimum sulphur removal.
<LI>The operation of a fluidised bed with circulation reduces
sulphur dioxide and oxides of nitrogen emissions even further
when compared to atmospheric fluidised beds. The rigorous circulation
in the bed promotes intimate contact of sulphur compounds with
limestone. This ensures high retention of sulphur irrespective
of the quality of fuel. Typical gas temperatures of 850 degrees
Celsius as well as 'staged' combustion maintains oxides of nitrogen
levels within acceptable limits. It also avoids the need to install
steam tubes inside the fluidised bed (these tubes accept heat
predominantly by conduction), since convectional heat transfer
is increased by the high volume of combustion products flowing
through the back pass of the boiler. In-bed tubes in the atmospheric
bed are subject to substantial erosion.
<LI>The circulating fluidised bed process was developed by a European
engineering company - Lurgi. The first industrial application
of their technology using coal, being in Luenen, West Germany
in 1982. This particular facility has a thermal capacity of 84
MW, burning coal washery wastes with a moisture content of up
to 65% and a sulphur content of 2%. The plant generates process
steam as well as electric power for a nearby aluminium oxide plant.
Other circulating fluidised bed installations include 67 MW electrical
with a simultaneous 138 MW of steam for district heating at Duisburg,
West Germany, 39 MW electrical and 109 MW of steam for district
heating at Flensburg, West Germany, as well as numerous demonstration
facilities, and plants under construction.
<LI>Circulating fluidised beds should be able, in the near future
to provide an electricity output of up to 200 MW(e). Part loads
down to 30% of the rated capacity can be catered for with a load
changing capability of 5% per minute.
<LI>Inherent disadvantages of the circulating fluidised bed technology
include the high auxiliary power requirement for the circulation
of bed material, as well as, erosion problems from ash carried
along in the flue gas. In this technology these disadvantages
are more pronounced than the other fluidised bed technologies.
<LI>Integration of the atmospheric bed technology with that of
the 'circulating' bed, has led to the development of the so-called
'circofluid' technology. This new development will combine the
advantages of the atmospheric bed, such as short start-up and
shut down times, low auxiliary power requirement and low investment
with the advantages of the 'circulating' bed which include, high
combustion efficiency, as well as reduced sulphur dioxide and
oxides of nitrogen emissions.
<LI>Figure 2.2 - Circulating Fluidised Bed Combustors (CFBC).
<LI>2.1.4 Pressurised Fluidised Bed Combustors (PFBC)
<LI>Pressurised fluidised beds operating at pressures of between
1 and 3 MPa are currently being tested in demonstration facilities
of a commercial scale. Given their greater energy density resulting
from operation at elevated pressure and with a greater mass flow
of combustion air, they have the potential to reach sizes of up
to 300 MW(e) and physically still be substantially smaller than
similar atmospheric fluidised bed combustors and circulating fluidised
bed installations. The pressurised fluidised bed as with the other
fluidised bed combustion technologies is capable of using a wide
variety of fuel types including those with low heating values
in an environmentally acceptable manner. Efficiency of these facilities,
however, is significantly higher between 40 and 45% (HHV) due
to the combined use of gas turbine technology and heat recovery
systems.
<LI>With conventional power generation facilities now reaching
a plateau in terms of efficiency improvements, combined gas/steam
cycles offer the potential to once again significantly increase
power generation efficiencies. The pressure energy of the fluidised
bed exhaust gases is recovered (after being cleaned of entrained
ash particles), in a gas turbine before heat recovery and exhaust
to atmosphere. It is important to ensure the gas is sufficiently
clean so as not to damage the gas turbine blades through erosion.
The gas turbine compressor supplies compressed air for combustion
in the high pressure fluidised bed. The generation of electricity
is therefore possible from both the gas turbine generator and
a conventional steam turbine and generator. Approximately 20%
of the electricity generated is provided by the gas turbine whilst
the remaining 80% is generated by the steam cycle. This combination
provides an increase of over 10% above the overall efficiency
of conventional coal-fired plant which does not utilise a gas
turbine.
<LI>Three commercial pressurised fluidised bed combustion installations
have recently been completed in Spain, Sweden and USA. One of
these plants located in Stockholm, Sweden and conceived as a twin
plant, generates 135 MW of electricity and 220 MW of district
heating. Fluidised bed combustion power stations have been extensively
developed worldwide and are now finding significant application
in energy markets. They have a claimed efficiency of 40-45% and
represent an investment 10-15% lower than a conventional power
station with complete flue gas purification, as they do not require
the related purification facilities of modern pulverised coal
power stations in Europe and the USA. Pressurised fluidised beds
have a predicted output in the intermediate range of 200-350 MW(e).
<LI>Figure 2.3 - PFBC Combined Cycle.
<LI>2.2 Gas Turbines and Combined Cycle
<LI>Gas turbines have been used for electricity generation for
many years. In the past, their use has been generally limited
to generating electricity in periods of peak electricity demand.
Gas turbines are ideal for this application as they can be started
and stopped quickly enabling them to be brought into service as
required to meet energy demand peaks. However, their previously
small unit sizes and their low thermal efficiency restricted the
opportunities for their wider use for electricity generation.
<LI>Over the last ten years there has been major improvements
to gas turbines such that they are now considered an attractive
option for base load electricity generation. Advances in gas turbine
technology have resulted in the efficiency of gas turbines being
increased to that of coal-fired power stations with much larger
machines being manufactured. Further, combined cycle plants (these
use the waste heat from the gas turbine exhaust to generate steam
to drive a steam turbine and so produce additional electricity)
have one of the highest efficiency ratings of non-renewable generating
plant currently available 40 to 45% HHV. The same technology improvements
have also resulted in the output capacity of gas turbines being
doubled. The largest units in service today produce 150 MW(e)
while units of around 200 MW(e) are scheduled to enter service
in 1993.
<LI>Figure 2.4 - Combined Cycle.
<MENU>
<LI>2.2.1 Operation
</MENU>

<LI>Gas turbines are internal combustion engines. The operating
principle is identical to conventional reciprocating petrol engines:
air is compressed, fuel burnt, and the expanding hot gas drives
the engine. However, instead of pistons compressing the air and
the hot expanding gases driving the piston, rotating compressor
blades (like a fan) compress the air and the resulting hot combustion
gases drive the turbine blades to produce power. A combustion
chamber is positioned between the air compressor and the power
turbine. Fuel is injected on a continuous basis into this chamber
and burnt. The continuous combustion of fuel enables more power
to be produced compared to a reciprocating engine of similar weight
and size.
<LI>Figure 2.5 - Simple Cycle Gas Turbine.
<LI>For electricity generation, the output shaft of the gas turbine
is connected to an electrical generator, identical to those driven
by steam turbines in coal fired plant.
<LI>Industrial gas turbines convert approximately 31% (HHV), of
the energy contained in the fuel to electrical energy. The remaining
energy is contained in the exhaust gases or used by auxiliary
equipment. By directing the exhaust gases through a heat recovery
boiler, steam is produced which can be used to drive a steam turbine
and generator set. This is the principle of combined cycle plant.
<LI>2.2.2 Aeroderivative &amp; Industrial Gas Turbines
<LI>There are two basic types of gas turbines - aeroderivative
and industrial units. As their name suggests, aeroderivative units
are aircraft jet engines modified to drive electrical generators.
These units have a maximum output of 40 MW(e) and are more fuel
efficient than industrial units. The latest aeroderivative unit
has a thermal efficiency of 36%. Aeroderivative units can produce
full power within three minutes after start up.
<LI>Industrial gas turbines range in sizes up to 150 MW(e). The
major gas turbine companies are just commencing to manufacture
units of around 200 MW(e). One company has a 218 MW(e) unit schedule
for operation in 1993. The most efficient industrial units have
efficiencies of around 31%. Depending on size, start up can take
from 10 to 40 minutes to produce full output.
<LI>Industrial gas turbines have a lower capital cost per kilowatt
installed than aeroderivative units. For this reason, it would
be most likely for Pacific Power to use industrial units if gas
turbines were selected as a generating option. Combined cycle
plant would also probably be based on industrial units as the
larger gas turbine capacities enable the use of larger steam plant
components which have significant cost advantages due to 'economies
of scale'.
</MENU>

<H5>Fuels</H5>

<P>
Gas turbines are capable of burning a wide variety of fuels. Distillate
and natural gas are the most common fuels as they do not contain
impurities which could damage the components in the turbine that
operate at high temperature. Crude oil and heavy fuel oils can
be burnt, but additional fuel treatment plant is necessary. When
natural gas is used, power output and thermal efficiency of gas
turbines are higher than when using distillate.
<P>
Gas turbines that operate at low capacity factors (referring to
the extent to which they are utilised) can be operated economically
on distillate. Base load combined cycle plant, however, needs
to be fuelled on natural gas for it to be competitive with alternative
coal based generating plants.
<H5>Environment</H5>

<P>
Natural gas contains only trace levels of sulphur, so sulphur
dioxide emissions are virtually non-existent when natural gas
is burnt. With distillate, the levels of sulphur dioxide in the
exhaust gas are low due to the very low levels of sulphur in the
distillate. Nitrogen oxides generation can be minimised by the
design of the combustion process. With natural gas, extremely
low levels of nitrogen oxides are achievable from burner design
alone. With distillate, nitrogen oxides generation is easily controlled
by the injection of water or steam into the combustion chamber.
<P>
Gas turbines and combined cycles are very compact and occupy small
ground area. Noise from the gas turbines needs to be considered,
but statutory limits on noise levels at site boundaries can be
achieved either by increasing the distance from the boundary to
the plant or by installing noise abatement equipment on the machines.
<H5>Potential Use of Gas Turbines for Pacific Power</H5>

<P>
Forecasts of future generating plant requirements indicate gas
turbines are an important option when considering the next generation
increment in NSW after the new coal fired Mount Piper Power Station
commences generating electricity in 1993. These gas turbines would
operate at low capacity factors, that is below 10% of the time.
The role of these machines would be to provide 'back-up' supply
for base load coal fired units that are forced out of service
due to plant failure. Gas turbines are suited to this role because
of their low capital cost around $410/kW compared to $1100/kW
for coal plant.
<P>
The lead time for gas turbine installation can be as short as
two years provided development approval is obtained in advance.
This short lead time would enable gas turbines to be installed
quickly should the electricity supply system require additional
unforeseen capacity. Combined cycle plant has a short lead time,
three years provided development approval is obtained in advance.
Combined cycle plant costs around $850/kW and retains this cost
for small generating increments as low as 400 MW(e).
<MENU>
<LI>2.2.3 Technological Developments
<LI>Over the last ten years there have been many advancements
in gas turbine technology. New materials and techniques used to
manufacture the turbine blades have resulted in a significant
increase in operating temperatures which leads to a corresponding
increase in efficiency. Turbine blades are manufactured with passages
inside the blades that allow air to pass through the blades to
keep them cool. This cooling air is provided by the compressor
section of the gas turbine. Further increases in turbine operating
temperatures are possible by pre-cooling the air after it leaves
the compressor.
<LI>Ceramic blades offer the possibility of higher operating temperatures
and increased efficiencies.
<LI>Currently, turbine blades are made from exotic alloys that
retain their strength at the high temperatures experienced in
the turbine. However, at these high operating temperatures, impurities
in the fuel (even at extremely low levels) can cause corrosion
of the blades. Various coatings for turbine blades have been developed
to avoid this high temperature corrosion.
<LI>2.3 Coal Gasification
<LI>2.3.1 Gasification Processes
<LI>In the early 1970's, as a result of the increasing fuel cost
and uncertainty of future fuel supply, research was begun on the
gasification of coal. Coal gasification was investigated as an
alternative to natural gas. Compared with direct coal firing of
power stations, the advantage of gasification is in the production
of a purified gas for which there is no subsequent need for flue
gas cleaning equipment, particularly for removal of sulphur dioxide.
Accordingly, the volume of gas to be cleaned is reduced to about
one hundredth of the equivalent flue gas volume. The integration
of gasification with the combined cycle process (referred to as
integrated gasification combined cycle) which yields higher efficiencies
than coal-fired and simple cycle power generation (combined cycle
refers to steam production utilising the waste heat from exhaust
gases) more than compensates for the loss in efficiency in coal
gasification brought about by partial oxidation of the gas and
incomplete gasification of the coal. The raw gas produced in the
gasification process contains mainly carbon monoxide and hydrogen
with small amounts of methane, hydrogen sulphide, tars, oils and
particulates. Ash or slag is removed from the bottom of the gasifier.
<LI>To generate the gas, coal is heated to temperatures typically
between 800 and 1600 degrees Celsius, oxygen and steam being added
at the same time. This produces a gas made up primarily of hydrogen
and carbon monoxide. Low-temperature processes (up to about 900
degrees Celsius) also generate methane and carbon dioxide. The
gas produced in this process has to be cooled and cleaned before
use. The heat inside the gasifier, the crude gas, and the slag
provides the energy for generating steam to drive a steam turbine
and generator set.
</MENU>

<H5>Types of Coal Gasification</H5>

<P>
The three main gasification methods are described below, and are
shown in Figure 2.6.
<P>
Figure 2.6 - Basic Types of Coal Gasification Processes.
<P>
Fixed Bed - In the &quot;fixed bed&quot; system, coal (3-30 mm)
is distributed onto a rotary grate at the base of the gasifier,
where the oxygen or air and steam are introduced. Ash is removed
from the rotary grate and passes through the ash lock under the
gasifier. The temperature in the gasifier must be kept below the
ash melting point to avoid slag formation. This form of gasifier
has a gas exit temperature in the order of 800 degrees Celsius,
and a pressure of 1 - 10 MPa. The low gas exit temperature in
this gasifier reflects the fact that as much as 90% of the coal's
energy remains as chemical energy in the gas.
<P>
Fluidised Bed - In this process, the coal (1-5 mm) is fed into
a 'fluidised' bed consisting of inert material and coal. Oxygen
or air for combustion, nitrogen to carry the fuel, and steam are
introduced through nozzles in the bed, thus fluidising the coal.
Gasification of the coal occurs in the bed, however further oxygen
or air, nitrogen and steam are added above the bed, increasing
the temperature and facilitating the conversion of coal and preventing
by product formation. Ash is removed from the bottom of the gasifier,
typically by a cooled screw conveyor.
<P>
Fluidised bed gasifiers work best with coals with an ash melting
point higher than 1100 - 1200 degrees Celsius, low coking tendency
and high reactivity. Wood and peat can also be used. This form
of gasifier has a gas exit temperature in the order of 1000 degrees
Celsius, and a pressure of 1 - 2.5 MPa. The moderate gas exit
temperature in this gasifier reflects the fact that 80% of the
coal's energy remains as chemical energy in the gas.
<P>
Entrained Flow - The fuel mix is introduced into the entrained
flow
<P>
gasifier through burner nozzles, and the gasification occurs as
the
<P>
fuel flows through the gasifier. The coal is introduced with a
<P>
particle size of 0.1 mm. This type of gasifier operates at a
<P>
temperature higher than the ash melting point, which enables the
ash
<P>
(slag) to flow out of the gasifier. The resulting gas has negligible
<P>
tar, oil, or phenol content. This form of gasifier has a gas exit
<P>
temperature in the order of 1400 degrees Celsius, and a pressure
of
<MENU>
<LI>2.5 - 4 MPa. The high gas exit temperature in this gasifier
reflects the fact that only 70% of the coal's energy remains as
chemical energy in the gas.
<LI>Processes currently being developed now operate at higher
pressures. The advantage is an increase in power output as well
as a reduction of the investment required for both the gasifier
and the subsequent processing of the product gas.
<LI>A variant now proposed is to operate with partial gasification
of coal; only 70% of the coal is transformed into gas, the rest
is left over as coke. The advantage is that this procedure does
not require pure oxygen that would have to be generated at high
cost; rather, air is quite sufficient. The exhaust heat produced
by such partial gasification serves together with the combustion
of the coke to generate steam. The hot exhaust gases from the
gas turbine still contain enough oxygen to be added to the coke
burning.
<LI>2.3.2 Integrated Gasification Combined Cycle (IGCC)
</MENU>

<H5>General Process Description</H5>

<P>
Basically IGCC is a combined cycle process (gas turbine/heat recovery
boiler) fuelled by gasified coal. This system takes advantage
of the abundance of coal and the high efficiency of the combined
cycle.
<P>
Gas Purification - After the coal is gasified, the fuel gas produced
passes through a heat recovery boiler which generates steam to
drive a steam turbine and generator. The dust in the cool fuel
gas is removed by wet scrubbing prior to sulphur compounds being
removed. About 2 to 5% of the fuel gas energy is lost in this
process. Hot gas cleaning methods are being researched, so that
gas cooling can be avoided and plant can operate at higher efficiency.
<P>
Combustion - The cleaned gas is mixed with compressed air, nitrogen
(from the air separation plant, if one exists) and/or steam, and
combusted in a gas turbine combustion chamber. The resulting hot
gas is passed through the gas turbine. The generator coupled to
the turbine produces electrical power. The nitrogen and steam
have a cooling effect on the process by diluting and controlling
combustion, hence decreasing the rate of oxides of nitrogen production.
<P>
Waste Heat Boiler - Heat remaining in the gas turbine exhaust
is retrieved by a waste heat boiler. This heat generates steam
which drives the steam turbine/generator.
<P>
Air Separation Plant - Processes which use oxygen rather than
air for gasification, require process plant for air separation.
The gas turbine's compressor provides air for the air separation
plant, where the oxygen and nitrogen are separated. The oxygen
is supplied to the gasifier, while the nitrogen is supplied to
the gas turbine combustion chamber and is also used to carry coal
into to the gasifier.
<P>
Coal Feed - Coal is introduced to the gasifier in a number of
ways, including screw feeds, blown pulverised coal and as a water
slurry. Slurry fed gasifiers use more heat to evaporate the water
and they also have a greater oxygen requirement.
<H5>Plant Capacity/Staged Construction</H5>

<P>
Although gasifiers have not reached sizes comparable to conventional
coal plant, a 250 MW(e) unit is under construction at Buggenum
in the Netherlands. One major advantage of IGCC is that its construction
can be staged. Initially a gas turbine can be commissioned (and
run on natural gas), then the heat recovery boiler (completing
the combined cycle, fuelled by natural gas) and finally the gasifier
to fuel the combined cycle with gasified coal.
<H5>Water Consumption</H5>

<P>
Based on a generation capacity of 600 MW(e) the table below shows
expected water requirements for cooling purposes of a gasification
process compared with conventional coal and combined cycle power
plant.
<H5>Figure 2.7 - Water Consumption</H5>

<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
Gasification Conventional Combined
<P>
Pulverised Cycle
<P>
Coal
<MENU>
<LI>Water 675t/h 915t/h 565t/h
<LI>Consumption
</MENU>

<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<H5>Developments</H5>

<P>
The main thrust of IGCC development is to build plant of comparable
capital cost to pulverised coal plant but achieve higher efficiencies.
It is claimed that existing IGCC systems have a similar capital
cost to pulverised coal systems fitted with flue gas desulphurisation.
Designed to achieve up to 43% efficiency (HHV) it is expected
to reach 45% (HHV) in the event that development of hot gas cleaning
technology is a success.
<P>
Apart from a number of pilot units, one large demonstration power
station with integrated coal gasification has been built so far:
the 100 MW(e) Southern California Edison power station in Cool
Water, USA operated successfully between 1984 and 1989 and has
been acknowledged as one of the cleanest coal based power stations
in the USA. Buggenum in the Netherlands, rated at 250 MW(e) will
be commissioned in 1993 and is designed to operate with an efficiency
of 41.4% (HHV).
<P>
Figure 2.8 - Integrated Gasification Combined Cycle.
<P>
2.4 Fuel Cells
<P>
The fuel cell operates by directly converting the chemical energy
in a fuel to electrical energy through an electrochemical process.
It consists of two electrodes separated by an electrolyte (fluid
capable of conducting an electric current) and electrically connected
through an external circuit.
<P>
Figure 2.9 - Fuel Cell.
<P>
Fuel cells offer considerable benefits as a future power source
due to high efficiencies in the range of 50-60% as well as quiet
and versatile operation. They are predicted to be serious contenders
for both central power stations and dispersed power generation
at load centres. Suitable fuels include methanol, natural gas
and gasified coal.
<P>
A fuel is supplied continuously to one electrode, where it is
oxidised, (i.e. burnt) and an oxidant (air) is supplied at the
other electrode where it is reduced. The electrolyte enables flow
of ions between the two electrodes. Fuel cell types are generally
classified by the type of electrolyte used.
<MENU>
<LI>(i) Phosphoric Acid Fuel Cells (PAFC) - these are currently
the most developed and field tested fuel cell systems to date.
A 4.5 MW(e) and an 11 MW(e) demonstration plant have been successfully
operated. The temperature of operation of the cell is about 200
degrees Celsius and waste heat recovery can be used for low temperature
applications. These low temperature fuel cells generally use hydrogen
as the fuel source.
<LI>(ii) Molten Carbonate Fuel Cells (MCFC) - these are less developed
than the phosphoric acid fuel cells. They operate at about 650
degrees Celsius with an efficiency of 55-60%, and the potential
to recover the waste heat generated for combined cycle operation.
Natural gas can be reacted directly in such a facility because
of the high temperature of operation. The development of MCFC
is at an advanced stage but several serious material problems
relating to degradation and stability of cell components still
needs to be investigated and resolved.
<LI>(iii) Solid Oxide Fuel Cells (SOFC) - these use ceramic electrolytes
based on zirconia, and operate at about 1000 degrees Celsius.
Experimental SOFCs have been demonstrated, and industry experts
predict megawatt size installations with energy densities of 1
MW/m3 and operation at 50-60% efficiency within a decade. Because
of the high temperature of operation they will be suited for combined
cycle operation where the unreacted fuel leaving the fuel cell
is augmented and combusted in a gas turbine. As the temperature
of exhaust gases is of the order of 500 to 900 degrees Celsius,
the waste heat can be used to generate steam. It is expected that
such an arrangement could achieve an overall efficiency of close
to 80% with waste heat recovery.
<LI>A marketing report prepared for the CSIRO indicates that SOFC's
would be particularly attractive for meeting the energy needs
of non-residential buildings. In this application natural gas
fuelled units of between 100 kW(e) and a few megawatts, would
reduce carbon dioxide emissions significantly and be viable where
capital cost is less than $2000/kW inclusive of all power conditioning
equipment.
<LI>Some of the inherent advantages of operating fuel cells as
power supplies includes their flexibility in utilising a wide
variety of fuel sources (gasified coal, oil, gas, hydrogen, methanol),
their silent operating characteristics particularly attractive
in building installations, their modular construction allowing
cost effective increases in capacity and the potentially high
efficiency in the conversion of chemical energy into electricity.
<LI>Pacific Power has recently joined a consortium which established
a new joint-venture company, Ceramic Fuel Cells Ltd. to develop
SOFC's. The ultimate objective is the development of the technology
for application to large central and dispersed power stations
for use within grids.
<LI>2.5 Magnetohydrodynamics
<LI>Magnetohydrodynamic (MHD) energy conversion is a process where
heat can be converted directly into electricity. The basic principle
by which electricity is generated is by moving a conductor through
a magnetic field. Thus, in the case of a conventional electricity
generator, using a turbogenerator, a coil of conductor is rotated
in a stationary magnetic field, or a magnetic field is rotated
in a cage of stationary conductors, namely copper or aluminium
bars.
<LI>Figure 2.10 - Open Cycle MHD Plant.
<LI>In the MHD generator, the combustion gas itself is an electrical
conductor. The gas is usually derived from the high temperature
combustion of coal. The combustion products produced are so hot
that they become electrically conducting, ie. a plasma. The ability
of the gas to conduct electricity is increased by &quot;seeding&quot;
it with a salt of readily ionisable alkali metal such as potassium
or caesium. This hot gas expands at high velocity through an intense
magnetic field via a long, narrow, divergent channel or nozzle.
An electric potential is induced between two opposite walls of
the generator and electric power can be extracted.
<LI>In both cases (conventional and MHD generators) the motion
of a conductor through a magnetic field gives rise to an electromotive
force and a flow of current in accordance with Faraday's laws
of induction. In a conventional generator, the current is carried
to the external load circuit through brushes. In the MHD generator
electrodes mounted in the channel walls tap off the current directly.
Thus for MHD, the energy released by the expanding hot gases is
converted directly to electricity without the use of rotating
machinery hence reducing mechanical losses.
<LI>When a conductor is placed in a magnetic field and a current
passed through it perpendicular to the field, a voltage is set
up perpendicular to both the field and current directions. This
phenomenon is known as the Hall effect, and the transverse voltage
developed is called the Hall voltage.
<LI>If a continuous electrode were used along the wall of a linear
MHD generator, Hall current would flow in the plasma, seriously
degrading performance. For this reason electrodes are segmented,
ie. there are a large number of electrodes separated by insulators
along the channel. With segmentation a voltage can develop between
adjacent electrodes because of the Hall effect.
<LI>The flue gas from the MHD process can be directed to a waste
heat boiler for steam raising or be passed to a gas turbine for
direct electricity generation. In both cases the efficiency of
the overall process can be significantly enhanced recovering energy
which would otherwise be exhausted to atmosphere.
<LI>An alternative to the linear MHD system described has been
developed as a result of technical problems associated with linear
systems on a commercial scale. Known as MHD disk generators they
avoid problems of the linear type such as superconducting magnets
of commercial scale are complex, expensive and of a size which
would make transport to site a difficult task. Cooling systems
as well as power consolidation systems and inverter system are
also less complex and expensive.
<LI>The MHD - disk generator has an overall simpler construction
than the linear system and benefits from less components under
high electrical potential and unbroken plasma flow.
<LI>By installing an MHD generator as a topping plant (installed
upstream of a secondary process which can also generate electricity),
overall efficiencies of up to 45% may be achievable with established
technology, reaching 50-55% with second generation development
and triple cycle configuration. Triple cycle refers to combined
MHD/gas turbine/steam plant. Size of MHD plant when used as a
topping cycle is in the range 25 MW(e) to 1000 MW(e).
<LI>Pacific Power has recently sponsored research at the University
of Sydney into a design study for retrofitting of MHD technology
at an existing power station.
<LI>2.6 Ultra Clean Coal (UCC)
<LI>Coal, in its natural form consists of carbon, hydrogen and
oxygen with traces of contaminants bound into the atomic structure,
as well as inert material known generally as ash. Because coal
typically contains from 10 to 30% ash by weight, its use as a
fuel is restricted to more conventional, coal-fired boilers. If
the inert material or ash content can be removed from the coal
such that less than 0.5% of ash remains, a new class of fuel,
ultra clean coal, can be produced and considered for a variety
of other uses, in particular as a replacement for liquid petroleum
fuels.
</MENU>

<H5>The Process</H5>

<P>
Physical processes for the removal of ash from coal have been
developed over the years to improve its quality for combustion
in conventional processes. In order to remove a high percentage
of ash from the coal by physical methods, large expensive and
cumbersome industrial plants need to be constructed.
<P>
A process for the chemical cleaning of coal, pioneered by the
CSIRO, is currently under development in Australia.
<P>
Figure 2.11 - Ultra Clean Coal Technology.
<P>
It is expected that this process will reduce the ash in coal to
less than 0.5% at a competitive cost and hence broaden the technologies
for which coal would be a substitute fuel.
<P>
The chemical cleaning process, which is currently under development
involves a number of distinct processing stages. Generally these
stages can be described as: caustic digestion of the mineral matter,
followed by acid neutralisation and finally water washing. The
reagents which are used throughout the process can be regenerated
for re-use in the process. Whilst being environmentally sound
and avoiding problems with waste disposal of chemicals this also
reduces the cost of the overall process and hence the finished
product.
<P>
The commercial success of the process for producing UCC will see
some very distinct benefits particularly in the area of electricity
generation. Some of these benefits include:
<P>
. increased export earnings through shipping a more versatile
fuel
<P>
to other countries resulting in their reduced dependence on gas
<P>
and petroleum products in electricity generation
<P>
. reduced transport and shipping costs for a fuel which can be
up to 30% lighter than raw coal from the mine;
<P>
. the ability to transport UCC through pipelines as a preference
to coal moved by rail or road transport. This being cheaper, less
congestive to our roads and environmentally sound.
<P>
. The development of high quality carbon anodes for use in the
production of aluminium.
<P>
. Development of advanced combustion technologies for more efficient
generation of electricity.
<P>
A pilot UCC plant co-funded by Pacific Power, was constructed
with production of tonnage quantities of UCC. The demonstration
project was erected on the site of the old Ulan Power Station
near Mudgee in central western NSW. The technical feasibility
of producing UCC was demonstrated during these trials.
<P>
The pilot plant has now been moved to the ACIRL laboratories at
Maitland where further development is being carried out by a consortium
of Australian interests.
<P>
A second project being considered, jointly with the production
of UCC, involves the development of a Clean Coal Engine. It is
envisaged that in order to develop this technology a modified
'coal burning' gas turbine will have to be constructed and tested
using UCC.
<MENU>
<LI>2.7 Underground (In-Situ) Coal Gasification (UCG)
<LI>Underground coal gasification is the process by which coal
is partially burned without being mined, and the heat generated
by the combustion decomposes and gasifies additional coal to produce
a combustible gaseous fuel. The benefit of this process is that
coal seams which are poor in quality and/or expensive to mine
can still be utilised by converting the coal into gas. Development
of UCG is quite recent and a great deal of interest in the technology
has already been shown worldwide.
<LI>The simplest type of underground gasification requires drilling
a well into a coal seam to inject oxygen containing gases whilst
another well is drilled to remove the gaseous products. The process
has two stages, the first being an ignition and linking stage
and the second a gasification stage.
<LI>Figure 2.12 - Underground Coal Gasification.
<LI>In the first stage the injection and production wells are
connected using a linking technique such as a horizontal borehole
or reverse combustion (i.e. fire and injection gases travel in
opposite directions). This stage produces a path of increased
permeability between the injection and production wells. At shallow
depths linked vertical wells may be used where it is possible
to establish linkage. At greater depths or where linkage is more
difficult to establish deflected 'horizontal' bores may be used.
<LI>Once the gasification channel is established and combustion
commenced, air or oxygen rich gases are injected and the gasification
zone progresses gradually toward the production well.
<LI>If air is injected as the oxidant, the product has a low heating
value (3 to 7 MJ/Nm3) due to the presence of nitrogen in the product
gas. If however oxygen and steam are injected, the product has
a medium heating value (8 to 11 MJ/Nm3 as compared to 38 MJ/Nm3
for natural gas). The product gas generally contains carbon monoxide,
hydrogen and methane.
<LI>The product gas may be used to fire a boiler to raise steam
or to fuel a gas turbine for generation of electricity. The product
gas can also be further refined to produce chemicals or liquid
fuels. The cost to produce gas using UCG compared to using a surface
gasifier is much lower due to the fact that mining and coal handling
equipment, as well as, surface gasifiers are not required.
<LI>Developments overseas include industrial scale operation in
the USSR since the 1950's and numerous demonstrations in the USA
to confirm technical feasibility, particularly since the 1972
oil price crisis. Testing has been curtailed in more recent years
due to fuel price declines and increased availability of both
natural gas and petroleum. However, with instability of oil prices
in more recent times, development of this technology could once
again takeoff. There are no commercial operations currently in
the USA or Australia.
<LI>The process has been shown to be technically feasible and
is appropriate where coal is not mineable by conventional means.
Areas have been identified in NSW with coal resources suitable
for UCG. However, a period of up to 10 years may be required to
prove the potential of these specific areas and develop experience
in the technology in Australia.
<LI>2.8 Geothermal Energy
<LI>The flow of heat from within the earth to the surface averages
0.06 W/m2 and is attributable to two factors: the process of the
earth cooling down and newly generated heat as a result of natural
radioactive decay in the earth's crust. Estimates show that the
latter is probably the more significant factor. Since this heat
liberation is not evenly distributed across the surface of the
earth, geothermal anomalies can lend themselves to economic utilisation.
Such anomalies are found mainly but not exclusively in areas with
active volcanoes.
<LI>Figure 2.13 provides a schematic diagram of a geothermal reservoir.
Depending on the temperature of the heat discharged, such reservoirs
may be subdivided into various categories:
<UL>
<LI>hot-steam reservoirs (e.g. the oldest source of this type
in operation is in the Italian town of Larderello operated since
1904);
<LI>hot-water reservoirs (e.g. Wairakei, New Zealand, Cerro Prieto,
Mexico, and in Iceland);
<LI>warm-water reservoirs with temperatures below 100 degrees
Celsius (e.g. Birdsville, Queensland).
</UL>

</MENU>

<P>
Of the energy stored, approximately 25% can be extracted in the
case of hot-steam reservoirs and about 1% in the case of hot-water
reservoirs.
<P>
There are also hot dry rock reservoirs which store by far the
most geothermal energy but have to be developed first by the artificial
creation of crevices and the insertion of water as a heat carrier.
This concept is still in the experimental stage.
<P>
Figure 2.13 - Geothermal Energy for Power Generation.
<H5>Use and Potential</H5>

<P>
Geothermal energy is used for generating electricity and for heating.
In steam and hotwater reservoirs the steam obtained is used directly
for driving turbines. In warm-water reservoirs steam is generated
via a second, closed circuit using low boiling point gases such
as isobutane or ammonia, as the working fluid. The principles
are based on the Rankine cycle; the organic gas being passed through
an expansion turbine/engine. The resulting mechanical energy is
used to generate electricity. Overall design and economy of a
geothermal installation is site specific depending greatly on
the quality and quantity of energy in the reservoir.
<P>
About 1% of the global heat flow is concentrated in geothermal
energy. Geothermal heat is not an immediately renewable source
of energy if a power station extracts more heat from a reservoir
than the adjacent rock can provide.
<P>
Figure 2.14 shows the rated output capacity of major geothermal
facilities currently installed in various countries. The largest
and most successful plant so far is The Geysers in the USA where
several power stations with a total installed capacity of 2000
MW(e) are fed from 250 geothermal sources.
<P>
Figure 2.14 - Number of major geothermal power stations installed
<P>
worldwide (Sept 1986)
<H5>Environmental Considerations</H5>

<P>
The main problem in the use of geothermal energy is that the steam
or water flowing from the artesian bore contains partly aggressive
gases and minerals. Up to a maximum of 26% of the water is made
up of dissolved solids, the average being about 3%. These impurities
cause corrosion and deposits in turbines and heat exchangers and
may also be a burden on the environment.
<P>
General repercussions for the environment include:
<UL>
<LI>the amount of heat discharged is 23 times greater than conventional
power stations;
<LI>the problem of harmful waste waters can be solved in part
by re-injection into the reservoir;
<LI>the amount of sulphur released in the Geysers field by way
of exhaust gases is comparable to the discharge of sulphur by
conventional power stations, a further factor being the unpleasant
smell of other gases including hydrogen sulphide;
<LI>with steam containing a large amount of water, the process
of separation of water from steam may cause significant noise,
requiring good sound insulation.
<MENU>
<LI>2.9 Nuclear Fission
</MENU>

</UL>

<H5>Nuclear Power in NSW</H5>

<P>
The &quot;Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions)
Act, 1986, No. 194&quot; Section 9 prohibits the Electricity Commission
of New South Wales from constructing, operating or approving a
nuclear reactor for the purposes of generating electricity. This
discussion of nuclear power generation is included for completeness
in the context of alternative and emerging technologies for power
generation.
<H5>The Status of Nuclear Power Fission</H5>

<P>
Electricity was first generated by a nuclear power station in
1951 at the &quot;Experimental Breeder Reactor 1&quot; in Idaho.
Since then nuclear power stations have become a major electricity
source. In 1988, 430 nuclear power stations were in operation,
producing 16% of the world's electrical energy (17 000 TWh). Nuclear
power stations have mostly large units typically 600-1300 MW(e)
in size. The USA has the greatest nuclear capacity, followed by
France, the USSR, Japan and Germany. At over 70%, France has the
greatest proportion of nuclear energy in their generation capacity.
<MENU>
<LI>2.9.1 Types of Nuclear Power Stations
<LI>The fission process which produces the heat required for a
conventional steam cycle occurs when the nucleus of a Uranium
235 atom is split in two after colliding with a neutron. As well
as a large amount of heat being generated, an average of 2.5 neutrons
are released per collision, one of these then moving on to continue
the fission process, and thus sustain the reaction. The 1.5 neutrons
which don't continue in the fission reaction are absorbed by nuclei.
<LI>The heat produced during the fission reaction, is transferred
to a fluid which may be a gas or liquid for example, air, helium,
carbon dioxide, molten salt, water, liquid metal (sodium), or
an organic liquid. This hot fluid then transfers its heat to a
conventional steam cycle from which electricity can be generated.
</MENU>

<H5>Light-Water Reactors</H5>

<P>
There are two forms of light water reactors; pressurised water
reactors (PWR) and less commonly boiling water reactors (BWR).
These reactors use light water as a coolant as opposed to a heavy
water cooled reactor which is also used to supply energy. The
boiling water reactors produce steam in the reactor core, the
saturated steam then passes directly to the turbo-generator where
the energy is recovered. In the pressurised water reactor, high
pressure liquid water is used as the reactor coolant, the water's
heat is then transferred to a secondary steam cycle which supplies
energy to a turbine and generator. Light water reactors are the
most common of the reactor types, and are likely to be for several
decades. They operate with efficiencies slightly less than conventional
fossil fuelled power stations.
<P>
A new design of light water reactor has been developed in the
USA. Known as the 'advanced' light water reactor (ALWR), it operates
with improved passive safety systems and is smaller than other
light water reactors. The reduction in the number of nuclear power
stations being constructed worldwide has slowed the implementation
of the ALWR.
<H5>High Temperature Reactors</H5>

<P>
High temperatures are possible in these reactors as the reactor
core is cooled by compressed helium gas. High temperatures of
up to 950 degrees Celsius result in relatively high efficiencies
of the order of the efficiency of fossil fuelled power stations.
<H5>Fast Breeder Reactors</H5>

<P>
In fast breeder reactors high energy neutrons cause most of the
fission events. This is in contrast to &quot;thermal&quot; reactors
where the neutrons are deliberately slowed down in the moderator,
releasing slow or &quot;thermal&quot; neutrons to the fission
process.
<P>
In the reactor, plutonium 239 is the main fuel. Depleted or natural
uranium (mostly U238) is placed as a blanket around the core.
<P>
High energy &quot;fast&quot; neutrons are necessary in breeder
reactors for the fission of the &quot;fertile&quot; uranium 238.
This in turn produces an increasing amount of plutonium 239. The
rate of production of plutonium 239 is greater than the rate of
consumption, thus the reactor is breeding fissionable fuel. This
reactor utilises the more abundant uranium 238, and could result
in total uranium reserves worldwide being extended.
<P>
Fast breeder technology is currently being promoted above all
in countries without their own uranium resources, such as France
and Japan, but also the USSR. More than 10 fast breeders are now
operating. Considering the low level of uranium prices today,
even proponents of the fast breeder do not believe that this type
of reactor can operate economically in this century.
<P>
This type of reactor is particularly suitable for the extraction
of high temperature heat for chemical processes, the gasification
of coal or the production of steam for electricity generation.
<H5>Radioactive Wastes</H5>

<P>
The nuclear fuel cycle including the production of fuel, its use
in a reactor and its subsequent disposal as waste, produces what
are termed low, medium and high level radioactive wastes.
<P>
Low level wastes are those items and materials used through the
fuel cycle which may have become contaminated. Typically this
may include cleaning equipment, gloves, clothes, tools etc. Low
level waste has similar radioactivity to uranium orebody.
<P>
Medium level wastes include fuel handling equipment, reactor equipment
and parts etc. Both low and medium radioactive wastes are disposed
of in shallow burial sites. Prior to disposal, highly toxic portions
of these wastes are separated and included for disposal with the
high level wastes.
<P>
High level wastes include fission products (spent fuel) and high
atomic mass elements artificially formed by neutron capture. This
waste emits a high level of radiation as well as a great deal
of heat. The heat mainly arising from fission products.
<P>
Quite a few countries have final storage facilities for low and
medium activity waste, however highly active waste is cooled for
years prior to storage, and as yet no final storage facilities
for highly active waste have been implemented. The following brief
descriptions indicate some of the avenues of research in this
area.
<H5>Glass Blocks in Salt Domes</H5>

<P>
The final storage method chosen by Germany is to cast the highly
active material into boron silicate glass blocks, ready for storage
in salt domes. The blocks are placed 850m underground in galleries
drilled in the salt dome. Salt domes have several characteristics
which make them suitable as final storage sites:
<MENU>
<LI>(i) they are located in proven water tight strata, by virtue
of their existence;
<LI>(ii) salt is structurally suitable to protect enclosed waste
from geological upheavals; and
<LI>(iii) salt has a good thermal conductivity allowing efficient
dissipation of heat produced by radioactive decay.
</MENU>

<P>
In spite of the above there are still problems to be considered
with salt domes such as recently small pockets of brine have been
detected in salt domes (in one case a test bore filled with water),
and the resistance of salt domes to high temperatures has been
questioned.
<P>
There is also doubt about the durability of the glass blocks when
subjected to the high temperatures and pressures experienced while
buried deep in geological formations. High temperatures and pressures
cause devitrification of glass and with water present leaching
may occur. Because of these doubts, Britain plans to keep their
glass blocks in air cooled enclosures for at least 50 years.
<H5>Synroc</H5>

<P>
Synroc (which is being developed in Australia) is a synthetic
ceramic crystalline rock, in which it is proposed to dispose of
highly active waste. The waste will be incorporated in synrocs
crystalline structure. Waste on a large scale has not yet been
incorporated in synroc and even after successful incorporation
of the waste, a 50 year testing programme will be required to
ensure the material is secure. If successful, the synroc blocks
would be stored in a stable geological structure such as granite.
Such structures are found in Australia.
<H5>Reprocessing of Fuel</H5>

<P>
Used fuel rods are reprocessed for three main reasons:
<MENU>
<LI>(i) to recover viable fuel for further use;
<LI>(ii) to recycle plutonium for use and destruction in the fission
process of a reactor;
<LI>(iii) to remove fission waste products for final storage.
</MENU>

<P>
The alternative to reprocessing is to store used fuel rods in
intermediate storage until they are cool enough for final storage.
<H5>Nuclear Energy Cost </H5>

<P>
Currently, nuclear power stations are technology intensive, resulting
in very high capital costs. Decommissioning of these power stations
at the end of their useful life is also now being identified as
a major cost. In total, electricity produced by nuclear power
stations costs of the order of three times that of electricity
produced by NSW coal-fired stations.
<MENU>
<LI>2.10 Nuclear Fusion
<LI>The aim of nuclear fusion research is to provide a new source
of energy for the industrialised world which offers significant
advantages:
<UL>
<LI>unproblematic procurement of fuel,
<LI>high energy yield,
<LI>minimum hazard,
<LI>minimum environmental pollution.
</UL>

</MENU>

<P>
Since this type of energy represents a long-term development,
it is currently not possible to make any reliable forecasts as
to the economic viability of nuclear fusion energy.
<P>
Commercial fusion power stations are not expected to be available
before the middle of next century.
<H5>Elementary Process and Fuel</H5>

<P>
The elementary process releasing energy is the fusion of two light
atomic nuclei. Fusion is counteracted by the electrostatic repulsion
of the nuclei, which can only be overcome by making them collide
with a sufficient impact, as is the case at temperatures above
100 million degrees Celsius. The requirement, therefore, is to
heat up the fusion fuel to such temperatures and to maintain it
with adequate density for sufficiently long period.
<P>
Deuterium and tritium have the highest reaction rates for nuclear
fusion. Deuterium can be extracted from water at low cost and
is therefore available in unlimited quantities. Tritium is &quot;bred&quot;
in the reactor itself out of lithium, an element found in large
quantities and well distributed in the earth's crust.
<P>
This would provide a virtually inexhaustible fuel supply, particularly
considering the very small amount of fuel required in nuclear
fusion: generation of 1 million kWh of electricity requires approximately
400t of hard coal but only 40g of lithium and 12.5g of deuterium.
<P>
An important advantage of the fusion reactor is that it does not
pollute the environment with chemically toxic substances. Rather,
the reaction product of the fusion process is helium, a chemically
inactive rare gas. None of the other processes in the fuel cycle
results in the emission of chemical contaminants either. In particular,
there is no emission of sulphur dioxide, nitrogen oxides or carbon
dioxide.
<MENU>
<LI>2.11 Dry Cooling In Power Stations
</MENU>

<H5>Future Power Station Sites in NSW</H5>

<P>
New South Wales power stations have in the past been sited close
to large coal reserves, and water supplies since these raw materials
strongly affect the economics of the electricity generated. Future
power stations may be required to make use of coal reserves which
are remote from sufficient water resources normally required for
cooling purposes. For this reason dry cooling technologies are
being developed such that areas which possess large quantities
of coal but little water become economically attractive as future
power generation sites.
<H5>Power Station Cooling Systems</H5>

<P>
Cooling systems are an integral part of the steam cycle of coal-fired
power stations. Their role can be described as follows:
<H5>The Basic Steam Cycle</H5>

<P>
Water is pumped into the boiler drum at high pressure and then
flows through banks of tubes into a boiler. This water is then
heated (in New South Wales the energy is provided by burning coal),
past its boiling point producing steam at a super-heat condition
of 540 degrees Celsius. When the super-heated high pressure steam
leaves the boiler, it enters an expansion turbine. The steam turns
the fan-like blades of the turbine which is, in turn connected
by a shaft to the electrical generator. This converts the rotational
mechanical power to electricity.
<P>
The spent steam exits the turbine at a low temperature (less than
50 degrees Celsius) and low pressure and is condensed using one
of the cooling systems outlined below. The resulting water is
then ready to be pumped back into the boiler drum to start the
cycle again.
<P>
Figure 2.15 - The Basic Steam Cycle.
<H5>Cooling Systems at NSW Power Stations</H5>

<P>
At present New South Wales power stations are either cooled by
using saltwater from coastal (estuarine), freshwater cooling pond
lake water or wet cooling towers, depending on the availability
of water resources at the particular site.
<P>
Limits have been placed on the maximum temperature (35 degrees
Celsius) at which cooling water can be discharged to prevent high
lake temperatures and avoiding environmental problems. Wet cooling
towers use freshwater and achieve 80% of their cooling by evaporation
of the cooling water. This evaporation represents a loss of millions
of litres of water per year. When the cost of water reaches approximately
70-90 cents/kL (depending on the location), dry cooling may become
the more attractive option for cooling. Current water costs of
Pacific Power Power Stations are of the order of 50 cents/kL.
<H5>Lake Cooling</H5>

<P>
In this system exhaust steam exiting the turbine enters the condenser.
The cooling water from the lake is pumped through a large number
of tubes which pass through the condenser box. The steam is condensed
by the cooling water and is then pumped out from the bottom of
the condenser. The cooling water is heated during this process,
and is then returned to the lake.
<H5>Wet Cooling Towers</H5>

<P>
Wet cooling towers use the same condenser system as in lake cooling,
however, the cooling water comes from a large basin at the bottom
of the cooling tower. In a natural draft cooling tower the heated
cooling water from the condenser is sprayed down the inside of
the cooling tower whilst air, under the effects of natural convection
flows up through the cooling tower. The air draft evaporates some
of the cooling water, lowering the temperature of the remaining
cooling water. The draft can also be produced by fans in an induced
draft cooling tower. A plume of pure water vapour can often be
seen exiting the top of wet cooling towers particularly when the
atmosphere has high humidity.
<H5>Figure 2.16 - Lake Cooling/ Figure 2.17 - Wet Cooling Tower
</H5>

<H5>Dry Cooling Systems</H5>

<P>
There are two main types of dry cooling technology, the direct
system and the indirect system. These systems operate similar
to car radiators, in that they use a flow of air to cool water
flowing inside finned tubes.
<H5>Indirect Dry Cooling</H5>

<P>
Indirect dry cooling towers use the same condenser system as in
lake cooling, however the cooling water is recirculated through
banks of finned tubes over which cooling air flows. The air flow
is induced in a natural draft cooling tower by convection.
<P>
If fans were used instead of the natural draft tower, a large
number of fans would be required to achieve the same heat rejection.
This is because the temperature difference between the air and
the cooling water is relatively small. The natural draft cooling
tower for dry cooling is larger than for an equivalent wet system,
since heat transfer rates are much less.
<P>
Another form of indirect cooling system is that of the 'spray'
condenser. In this system the boiler water acts also as the cooling
water and is circulated through the finned tubes for cooling.
This system is theoretically more efficient than other indirect
systems as heat transfer through tubes from the boiler water to
the cooling circuit is no longer required. In practice these condensers
have not proved to be as efficient as expected and research is
continuing. Water treatment in this case however is more critical
to maintain demineralised water quality for such a large volume.
<H5>Direct Dry Cooling</H5>

<P>
In the direct dry cooling system the turbine exhaust steam is
passed directly through finned tubes. The tubes are finned to
increase their surface area and hence cooling capability. Ambient
air is forced over these tubes with the aid of fans cooling and
condensing the steam.
<P>
The cooling system needs to be located as near as possible to
the turbine, so that the turbine operates efficiently. This also
minimises leaks which can contaminate the steam (steam pressure
is below atmospheric pressure, so leaks will allow air to flow
into the tubes). It is possible to locate a fan forced cooling
system closer to the turbine than a natural draft system. The
tube banks are located directly adjacent to the turbine hall,
minimising piping distance, and the fans are located under the
tubebanks.
<P>
Comparison of Direct vs Indirect Dry Cooling Systems. Indirect
dry cooling systems tend to have a large capital cost (due to
the large cost of the natural draft cooling tower) but low operating
cost. In comparison direct dry cooling has a low capital cost
but high operating cost (due to large power consumption of the
fans). In general, direct dry cooling is favoured at sites with
low fuel cost (the fan power is less costly), whilst indirect
dry cooling is more suitable at sites with high fuel costs.
<H5>Current Status</H5>

<P>
The largest dry cooled power stations have been constructed in
South Africa. Three power stations were built consisting of 6
units, each unit having an output in the range 660-685 MW(e):
Matimba - a direct dry cooled station, Majuba - also a direct
system and Kendal - an indirect dry cooled station. The largest
power station units in NSW are similar in size to the South African
units, hence the technology being developed for South Africa has
particular relevance to NSW developments.
<P>
Pacific Power is currently investigating the site specific nature
of corrosion and fouling of a variety of dry cooling tube types.
Because of the low heat transfer rates of dry cooling, this aspect
of their operation is critical as it may cause heat rejection
rates to vary considerably and hence affect the economics of electricity
produced.
<P>
Figure 2.18 - Indirect Dry Cooling Tower/ Figure 2.19 - Direct
Dry
<P>
Cooling Tower
</BODY>

