<H3>NEW AND ALTERNATIVE TECHNOLOGIES FOR ELECTRICITY GENERATION</H3>
<HR>

<H4><B>Chapter 3</B> </H4>

<H4>New Technologies in Power Generation</H4>

<H4>Renewables</H4>

<H5>3.1 Wind Energy</H5>

<P>
For centuries mankind has been harnessing the power of the wind,
to propel sailing ships, pump water and, during this century,
to produce electricity. Today a major focus for wind energy is
the production of electricity for supply into the main electricity
network.
<P>
Wind turbines for producing electricity range from kilowatt sized
machines for use on yachts and at isolated homesteads to a few
machines of several megawatts that are still largely experimental.
Currently, worldwide there are more than 2000 MW(e) of installed
wind turbine capacity, roughly equivalent to about 60% of the
capacity of the Snowy Mountains Scheme. Although this is located
mainly in California, Denmark has a total installed capacity of
some 360 MW(e), comprising almost 3000 turbines and providing
about 2% of electricity demand.
<P>
Various designs of wind turbines are available.
<H6>Figure 3.1 - Typical Wind Turbine Performance Data</H6>

<P>
Several countries are operating largescale (1 to 4 MW) experimental
wind turbines. However, the most widely used machines for electricity
production are much smaller. The design concept is relatively
simple and a typical 300 kW(e) machine could have the following
features:
<P>
. three-bladed 30 metre diameter rotor rotating at 40 rpm;
<P>
. blades constructed from fibreglass or wood epoxy and which are
<P>
able to change their pitch to optimise the angle to the wind;
<P>
. hub of the rotor connected to a gearbox and induction generator,
<P>
both placed within an enclosed nacelle;
<P>
. nacelle and rotor placed on a 30 metre tower, and able to rotate
<P>
so that the wind turbine is always facing into the wind;
<P>
. able to replace the combustion of 250 tonnes of coal per year
<P>
which would supply the energy requirements of 70 NSW homes.
<P>
Today, the most economical turbines are about 300 kW - 600 kW
capacity
<P>
and could typically be located as a 'wind farm' of 3 to 6 MW(e)
total
<P>
capacity occupying approximately 2 square kilometres of land.
The wind
<P>
turbines in each farm would be operated as an integrated unit
with
<P>
connection often being into the local electricity transmission
network.
<P>
Several countries have active wind energy programs. In some countries
<P>
the cost of electricity generated by wind turbines is competitive
with
<P>
that from other forms of generation. Other countries desirous
of
<P>
achieving a portion of generation from non fossil fuel sources
have
<P>
embarked upon wind generation programs.
<P>
Proponents of wind energy claim a number of advantages in support
of
<P>
the technology in addition to the value associated with providing
<P>
energy, and some credit for capacity. These advantages include
the
<P>
following:
<P>
. the energy produced displaces combustion of fossil fuels and
hence
<P>
emissions of carbon dioxide, particulates, sulphur dioxide and
<P>
other pollutants;
<P>
. the wind is a renewable resource;
<P>
. diversification of an electricity supply system generally reduces
<P>
risk;
<P>
. some distribution systems may benefit from local generation;
<P>
. local economic and employment benefits may result.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
The relationship between wind speed, wind power and typical wind
turbine performance follows:
<P>
The power (P) available from a wind swept area (A) with wind blowing
at velocity (V) is given by the following formula.
<P>
P = 0.5 x D x A x V3
<P>
P = Wind Power (watts)
<P>
D = Air Density (kg/m3)
<P>
A = Swept Area (m2)
<P>
V = Wind Speed (m/s)
<P>
It is important to note that power is proportional to the wind
speed
<P>
cubed, and hence for relatively small increases in wind speed
large
<P>
increases in power can be observed.
<P>
Betz Limit of Wind Turbine Efficiency
<P>
There is a theoretical limit to the amount of power which can
be
<P>
extracted from the wind. This is termed the Betz limit. The Betz
<P>
limit stipulates that a perfect wind turbine can at best extract
59.3%
<P>
of the total power available. This limit was originally derived
by A.
<P>
Betz in 1927.
<P>
Modern Wind Turbine Efficiencies
<P>
At their design wind speed, modern wind turbines can extract as
much as
<P>
40% of the available power from the wind.
<P>
The amount of energy produced by a wind turbine per year depends
<P>
strongly on the selected site and the climatic conditions associated
<P>
with that site. An annual average wind speed of above 6 m/s defines
a
<P>
good wind site.
<P>
The wind turbine energy production vs. wind speed curve shows
that most
<P>
of the electrical energy is produced at wind speeds well above
the
<P>
average wind speed.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
The cost of wind generated electricity is very sensitive to the
available wind resource. For example, wind with a velocity of
8 m/s will provide more than twice the power of 6 m/s wind. In
countries with an established wind turbine manufacturing industry,
and a good wind resource, the cost of electricity from the wind
is about 5 to 7 cents/kWh (or about twice the current cost of
producing coal-fired electricity in NSW).
<P>
Several issues must be carefully assessed when planning to install
wind turbines. Wind energy is not completely environmentally benign,
only relatively so. The choice of a suitable site involves assessment
of the wind and the availability of the necessary electricity
transmission infrastructure. However, other issues must also be
addressed which are particular to wind generation:
<UL>
<LI>visual impact of the wind farm on the local community;
<LI>local noise annoyance;
<LI>electromagnetic interference;
<LI>impact on bird life;
<LI>safety aspects.
<MENU>
<LI>It is anticipated that these issues would be resolved in NSW
with appropriate planning and community consultation. As a first
step in this process Pacific Power is funding a $220,000 study
with the CSIRO Centre for Environmental Mechanics to identify
prime wind farm sites in NSW. Figure 3.2 shows areas that may
contain suitable conditions for wind generation in NSW.
<LI>Figure 3.2 - Wind Generation Study Areas in New South Wales.
<LI>It is difficult to assess the potential for wind energy generation
in NSW other than to say that it is anticipated that it will play
a small, but important role in the future electricity supply mix.
To provide a perspective on this technology and its possible utilisation
in NSW it is interesting to note that supply of just 1% of existing
electrical needs would require the installation of more than twenty
10 MW(e) wind farms.
</MENU>

</UL>

<H5>3.2 Solar Photovoltaic</H5>

<P>
Photovoltaics (PV's) is the technology which uses thin sheets
of semiconductive material to directly transform sunlight into
electricity when illuminated.
<P>
The electricity is generated directly in the cell itself, and
so the process is virtually maintenance free except for cleaning
of the active surface as there are no moving parts in the system.
Another advantage of solar cells over concentrator type solar
thermal systems is that it is still possible for them to operate
in diffuse sunlight and in slightly overcast weather.
<P>
Production of solar photovoltaic cells began 30 years ago, with
cells of approximately 2% efficiency being developed for space
programmes. Now, cell efficiency at market level is approximately
14 - 15%. BP Solar are carrying out research here in Australia
and are now producing cells in a pilot production facility with
efficiencies of between 17 to 18%. Costs per watt have decreased
markedly, and research should see this continue whilst also providing
further increases in efficiency. The installed cost of photovoltaics
is still their major disadvantage, however, they still find practical
application for telecommunications, marine navigation, water pumping,
terrestrial applications and remote area power supplies.
<P>
Solar cells are made of 2 layers of a semiconductor material such
as silicon which is doped with minute quantities of other elements
to give n-type and p-type semiconductors. Sandwiching these together
gives what is termed a pn junction across which current flows.
This sets up an internal electric field which has a potential
difference of approximately 0.5 V.
<P>
Figure 3.3 - Construction of a Solar Photovoltaic Cell.
<P>
The electric current is then drawn by way of metal contacts which
are distributed across the negative and positive faces of the
cell. This necessary distribution of pick-ups also creates a problem
for cell efficiencies because the contacts create an area that
shades the semiconductor material. A great amount of research
goes into the practicalities of getting photons into the material,
quite apart from the movement of carriers within it.
<P>
A number of different forms of photovoltaic technology exist.
For example, there are concentrating and non-concentrating cells,
different cell materials such as silicon, gallium arsenide, and
compounds of copper with trace elements. Within the silicon cell
market, there are mono-crystalline, poly-crystalline and amorphous
silicon cells. Each type is being continually refined, and hence
efficiencies improved.
<P>
Professor Martin Green and his team at the University of NSW presently
hold the world record with a non-concentrating silicon cell at
an efficiency of 24.2%. Theoretically the maximum conceivable
efficiency would be of the order of 30%.
<P>
Professor Green also heads up the 'Centre for Photovoltaic Devices
and Systems'. One of the aims of this centre is to further research
into thin film silicon devices. This presently appears to be the
most promising of cells under research for the future. As well
as continuing with other cell research, part of the aim of the
centre is to look for specific sites within the electricity supply
network where PV's might best be used. Some examples are, preventing
the need for re-conductoring of heavily loaded lines approaching
thermal limits, reducing voltage drop at the end of single wire
earth return lines, and offsetting capital costs for upgrading
of thermally overloaded transformers.
<P>
The second largest application of solar cells in Australia provides
power for water pumping. This represents very good matching of
solar energy with water requirements because, usually, most water
is required when agricultural evaporation is high due to sunny
and hot conditions.
<P>
Solar cells are also being more widely used as Remote Area Power
Supplies (RAPS) where they can be economic in offsetting the cost
of diesel fuel for small communities, or single dwellings not
connected to the main electricity supply grid. PV cells can be
seen providing electricity for navigational aids on waterways,
lighting, electric fencing in remote areas, cathodic protection,
and outback telephone systems.
<P>
Presently, in Australia, solar cells would cost approximately
$6000/kW in large scale use. However, at least this much again
would be required for the balance of system costs, which includes
such items as power conditioning equipment and site installation
costs. By comparison, a coal-fired power station would cost around
$1200/kW for a coastal power station with access to lake or sea
water cooling, plus the cost of developing a coal mine to supply
the power station and bulk transmission cost.
<P>
Even given the dramatic reduction in cell costs over the years,
and the fact that photovoltaic generation would probably be connected
at distribution voltage level, some time would be required before
cells could compete on a large scale grid connected basis. The
availability of electricity would only correspond to the availability
of sunlight, and thus, could not directly compete as a reliable
alternative, without the added expense of storage such as a battery.
<P>
This in no way negates the goal of improving the viability of
solar cells. Specific site application has shown them to be viable,
and their generality of use will only increase as research continues
to reduce costs.
<H6>Types of Cells</H6>

<P>
Silicon is the second most abundant material on earth, and is
the most common material used in solar cells.
<P>
There are three major types of silicon solar cells.
<P>
Amorphous: These cells do not possess a regular crystal structure.
They can be produced in films of 0.3 microns and their production
is relatively simple and cheap. Mass production of these cells
is quite easy, with small amounts of material being deposited
on to a substrate such as glass or aluminium, and can even be
made flexible.
<P>
Their major drawback is their low efficiency and short lifespan.
Presently, efficiencies are only 5-7%, however this drops to 3-4%
in operation due to amorphous silicon instabilities. It is generally
used for small scale applications such as calculators and watches.
<P>
Poly-crystalline: These cells consist of a number of silicon crystals
grown as an ingot from which wafers are cut. Their maximum efficiency
is generally 15% and is standard material for high output applications.
Its layers are of the order of 250-400 microns thick.
<P>
Mono-crystalline: These are the highest efficiency silicon cells
available, however in the past their expense has generally precluded
them from anything except &quot;space&quot; applications where
the sun shines nearly all day. Recent developments in mono-crystalline
cell technology has seen their cost reduced to around that of
the poly-crystalline cell. Mono-crystalline cells consist only
of a single crystal.
<P>
Cells other than silicon are available, and some, such as gallium
arsenide, have efficiencies higher than that of silicon. They
are more efficient because their particular band-gap energies
are closer to the theoretical optimum than silicon. They do however
use materials which are more expensive, less abundant, and can
be environmentally hazardous.
<P>
Because different semi-conductor materials absorb different portions
of the solar spectrum, the possiblility of piggy-backing them
to produce a tandem cell has been investigated. These then absorb
much more of the incident radiation than either material would
alone. Once again, however, their cost is much greater than silicon
cells, even on a unit energy delivered basis.
<H5>3.3 Solar Thermal</H5>

<H6>Introduction</H6>

<P>
Solar thermal does not create electricity directly as does photovoltaic
technology but rather uses solar collectors to heat a fluid, usually
water. The resulting heat may then be used either directly, as
hot water (e.g. domestic hot water system), or process heat, which
is when solar energy systems are at their most efficient (e.g.
domestic hot water system), or may supply preheating, or indeed
steam, for turning a heat engine and generator.
<P>
The solar collectors are the heart of the system and their design
determines the final application and efficiency. The critical
factors are the amount and temperature of solar energy collection
that they provide.
<P>
Flat plate solar collectors are commonly used for heating water
or air for a range of domestic and industrial applications. This
collector provides no concentration and its maximum operating
temperature is generally around 80 degrees Celsius.
<P>
To reach higher temperatures efficiently, some concentration needs
to be employed. Concentration to give high temperatures offers
advantages of more efficient heat transfer, higher theoretical
steam cycle efficiencies, and subsequently a much wider range
of applications. However higher temperatures require greater emphasis
upon reducing thermal losses. As well as this, the greater the
concentration, the greater can be the detrimental effect of cloud
cover or hazy days.
<H6>Solar Thermal Systems</H6>

<P>
Residential flat plate collectors are presently installed on about
5% of NSW homes. The Pacific Power and Sydney University are collaborating
in the testing of a system using a mildly concentrating trough
with an evacuated tube collector. It can supply not only hot water
but space heating and cooking requirements as well. Investigations
show that with one day's storage, solar collection could supply
up to 90% of the thermal loads of a household. The reason for
this and its inherent advantages over other solar systems, is
that it can be designed to give a winter bias, which is when thermal
energy is most needed. A home in the Sydney region has been retrofitted
with such a system and data is now being collected. In keeping
with the whole concept of energy efficiency, a 12-star equivalent
refrigerator, insulation, and compact fluorescent lighting have
also been installed for evaluation.
<P>
Solar Cogeneration: In terms of solar cogeneration, a practical
study was co-funded by Pacific Power in 1991 to look at the provision
of electrical energy and process heat for applications such as
hospitals and process industries. The energy for the production
of steam would be supplied by high temperature collectors. Though
technically viable, none of the sites studied would presently
be economically viable against gas-fired systems or grid electricity.
<P>
Industrial process heat is the largest single energy sector in
Australia, amounting to some 900 PJ annually. Of this, 15% is
below 200 degrees Celsius and 50% below 500 degrees Celsius. Present
solar collector technology could provide the former, and higher
temperature collectors under refinement could provide much of
the latter. Some estimates predict that low temperature steam
could be provided by mass-produced solar collectors at around
2 c/kWh.
<P>
In terms of solar cogeneration, a practical study was co-funded
by Pacific Power in 1991 to look at the provision of electrical
energy and process heat for applications such as hospitals and
process industries. The energy for the production of steam would
be supplied by high temperature collectors. Though technically
viable, none of the sites studied would presently be economically
viable against gas-fired systems or grid electricity.
<P>
Large-Scale Grid Connection: Electricity generation can be provided
24 hours per day by using a solar and gas system, with the gas
providing super-heat or backup to that steam provided by solar
energy. Sites in NSW such as Cobar could be ideal for this technology
since there is a gas supply available and the number of hours
of sunshine per year are high. The largest solar installations
in the world are the 275 MW solar thermal electricity plants installed
by LUZ in Southern Calfornia.
<P>
The solar array is composed of parabolic trough reflectors which
individually track the sun's movement with microprocessors and
light sensing instruments. The light is concentrated on to evacuated
tubes through which a synthetic oil, heat transfer fluid flows.
Temperatures of nearly 400 degrees Celsius are possible. This
is used to produce super-heated steam via a heat exchanger, with
natural gas fuel as a supplement. The power plant produces electricity
with a peak solar to electric efficiency of approximately 25%.
<P>
Average solar radiation at these LUZ sites is similar to that
at Broken Hill in NSW. SEGS VIII, LUZ's largest project so far,
sized at 80 MW(e), is designed for an annual output of 252.7 GWh.
It has 464 000 square metres of collecting surface area, and occupies
an area of some 300 hectares.
<P>
A small-scale demonstration plant was installed at White Cliffs,
Western New South Wales, using 14 parabolic dishes. The dishes
themselves performed extremely well, however, there were problems
with the steam engine and oil separation system. Larger systems
(greater than 5 MW(e)) which can use steam turbines rather than
engines are expected to give greater overall performance, and
also cost reductions due to economies of scale.
<P>
Central Receiver Systems: These use the heliostats in a reflective
arrangement to generate very high temperatures at a single point.
Though this offers greater turbine efficiency, their capital cost
is higher.
<P>
Solar Ponds: Such a system is most attractive for arid regions
of Australia where there is accompanying high salinity. Technically,
this process is quite feasible. A 250,000 square metres, 5 MW(e)
pond in Israel collects heat at an efficiency of 16%. A demonstration
pond at Curtin Springs in the Northern Territory quotes costs
of around $10,800/kW with energy supplied at 16.6 c/kWh. Further
development is required to make this system viable in the future.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<H6>Evacuated Tube Solar Water Heaters</H6>

<P>
Convection and conduction losses become more serious as high temperature
applications are attempted, and it became apparent very early
on in research, that evacuating the space between the glass cover
and the absorber surface would yield much improved performance.
<P>
Figure 3.4 - Solar House Retrofit Project.
<P>
Evacuated flat plate collectors have been investigated, however
are unable to withstand atmospheric pressure without costly mechanical
reinforcement. Tubes have been shown that they can withstand such
pressures.
<P>
The combination of the vacuum (which reduces convection and conduction
losses) and a selective surface (which reduces radiation losses)
means that while evacuated tubes do not offer efficiency improvements
over flat plates at temperatures around 80 degrees Celsius, they
do allow higher temperatures to be reached, up to 350 degrees
Celsius.
<P>
Evacuated tubes have solar energy concentrated on them by a reflective
surface. These surfaces range from flat white painted diffuse
reflectors with no concentration and optical efficiencies of 53%
to highly reflective, concentrating, parabolic troughs with optical
efficiencies of greater than 90%.
<H6>Selective Surfaces</H6>

<P>
Solar energy is a form of electromagnetic radiation whose wavelength
ranges from about 0.3 to 2.5 microns. When this strikes a surface,
some is reflected, some absorbed, and the remainder transmitted
through. Materials are then chosen to suit the application. For
example, in the hot, arid regions of the world, houses are usually
painted white to reflect as much of the radiation as possible.
However, in a solar collector, black coatings are used to absorb
as much of the heat as possible. A problem arises here, however,
in that the more heat that is absorbed, the hotter the surface
gets, and thus the more radiation that the surface emits back
to its environment as a loss. This is what prevents standard flat
plate collectors reaching temperatures much above 80 degrees Celsius.
Loss of heat through emittance is especially a problem in areas
with cold, clear nights. It explains for example, why pools are
often warmer after a cloudy night.
<P>
The emittance from a hot surface is at a higher wavelength than
the solar radiation which heats it initially, and this is why
a selective black surface is a more efficient means of collection
than conventional black surfaces. A selective surface uses a specially
selected combination of materials to allow the sunlight portion
of the spectrum in, but which has very low emissivity in the infra-red
range, and therefore lose very little heat through re-radiation.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<H5>3.4 Wave Energy</H5>

<P>
Waves are not regarded as a large energy source in NSW, as wave
energy is reduced significantly by the existence of the continental
shelf along the coastline. Suitably sited, however, wave energy
may be beneficial to coastal communities remote from the electricity
supply network.
<H6>Wave Formation</H6>

<P>
Energy is transmitted to the ocean from the winds through friction
between the air and the surface of the seas across which they
blow. As winds derive their energy from solar gradients, wave
energy is an indirect by-product of solar energy. Contrary to
popular belief the water in a wave does not actually travel but
merely oscillates while the energy of the wave is translated across
the surface of the ocean.
<P>
The power in a wave is equal to the product of the potential energy
per unit area and the phase velocity of the wave train. The average
power flux in kW/m can be calculated from the expression P = 0.5H2T
(approx) where H is the significant wave height at the location
and T is the dominant wave period.
<P>
Preliminary estimates of some NSW sites yields wave energies of
approximately 12 kW/m of coastline. Thus a 120 kW device would
need to be 10m wide at this location. Ideal on-shore sites yield
wave energies of 25 kW/m.
<P>
A study commissioned by Pacific Power and completed in 1991 investigated
suitability of sites along the New South Wales coastline. The
NSW coast wave power is not high enough for long enough to be
presently viable.
<P>
Costs for a prototype device are estimated to be of the order
of $3000/kW.
<P>
It is estimated that some 1 000 000 GWh of wave energy is dissipated
each year along the southern shores of Australia.
<P>
A number of attempts have been made to harness the perennial motion
of the ocean. These include such devices as the Nodding Duck,
Cockerell Raft, Circular Sea Clam, Bristol Cylinder, the Frog,
and a Swedish Wave Rotor. However the two devices which have shown
the most promise are the Tapchan and the oscillating water chamber:
<P>
Tapchan: The principle here is capital intensive yet very simple.
Waves moving forward through a tapered channel rise and spill
over the sides into an elevated reservoir, from which water can
be released through a turbine as in a hydro system. The advantages
here lie in the buffer storage which dampens the irregularity
of the waves.
<P>
Oscillating Water Chamber: A number of versions of this technology
exist, however essentially as the wave rolls in a column of water
is forced upwards through a cylinder, the pocket of air trapped
above being blown through an air turbine which in turn drives
a generator. As the wave rolls out, air is drawn back through
the air turbine. The profile of the turbine blades are designed
so that they continue to spin the turbine in the same direction
no matter what the direction of airflow. This allows energy to
be extracted from the air as the wave rolls in and also as it
recedes.
<P>
Figure 3.5 - Wave Resonance Power Generation.
<P>
Installation of a number of different sized chambers allows maximum
use to be made of different period waves in resonating chambers.
<H6>Data Collection</H6>

<P>
Wave data is collected using wave-rider buoys. These are large
spherical steel floats which house the electronic processing equipment.
The heart of this equipment, is an accelerometer which responds
to the vertical movements of the buoy. Integration of wave movement
via a microprocessor calculates wave velocities in the vertical
direction, and as a result can calculate wave displacement data.
A solar cell powered transmitter sitting atop the buoy then relays
the data to a shore based receiver. This data is compiled on computer
for processing and assessment.
<P>
Eight wave rider buoys have been deployed along the NSW coast,
and are constantly compiling data which is useful for investigating
wave power potential. This data is used for a variety of engineering
projects along the coast including wharves and jetties, foreshore
developments, storm damage, etc.
<P>
A New Zealand device for wave energy measurement consists of a
seismograph on the shore, monitoring the energy of breaking waves
and correlating this data to wave height.
<H5>3.5 Biomass</H5>

<P>
The extraction of energy from biomass is understood to mean two
processes: first, large-scale production of liquid or gaseous
fuel from plants or crops specially cultivated for this purpose;
second, biological recovery of combustible gas from organic waste
commonly known as biogas.
<P>
The potential and economics of these two processes are clearly
different. The utilization of crops and plants for energy production
purposes is, in general, not practicable on a large scale. In
addition to this, it still has to be proved whether the substantial
input of energy by way of manuring, sowing, tilling the fields,
harvesting and transport can be recovered anyway. Last but certainly
not least, the harmful effect of monocultures on the environment
with large amounts of fertilisers, insecticides, pesticides and
herbicides would be difficult to justify.
<P>
So far, most of the emphasis has been on the useful energy obtained
from organic waste which is considered to be zero cost. The waste
may be used for energy production in many ways. The direct combustion
of such waste for process heat and electricity generation is finding
increasing application. However, such waste must be used within
reasonably close proximity to its point of origin to compensate
for its high collection cost and to avoid the high cost of transportation
to the point of use.
<P>
In principle, many farms could provide themselves with the energy
they need from their own organic waste. One of the main advantages
of biogas is that the gas which is generated is produced where
biomass accumulates as a waste material.
<P>
Biogas systems have been in widespread use for more than 30 years,
especially in Third World countries. India has a few hundred thousand
simple facilities of this kind, whilst in China about 7 million
operate.
<P>
Compared with other energy generation facilities, construction
and operation of a biogas facility is a simple and straightforward
task. Animal excrements and plant waste are the source of energy
used. They are reduced in size and mixed before being placed in
a fermentation tank. The organic waste decomposes under anaerobic
(ie. without oxygen) conditions as a result of its exposure to
microbes naturally present, generating combustible gases in the
process. The only prerequisite for proper fermentation is correct
acidity and operating in a specific temperature range so that
the microbes thrive. Pesticides, disinfectants and antibiotics
must be avoided as they are likely to bring the fermentation process
to a halt.
<P>
Figure 3.6 - Floating Bell Biogas Producer Schematic Diagram.
<P>
The biogas generated in this way consists primarily of 40-70%
methane and 30-60% carbon dioxide. If the gas contains 60% methane,
it has a calorific value of 70% of natural gas. The yield generated
by a biogas facility depends above all on the composition of the
waste material to be fermented and the ambient temperature. If
this temperature is low, up to 50% of the gas generated can be
required afterwards for heating the biomass.
<P>
The other product generated by the process is odourless and hygienic
compost which is ideally suited for use as a fertiliser, provided
the biomass was free of toxic substances such as heavy metals.
<P>
Biogas generation facilities are used mainly by family operated
farms and, in particular, by farms keeping their own livestock.
Using fermentation tanks with a capacity of 6-25 cubed metres,
small and medium-sized farms mainly generate their own energy
for cooking and lighting. The following figures provide basic
orientation on the capacities available. Using the dung of four
head of cattle or 10 pigs, a farm can produce approximately 2
cubed metres of gas and 100 L of sludge manure a day in a 10 cubed
metres facility. This gas is sufficient for:
<P>
. cooking three meals for a family of eight, or
<P>
. running a refrigerator all day and burning a lamp for
<P>
three hours, or
<P>
. generating electricity for one hour with a 3 kW motor
<P>
generator.
<P>
The bright light of gas lamps is generated by incandescent mantles.
Gas operated refrigerators are ammonia absorption refrigerators,
biogas serving merely as the external heating supply. The gas
motors for driving power generators, in turn, are modified diesel
or petrol engines. Any corrosion caused by the hydrogen sulphide
in biogas is kept within limits by changing the oil regularly.
<P>
The production and use of biogas for energy generation has significant
environmental implications. The biogas as it is produced contains
major greenhouse gases, such as methane and carbon dioxide. It
is estimated that methane is 8 times more potent a greenhouse
gas than is carbon dioxide. Therefore by burning the methane gas
produced, which would otherwise have escaped to atmosphere, carbon
dioxide is formed and the overall addition of greenhouse gases
to the atmosphere is less. The environmental benefit is further
enhanced by using the biogas to generate energy, thus reducing
the amount of fossil fuel required to match energy demand. The
utilization of biogas is not only of benefit to the environment,
but has the potential to provide economic returns as well.
<H5>3.6 Waste Incineration</H5>

<P>
In 1989 there were 3.75 million tonnes of solid waste disposed
of in the Sydney region. The quantity of waste being disposed
of is increasing both in total and on a per capita basis. It is
estimated that at these rates, annual waste quantities would increase
to some 5.5 million tonnes by 2001 and by as much as 7.1 million
tonnes by 2011.
<P>
Waste analysis programs carried out by the then Waste Management
Authority (WMA) indicate the average composition of council collected
garbage are those shown in the following table:
<H6>Figure 3.7 - Average composition of council collected garbage
</H6>

<P>
Component of Waste Weight % (as received)
<P>
----------------------------------------------------------
<P>
paper products 20.9
<P>
food waste 27.5
<P>
garden waste 20.5
<P>
plastics 7.6
<P>
wood, rubber, textiles 4.3
<P>
metals 6.3
<P>
glass 9.3
<P>
fines 3.6
<P>
It is important to note that solid wastes are not homogeneous
in nature but are a mixture of both combustible and non-combustible
materials which vary from location to location and over time.
<P>
Apart from avoiding waste from the very beginning and recycling
the waste produced, one of the best methods of waste management
for the future is to burn it in a refuse fuelled power station.
<P>
An international comparison shows that countries with little space
for waste disposal sites make greater use of incineration technologies.
While the incineration of household waste in the European Community
member countries averages only 20%, the corresponding figures
for Japan and Switzerland are 65% and 80% respectively.
<P>
The energy content of household waste varies greatly. This energy
can be recovered in waste incineration. The relative contribution
of waste incineration to the overall generation of energy is small,
hardly exceeding 1% of the national consumption of primary energy
in any country. However, considered from the perspective of plant
technology, conventional waste incineration is a well-developed
process.
<P>
The technology of waste incineration provides two distinct advantages.
The first is the reduction in volume of disposed wastes to about
5% of the original volume (or about 20-30% of the original weight)
and the second is the utilization of the energy produced for the
generation of electricity.
<P>
The scarcity of landfill sites and the increasing difficulty in
obtaining approval for future disposal sites, particularly in
built-up areas such as the Sydney Basin, is forcing other disposal
options to be considered. Waste incineration whilst it is not
necessarily the whole answer, will be an important consideration
in the assessment of options for future disposal.
<P>
The WMA Strategic Plan has included the use of incineration as
an alternative to the long distance transfer of waste away from
the metropolitan area. The WMA also indicate that a strategy of
progressive implementation of three incinerators (1000 tonnes/day)
during the planning period of 2001 to 2011 would require an investment
of the order of $450 million in 1988 values.
<H6>Technologies</H6>

<P>
The technologies for the incineration of wastes can be divided
in two distinct categories. The first has been developed for the
incineration of domestic refuse and sewage sludge, whilst the
second has been developed for the incineration of industrial refuse
and sludge.
<P>
Domestic incinerators consist of a moving grate, of which there
are numerous designs and onto which the garbage is dumped (some
of the more common designs are known as the roller grate, tilting
grate, step type travelling grate and the inclined grate). Combustion
air is passed from beneath the grate through the burning garbage.
The heat produced is used for the production of steam. Residence
time in the incinerator can be strictly controlled by varying
the grate speed and hence avoiding emission problems caused by
incomplete combustion.
<P>
There are two types of industrial refuse and sludge incineration
plant, namely the rotary kiln and the fluidised bed.
<P>
Both domestic and industrial waste disposal methods rely on the
concept of complete 'burnout' of the waste. This is done to minimise
the pollutants contained in combustion gases. Complete 'burnout'
is best achieved by high temperatures, long residence times and
by good mixing of the combustion gases.
<P>
The heat produced from the combustion of waste material is transferred
to banks of water wall tubes for the production of steam which
in turn is used to drive a steam turbine and electrical generator.
This process of steam raising is similar in design to some of
the other technologies discussed throughout this document, for
instance fluidised bed combustion technologies and combined cycle.
<P>
Once the heat contained in the combustion gases is transferred
to the steam circuit, pollution control equipment is used to reduce
harmful pollutants. Burning of domestic and industrial refuse,
leads to emissions of pollutants such as sulphur dioxide, nitrogen
oxides, carbon monoxide and particulate matter. Depending on the
nature of refuse, it is expected that the refuse residue should
only contain low levels of organic compounds and heavy metals.
Waste incineration plants can operate with minimum impact on the
environment by employing emission control equipment such as flue
gas desulphurisation for the control of sulphur dioxide and acid
gases, a thermal nitrogen oxides removal system for control of
nitrogen oxides and a high efficiency particulate collection device
such as a fabric filter for removal of solids and heavy metals
carried along by the exhaust gases.
<P>
The size of waste incineration plants is often quoted in terms
of the mass of refuse consumed per hour rather than the maximum
electrical output. This is useful because the energy contained
in the refuse feed can vary substantially with time and hence
the maximum electrical energy generated also varies. Common incinerator
sizes are between 5 and 30 tonnes per hour. Plant sizes are generally
between 15 and 30 MW of electrical output. For waste tonnages
greater than this, it is usual to install a number of these units
in a single facility.
<P>
The energy contained in domestic garbage is approximately 8-10
MJ/kg or 30-40% of the energy content of black coal.
<P>
Industrial refuse incineration generally excludes the burning
of scrap tyres. Because of the nature of manufacture of tyres,
the tyre combustion process releases a significant amount of potentially
toxic air pollutants such as arsenic, cadmium, dioxins, furans
and other trace heavy metals.
<P>
Therefore, tyre combustion requires &quot;Best Available Control
Technology&quot; (BACT) for the control of emissions. To achieve
this level of environmental control a significant amount of expenditure
is required which adds significantly to the total cost of the
incineration plant. For this reason, the current practice of waste
disposal is to separate scrap tyres from other wastes.
<P>
Tyre combustion technology has already proven to be clean, safe,
odourless and virtually pollution free at a power plant constructed
at Modesto, California, U.S.A. The plant can burn up to 6 million
tyres per year. Whole scrap tyres are fed into two identical incineration
plants at a rate of about 6.5 tonnes/hour and burned under carefully
controlled conditions. Combustion is carried out at a temperature
of 1100 degrees Celsius to produce 14 MW of electric power. This
relatively high temperature combustion process ensures the complete
burnout of the tyres. Together with complete air quality control,
the operation of this facility has been claimed to be environmentally
safe.
<H5>3.7 Landfill Gas</H5>

<P>
Landfill gas refers to the formation of combustible gases from
garbage dumps through primarily anaerobic decomposition of organic
wastes (mostly food, garden and paper wastes). The gas produced
consists predominantly of methane and carbon dioxide and contains
40-60% of the energy content of natural gas.
<P>
Some 3.75 million tonnes of solid waste were disposed of in the
Sydney region in 1989, and as much as 7.1 million tonnes annually
are projected by the year 2011. These wastes not only represent
a significant problem in terms of disposal urban areas such as
Sydney but also a large potential energy resource.
<P>
Driven by environmental concerns during the 1950's investigations
were carried out around the world into the characteristics of
landfills over their lifetime and the constituents of the odorous
gases produced. It was found that the wastes decomposed in the
presence of moisture and the action of anaerobic bacteria, producing
methane and carbon dioxide. As well as these gases being produced,
other gases were released including nitrogen, oxygen, hydrogen
and traces of hydrogen sulphide (rotten egg gas) resulting in
the foul odours normally associated with garbage dumps.
<P>
Methane as a gas contributes significantly to the greenhouse effect
and contributes 6 times more to global warming than does carbon
dioxide on a molecule for molecule basis. For this reason there
is an advantage in burning this methane to produce energy, which
although producing carbon dioxide has less impact on the greenhouse
effect.
<P>
The decomposition of garbage commences soon after collection with
the initial process being aerobically activated and the gases
produced consisting mainly of carbon dioxide. Once the garbage
has been compacted into the landfill the remaining oxygen is consumed
and anaerobic conditions prevail. This is then suitable, providing
moisture is present, for the production of methane.
<P>
The technology for using landfill gas as a fuel source for power
generation, using gas turbines or engines is well established.
In 1975, the USA started utilising landfill gas at Palos Verdes
in southern California and since then more than 70 sites have
been developed. In Germany more than 50 sites now exploit this
gas and in Britain there are 24 commercial schemes drawing gas
from 18 locations with a further 26 schemes either in advanced
planning stages or under construction.
<P>
In the Sydney region there are two projects presently underway.
The first located at Merrylands was originally the site of an
old brickworks excavation which was filled with approximately
700,000 tonnes of garbage between 1979 and 1985 and now produces
about 700 cubed metres per hour of landfill gas. Most of this
site has now been dressed with soil and landscaped. About 7 years
ago the then Waste Management Authority began selling this gas
to the local brick works for firing its kilns. More recently,
however, the brickworks have ceased operation and a 165kW engine
and generator have now been installed to utilise the gas for generating
electricity. This project has been a joint effort between Prospect
Electricity, Waste Management Authority and Pacific Power and
will provide valuable operating experience for future use of this
technology.
<P>
The second project located at Lucas Heights, south-west of Sydney,
is planned to be larger than the Merrylands project and will be
built, owned and operated by a private company as a commercial
venture. There is estimated to be at least 0.5 PJ per annum (initially
some 3000 cubed metres per hour) of gas at this location which
is sufficient to generate on average 5 MW of electricity over
the next 15 years. 
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
