<HTML>

<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Roger Buck">
<TITLE>Alternative Technologies Chapter 6</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#6b238e"
ALINK="#00ff00">


<H3>NEW AND ALTERNATIVE TECHNOLOGIES FOR ELECTRICITY GENERATION</H3>
<HR>

<H4>Chapter 6 </H4>

<H4>Technology for Environmental Control</H4>

<MENU>
<LI>6.1 Flue Gas Desulphurisation
<MENU>
<LI>6.1.1 Wet Scrubbing
<LI>6.1.2 Spray Dry Scrubbing
<LI>6.1.3 Sorbent Injection
</MENU>

<LI>6.2 Control of Gaseous Oxides of Nitrogen
<LI>6.3 Fabric Filter Gas Cleaning
<MENU>
<LI>6.3.1 Mechanical Shaker Fabric Filters
<LI>6.3.2 Reverse Gas Fabric Filters
<LI>6.3.3 Pulse Jet Fabric Filters
</MENU>

</MENU>

<P>

<P>
Pacific Power is highly committed to the development and implementation
of technologies which improve the environmental acceptability
of power stations. To date Pacific Power's concern for the environment
has seen significant firsts in emission control and in the reduction
to the point of 'zero discharges' of waste water from power station
sites.
<P>
Combustion of fossil fuels inevitably generates carbon dioxide
which is a highly significant greenhouse gas and there are no
reasonable procedures or technologies for retaining carbon dioxide
within the power station. There are, however, new power station
technologies which help to provide an improvement through higher
efficiency and hence smaller output of carbon dioxide per unit
of energy generated.
<P>
In addition to this, fuel selection can influence the amount of
carbon dioxide produced. Carbon dioxide emissions decrease with
decreasing carbon to hydrogen ratio in the fuel; accordingly from
coal to oil to gas and ultimately hydrogen. Consequently, moisture
in the combustion gases is increased for higher hydrogen content
fuels. Naturally this is one factor which favours the use of natural
gas as a replacement fuel for coal and oil and the development
of hydrogen as a fuel for transport.
<P>
Another serious but technically manageable factor is the emission
of pollutants into the atmosphere. Each year consumption of fossil
fuels worldwide releases an estimated 80 million tonnes of nitrogen
oxides, 140 million tonnes of sulphur dioxide, 300 million tonnes
of dust and similarly large amounts of hydrocarbons.
<P>
With the burden on the environment, industrialised countries are
implementing counter measures and it is the introduction of new
technologies, improved efficiencies and government policies that
the problem is now being addressed.
<H4>6.1 Flue Gas Desulphurisation</H4>

<P>
Acid rain is the subject of considerable concern throughout the
world, particularly in Europe where it is now regarded as fact
that pollutants play a major part in the current damage to lakes
and forests. In New South Wales, however, the low sulphur content
of locally mined coal, which the Commission uses, significantly
reduces missions of sulphur dioxide in flue gases. Pacific Power
has participated in a study under the National, Energy, Research,
Development and Demonstration programme to analyse the acidity
of precipitation in the Hunter region. The study concluded that
precipitation acidity was equivalent to or slightly greater than
background.
<P>
Pacific Power maintains a watching brief on technologies for sulphur
control as well as the associated capital and operating costs
of such facilities. The most common flue gas desulphurisation
technology available (scrubbing devices) can add up to 40% to
the investment value of a conventional coal fired power station.
A brief description of the more relevant technologies follows.
<H5>6.1.1 Wet Scrubbing</H5>

<P>
Perhaps the most widely used technology for the desulphurisation
of flue gases is 'Wet Scrubbing'. The technology employs an alkaline
sorbent slurry which is predominantly lime or limestone based.
A 'scrubbing vessel' or scrubber is located downstream of the
boiler in which intimate contact between gas and sorbent is carried
out, a process which readily removes over 90% of sulphur dioxide
from the flue gases. The resulting solid is predominantly calcium
sulphite which can be further oxidised to be sold as a by-product
to the building industry where it finds application as plaster
board. Wet scrubbing technology is currently in place in over
300 coal-fired installations worldwide with at least another 100
units planned to be constructed in the foreseeable future.
<H6>Figure 6.1 - Flue Gas Desulphurisation Wet Scrubbing</H6>

<P>
The capital cost of new ($250/kW) or retrofitted ($400/kW) equipment
is considerable and is a function of the sulphur content of the
fuel source, chlorine levels (which may require an additional
pre-scrubber) and often land space available. Design considerations
which lead to such high costs include:
<P>
. size of equipment (e.g. 'scrubber') in order to handle voluminous
<P>
quantities of flue gas;
<P>
. material selection to handle the wet and corrosive nature of
<P>
material;
<P>
. incorporation of equipment into the boiler flue gas path;
<P>
. ancillary equipment which must also be of high quality to handle
<P>
corrosive sorbent and by-product;
<P>
Operating cost components include:
<UL>
<LI>purchase of sorbent materials
<LI>maintenance
<LI>disposal of wastes
<LI>additional cost of fuel to account for reduced overall plant
efficiency by 3.8% of total electrical output
</UL>

<P>
Modern 'wet scrubbers' use sorbents efficiently which they purchase
for reasonably low prices. The by-product produced is potentially
saleable although it is expected that in European countries the
construction/building industry may become flooded with gypsum
reducing its saleable value. Finally, recent developments in this
technology for example, regenerative flue gas reheating and natural
draft cooling towers are looking at increasing overall efficiency
to minimise operating costs.
<H5>6.1.2 Spray Dry Scrubbing</H5>

<P>
This technology as with 'wet scrubbing' employs a sorbent slurry
or solution, however, the by-product produced is 'dry'. The slurry
of sorbent, again alkaline based, is sprayed into the scrubbing
vessel in very fine droplets and dries as it contacts the flue
gas. At this point the sorbent reacts with the sulphur dioxide.
<P>
The dry sorbent is picked up by the gas stream and carried into
the dust collection plant (e.g. fabric filters) for removal.
<P>
Spray dry scrubbing has been installed in over 80 power station
installations worldwide making it the second most popular flue
gas desulphurisation technology available. Currently capital costs
are only slightly less than for wet scrubbing systems, whilst
removal efficiencies of up to 90% have been quoted.
<P>
Operating costs are noticeably higher than for 'wet scrubbers'
because of the reduced contact between sorbent and gas. Lime rather
than limestone is the preferred sorbent although more costly.
Because of the cost structure of this technology it is more suited
when burning low to medium sulphur coals. Another disadvantage
with 'spray dry scrubbing' is that there is no commercial use
for the by-product produced, since it is mixed with the dust originating
in the coal and collected in the dust collecting plant. Of course
this may also prevent the sale of fly ash to existing markets
such as for concrete.
<H5>6.1.3 Sorbent Injection</H5>

<P>
The technology of calcium sorbent injection is a more recently
developed technology and is the lowest in terms of capital outlay
of all the available sulphur dioxide removal technologies.
<P>
The sorbent can be added dry into one of three locations;
<UL>
<LI>with the fuel, thus into the furnace (gas temperature 850-1250
degrees Celsius)
<LI>into the economiser region (gas temperature 950-550 degrees
Celsius)
<LI>after the air heaters (gas temperature close to saturation).
<MENU>
<LI>However, because of relatively poor contact between the sorbent
and sulphur dioxide, efficiency is generally in the range 30-60%
and hence, sorbent use is much higher. The residual sorbent and
ash mixture is not a commercial product as with 'wet scrubbing'.
<LI>The technology has found a niche market for small boilers
with less stringent environmental controls than are imposed on
large utilities, or where the ash content of the coal is sufficiently
alkaline in itself to assist in the sulphur dioxide removal process.
<LI>Considerable research of the technology is underway with efficiencies
expected to reach as high as 80% should techniques like humidification
of the flue gas or other additives into the gas stream prove successful.
<LI>Due to Pacific Power's commitment to the use of fabric filter
technology for particulate control on coal-fired power stations,
direct sorbent injection was identified as being an attractive
alternative to more complex wet flue gas desulphurisation systems.
A study is currently deing conducted by Pacific Power to investigate
the feasibility of the large scale use of direct sorbent injection
upstream of fabric filter plant for sulphur dioxide reduction.
<LI>A pilot has been constructed which utilises flue gas diverted
from an operating 660 MW(e) power station boiler into a 160 bag
fabric filter pilot test plant. The plant consists of a sorbent
storage silo, volumetric feeder, pneumatic conveying and injection
equipment along with oxygen and sulphur dioxide monitoring equipment
upstream of the sorbent injector, immediately prior to the bags
and downstream of the filter bags.
<LI>Preliminary testing has been conducted using industrial grade
Calcium Hydroxide as the sorbent material, no flue gas humidification
and 'as-found' inlet sulphur dioxide concentrations. The results
have demonstrated removal efficiencies in excess of 60% at high
dosing rates are possible.
<LI>Although the previously discussed sulphur removal technologies
are proven, new technologies such as pressurised fluidised bed
combustors as well as integrated gasification and combined cycle
plants (as discussed earlier in sections 2.1.4 and 2.3.2 respectively)
provide similarly clean exhaust gases by reducing sulphur dioxide
formation prior to or during the combustion process.
</MENU>

</UL>

<H4>6.2 Control Of Gaseous Oxides Of Nitrogen</H4>

<P>
In coal and oil-fired power stations with conventional combustion
systems, the measures to reduce emissions must be taken largely
by cleaning the flue gas. Environmental measures for removing
pollutants from the flue gas can be very expensive and depending
on the quality of the coal and location of the plant can increase
overall investment by up to 40%. The principal measures carried
out to control nitrogen oxides in the combustion chamber of a
power station involves strict control of air and fuel supply to
the burners. Up to a 50% reduction in nitrogen oxides emissions
can be achieved in this way and at relatively low cost.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
There are as many as five stable gaseous oxides of nitrogen but
of these the only ones present in the atmosphere in significant
amounts are nitrous oxide, nitric oxide and nitrogen dioxide.
These three gases are potential atmospheric pollutants.
<P>
Nitric oxide is a colourless gas. Its ambient concentration is
usually much less than that which leads to biological toxicity
in terms of human health. Nitric oxide is, however, a precursor
to an active gaseous compound in the formation of photochemical
smog, nitrogen dioxide. Nitrogen dioxide is a reddish-brown gas
and in sufficient concentration visible to the eye. The toxicological
and epidemiological effects of nitrogen dioxide are not fully
understood and unless present in extremely high concentrations
does not affect human health. Environmental emission standards
for this gas are often based on visibility effects.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
Where environmental limits cannot be achieved using this method,
DENOX units are required as secondary measures. The only process
applied so far on a large scale, has been selective catalytic
reduction (SCR) using ammonia or ammonia compounds in the presence
of a catalyst. A schematic of this process is shown in Figure
6.2.
<P>
Figure 6.2 - Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR) for Reduction
of
<P>
Oxides of Nitrogen Emissions
<P>
The ammonia is injected at about 450 degrees celsius in the presence
of a vanadium pentoxide catalyst (titanium dioxide catalysts have
also been used successfully). Reduction of nitrogen oxides in
the flue gas of more than 80% is possible and in conjunction with
burner management systems can be increased to over 90% removal.
The cost of employing this technology can be up to 10 times greater
than burner control and efficiency management systems however
removal efficiency is much higher.
<P>
The amount of nitrogen oxides produced from the combustion of
two different fuel types can vary significantly if the nitrogen
content of the raw fuel is different. As shown in Figure 6.3,
fuel oil which contains nitrogen chemically bound into its molecular
structure gives rise to higher levels of nitrogen oxides emissions
than does natural gas which contains none.
<H6>Figure 6.3 - Gas Turbines - Oxides of Nitrogen Emissions</H6>

<P>
SCR has been applied in Japan and throughout Europe and is fast
gaining acceptance in industrialised countries worldwide. In Germany
alone, over 25 000 MW of coal-fired power stations are expected
to be using this technology by the early 1990's.
<H4>6.3 Fabric Filter Gas Cleaning</H4>

<P>
The flue gas discharged from a power plant boiler carries fly
ash (residue from the coal burned in the boiler). The amount of
this residue (in the form of solid particles which can be discharged
in to the atmosphere) with the flue gas is limited by the Regulations
of The Clean Air Act.
<P>
The Clean Air Act makes it necessary to provide plant between
the boiler and the stack to remove the fly ash from the flue gas
so that the total mass of solid particles actually passing into
the atmosphere is not greater than the amount permitted by the
Act.
<P>
Flue gas cleaning plant may consist of either fabric filters or
precipitators. The plant extends from the boiler discharge flanges
(located after the air heaters), to the inlet flange on the stack.
The fabric filter or bag house operates in a similar manner to
a domestic vaccuum cleaner.
<P>
There are three basic types of fabric filters designated by the
cleaning mode adopted. They are:
<MENU>
<LI>(i) Mechanical Shaker
<LI>(ii) Reverse Gas
<LI>(iii) Pulse Jet
</MENU>

<P>
For all of these types, the fabric is installed in the form of
tube like bags.
<H5>6.3.1 Mechanical Shaker Fabric Filters</H5>

<P>
Mechanical Shaker cleaned units operate on the principle of the
bags being suspended from a shaker frame with the open end of
the bags facing down. These are attached to a cell plate which
separates the 'dirty' gas side from the 'clean' gas side of the
fabric filter compartment.
<P>
As dirty gas is filtered in the bags, the differential pressure
across the plant will gradually rise, requiring the bags to be
cleaned. This is accomplished by sequentially isolating the individual
cells and energising the associated shaker mechanisms, shaking
the bags and causing the ash to fall into the hoppers. The ash
is continually discharged from the hoppers into the disposal system.
<P>
The gas enters from below the cell plate, (through thimbles protruding
through the cell plate) passes up through the centre of the bags
and deposits fly ash on the inside of the bags. The clean gas
passes through the bags and discharges through outlet dampers
at the top of the cell. The filtered flue gas enters an outlet
manifold that joins other similar ducts and is discharged through
induced draft fans to the stack.
<P>
Fabrics used in shaker plants are normally woven from synthetic
polymer fibres such as acrylics, polyesters, etc. Pacific Power
plant of this design characteristically have between 47 360 and
52 480 bags per (660 MW) unit divided into 40 individual cells.
<P>
The bags are 5.5 m long and 165 mm diameter and handle between
890 and 1090 m cubed metres per second of flue gas. Inlet burdens
average 25 g per cubed metre while outlet emissions range from
20 to 30 mg per cubed metre.
<P>
This type of plant is often described as a low-ratio filter as
it has a relatively large fabric area compared to the amount of
gas being cleaned.
<H5>6.3.2 Reverse Gas Fabric Filters</H5>

<P>
Reverse Gas cleaned fabric filters are very similar to mechanical
shaker plant. The cleaning method differs when a cell is taken
off line for cleaning. Instead of activating a mechanical shaker
mechanism, 'clean' gas from the discharge side of the filter is
drawn into the clean side of the cell undergoing cleaning. This
gas passes from the 'clean' to the 'dirty' side of the bags, dislodging
the collected fly ash in a 'back washing' operation. This type
of filter is also known as a low-ratio filter and is usually designed
along similar sizing parameters to shaker plant. The cleaning
operation is much more gentle relative to shaker plant. The fabric
traditionally used in reverse gas units is woven fibreglass.
<P>
Reverse gas plants are widely used in American power stations
as the fibreglass bags are suitable for gas at a higher temperature
than generally expected in New South Wales power stations. This
is due to the high sulphur coal in the USA and the necessity to
reduce corrosion caused by the formation of acid if condensation
occurs.
<H5>6.3.3 Pulse Jet Cleaned Plant</H5>

<P>
Pulse jet plants have a cell plate located above the bags and
the gas passes through the bags from outside to inside. The fly
ash is deposited on the outside of the bag.
<P>
Cleaning of the bags is carried out by passing a short burst of
compressed air down the centre of the bags which causes them to
flex, dislodging the fly ash from the outside of the bag.
<P>
As this plant cleans bags on-line it is not necessary to provide
equipment for cell isolation to clean the bags.
<P>
Pacific Power plant of the pulse jet design are characteristically
equipped with between 9120 and 14664 bags, varying in length from
6 m to 8 m, and a nominal diameter of 130 mm. Gas volumes range
from 480 cubed metres per second to 550 cubed metres per second
with similar inlet burdens and emission figures to low-ratio plants.
<P>
Because of the much smaller amount of fabric area required to
clean a given amount of gas, these plants are known as high-ratio
and are significantly cheaper to build and to run.
<P>
All power stations which have been commissioned in NSW since 1981
have fabric filters installed for particulate emission control.
Retrofitting of fabric filters to a number of older boilers in
our system is currently taking place. In all of the fabric filters
currently used by Pacific Power, the concept of Best Available
Control Technology has been vital. All of the installations to
date and those in progress have been very effective in the elimination
of visible emissions from power station chimneys. This is a significant
factor in the public acceptance of power stations as part of this
local community. 
</BODY>

