<MENU>
<LI>Water 675t/h 915t/h 565t/h
<LI>Consumption
</MENU>

<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<H3>Developments</H3>

<P>
The main thrust of IGCC development is to build plant of comparable
capital cost to pulverised coal plant but achieve higher efficiencies.
It is claimed that existing IGCC systems have a similar capital
cost to pulverised coal systems fitted with flue gas desulphurisation.
Designed to achieve up to 43% efficiency (HHV) it is expected
to reach 45% (HHV) in the event that development of hot gas cleaning
technology is a success.
<P>
Apart from a number of pilot units, one large demonstration power
station with integrated coal gasification has been built so far:
the 100 MW(e) Southern California Edison power station in Cool
Water, USA operated successfully between 1984 and 1989 and has
been acknowledged as one of the cleanest coal based power stations
in the USA. Buggenum in the Netherlands, rated at 250 MW(e) will
be commissioned in 1993 and is designed to operate with an efficiency
of 41.4% (HHV).
<P>
Figure 2.8 - Integrated Gasification Combined Cycle.
<MENU>
<LI>2.4 Fuel Cells
<LI>The fuel cell operates by directly converting the chemical
energy in a fuel to electrical energy through an electrochemical
process. It consists of two electrodes separated by an electrolyte
(fluid capable of conducting an electric current) and electrically
connected through an external circuit.
<LI>Figure 2.9 - Fuel Cell.
<LI>Fuel cells offer considerable benefits as a future power source
due to high efficiencies in the range of 50-60% as well as quiet
and versatile operation. They are predicted to be serious contenders
for both central power stations and dispersed power generation
at load centres. Suitable fuels include methanol, natural gas
and gasified coal.
<LI>A fuel is supplied continuously to one electrode, where it
is oxidised, (i.e. burnt) and an oxidant (air) is supplied at
the other electrode where it is reduced. The electrolyte enables
flow of ions between the two electrodes. Fuel cell types are generally
classified by the type of electrolyte used.
<LI>(i) Phosphoric Acid Fuel Cells (PAFC) - these are currently
the most developed and field tested fuel cell systems to date.
A 4.5 MW(e) and an 11 MW(e) demonstration plant have been successfully
operated. The temperature of operation of the cell is about 200
degrees Celsius and waste heat recovery can be used for low temperature
applications. These low temperature fuel cells generally use hydrogen
as the fuel source.
<LI>(ii) Molten Carbonate Fuel Cells (MCFC) - these are less developed
than the phosphoric acid fuel cells. They operate at about 650
degrees Celsius with an efficiency of 55-60%, and the potential
to recover the waste heat generated for combined cycle operation.
Natural gas can be reacted directly in such a facility because
of the high temperature of operation. The development of MCFC
is at an advanced stage but several serious material problems
relating to degradation and stability of cell components still
needs to be investigated and resolved.
<LI>(iii) Solid Oxide Fuel Cells (SOFC) - these use ceramic electrolytes
based on zirconia, and operate at about 1000 degrees Celsius.
Experimental SOFCs have been demonstrated, and industry experts
predict megawatt size installations with energy densities of 1
MW/m3 and operation at 50-60% efficiency within a decade. Because
of the high temperature of operation they will be suited for combined
cycle operation where the unreacted fuel leaving the fuel cell
is augmented and combusted in a gas turbine. As the temperature
of exhaust gases is of the order of 500 to 900 degrees Celsius,
the waste heat can be used to generate steam. It is expected that
such an arrangement could achieve an overall efficiency of close
to 80% with waste heat recovery.
<LI>A marketing report prepared for the CSIRO indicates that SOFC's
would be particularly attractive for meeting the energy needs
of non-residential buildings. In this application natural gas
fuelled units of between 100 kW(e) and a few megawatts, would
reduce carbon dioxide emissions significantly and be viable where
capital cost is less than $2000/kW inclusive of all power conditioning
equipment.
<LI>Some of the inherent advantages of operating fuel cells as
power supplies includes their flexibility in utilising a wide
variety of fuel sources (gasified coal, oil, gas, hydrogen, methanol),
their silent operating characteristics particularly attractive
in building installations, their modular construction allowing
cost effective increases in capacity and the potentially high
efficiency in the conversion of chemical energy into electricity.
<LI>Pacific Power has recently joined a consortium which established
a new joint-venture company, Ceramic Fuel Cells Ltd. to develop
SOFC's. The ultimate objective is the development of the technology
for application to large central and dispersed power stations
for use within grids.
<LI>2.5 Magnetohydrodynamics
<LI>Magnetohydrodynamic (MHD) energy conversion is a process where
heat can be converted directly into electricity. The basic principle
by which electricity is generated is by moving a conductor through
a magnetic field. Thus, in the case of a conventional electricity
generator, using a turbogenerator, a coil of conductor is rotated
in a stationary magnetic field, or a magnetic field is rotated
in a cage of stationary conductors, namely copper or aluminium
bars.
<LI>Figure 2.10 - Open Cycle MHD Plant.
<LI>In the MHD generator, the combustion gas itself is an electrical
conductor. The gas is usually derived from the high temperature
combustion of coal. The combustion products produced are so hot
that they become electrically conducting, ie. a plasma. The ability
of the gas to conduct electricity is increased by &quot;seeding&quot;
it with a salt of readily ionisable alkali metal such as potassium
or caesium. This hot gas expands at high velocity through an intense
magnetic field via a long, narrow, divergent channel or nozzle.
An electric potential is induced between two opposite walls of
the generator and electric power can be extracted.
<LI>In both cases (conventional and MHD generators) the motion
of a conductor through a magnetic field gives rise to an electromotive
force and a flow of current in accordance with Faraday's laws
of induction. In a conventional generator, the current is carried
to the external load circuit through brushes. In the MHD generator
electrodes mounted in the channel walls tap off the current directly.
Thus for MHD, the energy released by the expanding hot gases is
converted directly to electricity without the use of rotating
machinery hence reducing mechanical losses.
<LI>When a conductor is placed in a magnetic field and a current
passed through it perpendicular to the field, a voltage is set
up perpendicular to both the field and current directions. This
phenomenon is known as the Hall effect, and the transverse voltage
developed is called the Hall voltage.
<LI>If a continuous electrode were used along the wall of a linear
MHD generator, Hall current would flow in the plasma, seriously
degrading performance. For this reason electrodes are segmented,
ie. there are a large number of electrodes separated by insulators
along the channel. With segmentation a voltage can develop between
adjacent electrodes because of the Hall effect.
<LI>The flue gas from the MHD process can be directed to a waste
heat boiler for steam raising or be passed to a gas turbine for
direct electricity generation. In both cases the efficiency of
the overall process can be significantly enhanced recovering energy
which would otherwise be exhausted to atmosphere.
<LI>An alternative to the linear MHD system described has been
developed as a result of technical problems associated with linear
systems on a commercial scale. Known as MHD disk generators they
avoid problems of the linear type such as superconducting magnets
of commercial scale are complex, expensive and of a size which
would make transport to site a difficult task. Cooling systems
as well as power consolidation systems and inverter system are
also less complex and expensive.
<LI>The MHD - disk generator has an overall simpler construction
than the linear system and benefits from less components under
high electrical potential and unbroken plasma flow.
<LI>By installing an MHD generator as a topping plant (installed
upstream of a secondary process which can also generate electricity),
overall efficiencies of up to 45% may be achievable with established
technology, reaching 50-55% with second generation development
and triple cycle configuration. Triple cycle refers to combined
MHD/gas turbine/steam plant. Size of MHD plant when used as a
topping cycle is in the range 25 MW(e) to 1000 MW(e).
<LI>Pacific Power has recently sponsored research at the University
of Sydney into a design study for retrofitting of MHD technology
at an existing power station.
<LI>2.6 Ultra Clean Coal (UCC)
<LI>Coal, in its natural form consists of carbon, hydrogen and
oxygen with traces of contaminants bound into the atomic structure,
as well as inert material known generally as ash. Because coal
typically contains from 10 to 30% ash by weight, its use as a
fuel is restricted to more conventional, coal-fired boilers. If
the inert material or ash content can be removed from the coal
such that less than 0.5% of ash remains, a new class of fuel,
ultra clean coal, can be produced and considered for a variety
of other uses, in particular as a replacement for liquid petroleum
fuels.
</MENU>

<H3>The Process</H3>

<P>
Physical processes for the removal of ash from coal have been
developed over the years to improve its quality for combustion
in conventional processes. In order to remove a high percentage
of ash from the coal by physical methods, large expensive and
cumbersome industrial plants need to be constructed.
<P>
A process for the chemical cleaning of coal, pioneered by the
CSIRO, is currently under development in Australia.
<P>
Figure 2.11 - Ultra Clean Coal Technology.
<P>
It is expected that this process will reduce the ash in coal to
less than 0.5% at a competitive cost and hence broaden the technologies
for which coal would be a substitute fuel.
<P>
The chemical cleaning process, which is currently under development
involves a number of distinct processing stages. Generally these
stages can be described as: caustic digestion of the mineral matter,
followed by acid neutralisation and finally water washing. The
reagents which are used throughout the process can be regenerated
for re-use in the process. Whilst being environmentally sound
and avoiding problems with waste disposal of chemicals this also
reduces the cost of the overall process and hence the finished
product.
<P>
The commercial success of the process for producing UCC will see
some very distinct benefits particularly in the area of electricity
generation. Some of these benefits include:
<P>
. increased export earnings through shipping a more versatile
fuel
<P>
to other countries resulting in their reduced dependence on gas
<P>
and petroleum products in electricity generation
<P>
. reduced transport and shipping costs for a fuel which can be
up to 30% lighter than raw coal from the mine;
<P>
. the ability to transport UCC through pipelines as a preference
to coal moved by rail or road transport. This being cheaper, less
congestive to our roads and environmentally sound.
<P>
. The development of high quality carbon anodes for use in the
production of aluminium.
<P>
. Development of advanced combustion technologies for more efficient
generation of electricity.
<P>
A pilot UCC plant co-funded by Pacific Power, was constructed
with production of tonnage quantities of UCC. The demonstration
project was erected on the site of the old Ulan Power Station
near Mudgee in central western NSW. The technical feasibility
of producing UCC was demonstrated during these trials.
<P>
The pilot plant has now been moved to the ACIRL laboratories at
Maitland where further development is being carried out by a consortium
of Australian interests.
<P>
A second project being considered, jointly with the production
of UCC, involves the development of a Clean Coal Engine. It is
envisaged that in order to develop this technology a modified
'coal burning' gas turbine will have to be constructed and tested
using UCC.
<MENU>
<LI>2.7 Underground (In-Situ) Coal Gasification (UCG)
<LI>Underground coal gasification is the process by which coal
is partially burned without being mined, and the heat generated
by the combustion decomposes and gasifies additional coal to produce
a combustible gaseous fuel. The benefit of this process is that
coal seams which are poor in quality and/or expensive to mine
can still be utilised by converting the coal into gas. Development
of UCG is quite recent and a great deal of interest in the technology
has already been shown worldwide.
<LI>The simplest type of underground gasification requires drilling
a well into a coal seam to inject oxygen containing gases whilst
another well is drilled to remove the gaseous products. The process
has two stages, the first being an ignition and linking stage
and the second a gasification stage.
<LI>Figure 2.12 - Underground Coal Gasification.
<LI>In the first stage the injection and production wells are
connected using a linking technique such as a horizontal borehole
or reverse combustion (i.e. fire and injection gases travel in
opposite directions). This stage produces a path of increased
permeability between the injection and production wells. At shallow
depths linked vertical wells may be used where it is possible
to establish linkage. At greater depths or where linkage is more
difficult to establish deflected 'horizontal' bores may be used.
<LI>Once the gasification channel is established and combustion
commenced, air or oxygen rich gases are injected and the gasification
zone progresses gradually toward the production well.
<LI>If air is injected as the oxidant, the product has a low heating
value (3 to 7 MJ/Nm3) due to the presence of nitrogen in the product
gas. If however oxygen and steam are injected, the product has
a medium heating value (8 to 11 MJ/Nm3 as compared to 38 MJ/Nm3
for natural gas). The product gas generally contains carbon monoxide,
hydrogen and methane.
<LI>The product gas may be used to fire a boiler to raise steam
or to fuel a gas turbine for generation of electricity. The product
gas can also be further refined to produce chemicals or liquid
fuels. The cost to produce gas using UCG compared to using a surface
gasifier is much lower due to the fact that mining and coal handling
equipment, as well as, surface gasifiers are not required.
<LI>Developments overseas include industrial scale operation in
the USSR since the 1950's and numerous demonstrations in the USA
to confirm technical feasibility, particularly since the 1972
oil price crisis. Testing has been curtailed in more recent years
due to fuel price declines and increased availability of both
natural gas and petroleum. However, with instability of oil prices
in more recent times, development of this technology could once
again takeoff. There are no commercial operations currently in
the USA or Australia.
<LI>The process has been shown to be technically feasible and
is appropriate where coal is not mineable by conventional means.
Areas have been identified in NSW with coal resources suitable
for UCG. However, a period of up to 10 years may be required to
prove the potential of these specific areas and develop experience
in the technology in Australia.
<LI>2.8 Geothermal Energy
<LI>The flow of heat from within the earth to the surface averages
0.06 W/m2 and is attributable to two factors: the process of the
earth cooling down and newly generated heat as a result of natural
radioactive decay in the earth's crust. Estimates show that the
latter is probably the more significant factor. Since this heat
liberation is not evenly distributed across the surface of the
earth, geothermal anomalies can lend themselves to economic utilisation.
Such anomalies are found mainly but not exclusively in areas with
active volcanoes.
<LI>Figure 2.13 provides a schematic diagram of a geothermal reservoir.
Depending on the temperature of the heat discharged, such reservoirs
may be subdivided into various categories:
<UL>
<LI>hot-steam reservoirs (e.g. the oldest source of this type
in operation is in the Italian town of Larderello operated since
1904);
<LI>hot-water reservoirs (e.g. Wairakei, New Zealand, Cerro Prieto,
Mexico, and in Iceland);
<LI>warm-water reservoirs with temperatures below 100 degrees
Celsius (e.g. Birdsville, Queensland).
</UL>

</MENU>

<P>
Of the energy stored, approximately 25% can be extracted in the
case of hot-steam reservoirs and about 1% in the case of hot-water
reservoirs.
<P>
There are also hot dry rock reservoirs which store by far the
most geothermal energy but have to be developed first by the artificial
creation of crevices and the insertion of water as a heat carrier.
This concept is still in the experimental stage.
<P>
Figure 2.13 - Geothermal Energy for Power Generation.
<H3>Use and Potential</H3>

<P>
Geothermal energy is used for generating electricity and for heating.
In steam and hotwater reservoirs the steam obtained is used directly
for driving turbines. In warm-water reservoirs steam is generated
via a second, closed circuit using low boiling point gases such
as isobutane or ammonia, as the working fluid. The principles
are based on the Rankine cycle; the organic gas being passed through
an expansion turbine/engine. The resulting mechanical energy is
used to generate electricity. Overall design and economy of a
geothermal installation is site specific depending greatly on
the quality and quantity of energy in the reservoir.
<P>
About 1% of the global heat flow is concentrated in geothermal
energy. Geothermal heat is not an immediately renewable source
of energy if a power station extracts more heat from a reservoir
than the adjacent rock can provide.
<P>
Figure 2.14 shows the rated output capacity of major geothermal
facilities currently installed in various countries. The largest
and most successful plant so far is The Geysers in the USA where
several power stations with a total installed capacity of 2000
MW(e) are fed from 250 geothermal sources.
<P>
Figure 2.14 - Number of major geothermal power stations installed
<P>
worldwide (Sept 1986)
<H3>Environmental Considerations</H3>

<P>
The main problem in the use of geothermal energy is that the steam
or water flowing from the artesian bore contains partly aggressive
gases and minerals. Up to a maximum of 26% of the water is made
up of dissolved solids, the average being about 3%. These impurities
cause corrosion and deposits in turbines and heat exchangers and
may also be a burden on the environment.
<P>
General repercussions for the environment include:
<UL>
<LI>the amount of heat discharged is 23 times greater than conventional
power stations;
<LI>the problem of harmful waste waters can be solved in part
by re-injection into the reservoir;
<LI>the amount of sulphur released in the Geysers field by way
of exhaust gases is comparable to the discharge of sulphur by
conventional power stations, a further factor being the unpleasant
smell of other gases including hydrogen sulphide;
<LI>with steam containing a large amount of water, the process
of separation of water from steam may cause significant noise,
requiring good sound insulation.
<MENU>
<LI>2.9 Nuclear Fission
</MENU>

</UL>

<H3>Nuclear Power in NSW</H3>

<P>
The &quot;Uranium Mining and Nuclear Facilities (Prohibitions)
Act, 1986, No. 194&quot; Section 9 prohibits the Electricity Commission
of New South Wales from constructing, operating or approving a
nuclear reactor for the purposes of generating electricity. This
discussion of nuclear power generation is included for completeness
in the context of alternative and emerging technologies for power
generation.
<H3>The Status of Nuclear Power Fission</H3>

<P>
Electricity was first generated by a nuclear power station in
1951 at the &quot;Experimental Breeder Reactor 1&quot; in Idaho.
Since then nuclear power stations have become a major electricity
source. In 1988, 430 nuclear power stations were in operation,
producing 16% of the world's electrical energy (17 000 TWh). Nuclear
power stations have mostly large units typically 600-1300 MW(e)
in size. The USA has the greatest nuclear capacity, followed by
France, the USSR, Japan and Germany. At over 70%, France has the
greatest proportion of nuclear energy in their generation capacity.
<MENU>
<LI>2.9.1 Types of Nuclear Power Stations
<LI>The fission process which produces the heat required for a
conventional steam cycle occurs when the nucleus of a Uranium
235 atom is split in two after colliding with a neutron. As well
as a large amount of heat being generated, an average of 2.5 neutrons
are released per collision, one of these then moving on to continue
the fission process, and thus sustain the reaction. The 1.5 neutrons
which don't continue in the fission reaction are absorbed by nuclei.
<LI>The heat produced during the fission reaction, is transferred
to a fluid which may be a gas or liquid for example, air, helium,
carbon dioxide, molten salt, water, liquid metal (sodium), or
an organic liquid. This hot fluid then transfers its heat to a
conventional steam cycle from which electricity can be generated.
</MENU>

<H3>Light-Water Reactors</H3>

<P>
There are two forms of light water reactors; pressurised water
reactors (PWR) and less commonly boiling water reactors (BWR).
These reactors use light water as a coolant as opposed to a heavy
water cooled reactor which is also used to supply energy. The
boiling water reactors produce steam in the reactor core, the
saturated steam then passes directly to the turbo-generator where
the energy is recovered. In the pressurised water reactor, high
pressure liquid water is used as the reactor coolant, the water's
heat is then transferred to a secondary steam cycle which supplies
energy to a turbine and generator. Light water reactors are the
most common of the reactor types, and are likely to be for several
decades. They operate with efficiencies slightly less than conventional
fossil fuelled power stations.
<P>
A new design of light water reactor has been developed in the
USA. Known as the 'advanced' light water reactor (ALWR), it operates
with improved passive safety systems and is smaller than other
light water reactors. The reduction in the number of nuclear power
stations being constructed worldwide has slowed the implementation
of the ALWR.
<H3>High Temperature Reactors</H3>

<P>
High temperatures are possible in these reactors as the reactor
core is cooled by compressed helium gas. High temperatures of
up to 950 degrees Celsius result in relatively high efficiencies
of the order of the efficiency of fossil fuelled power stations.
<H3>Fast Breeder Reactors</H3>

<P>
In fast breeder reactors high energy neutrons cause most of the
fission events. This is in contrast to &quot;thermal&quot; reactors
where the neutrons are deliberately slowed down in the moderator,
releasing slow or &quot;thermal&quot; neutrons to the fission
process.
<P>
In the reactor, plutonium 239 is the main fuel. Depleted or natural
uranium (mostly U238) is placed as a blanket around the core.
<P>
High energy &quot;fast&quot; neutrons are necessary in breeder
reactors for the fission of the &quot;fertile&quot; uranium 238.
This in turn produces an increasing amount of plutonium 239. The
rate of production of plutonium 239 is greater than the rate of
consumption, thus the reactor is breeding fissionable fuel. This
reactor utilises the more abundant uranium 238, and could result
in total uranium reserves worldwide being extended.
<P>
Fast breeder technology is currently being promoted above all
in countries without their own uranium resources, such as France
and Japan, but also the USSR. More than 10 fast breeders are now
operating. Considering the low level of uranium prices today,
even proponents of the fast breeder do not believe that this type
of reactor can operate economically in this century.
<P>
This type of reactor is particularly suitable for the extraction
of high temperature heat for chemical processes, the gasification
of coal or the production of steam for electricity generation.
<H3>Radioactive Wastes</H3>

<P>
The nuclear fuel cycle including the production of fuel, its use
in a reactor and its subsequent disposal as waste, produces what
are termed low, medium and high level radioactive wastes.
<P>
Low level wastes are those items and materials used through the
fuel cycle which may have become contaminated. Typically this
may include cleaning equipment, gloves, clothes, tools etc. Low
level waste has similar radioactivity to uranium orebody.
<P>
Medium level wastes include fuel handling equipment, reactor equipment
and parts etc. Both low and medium radioactive wastes are disposed
of in shallow burial sites. Prior to disposal, highly toxic portions
of these wastes are separated and included for disposal with the
high level wastes.
<P>
High level wastes include fission products (spent fuel) and high
atomic mass elements artificially formed by neutron capture. This
waste emits a high level of radiation as well as a great deal
of heat. The heat mainly arising from fission products.
<P>
Quite a few countries have final storage facilities for low and
medium activity waste, however highly active waste is cooled for
years prior to storage, and as yet no final storage facilities
for highly active waste have been implemented. The following brief
descriptions indicate some of the avenues of research in this
area.
<H3>Glass Blocks in Salt Domes</H3>

<P>
The final storage method chosen by Germany is to cast the highly
active material into boron silicate glass blocks, ready for storage
in salt domes. The blocks are placed 850m underground in galleries
drilled in the salt dome. Salt domes have several characteristics
which make them suitable as final storage sites:
<MENU>
<LI>(i) they are located in proven water tight strata, by virtue
of their existence;
<LI>(ii) salt is structurally suitable to protect enclosed waste
from geological upheavals; and
<LI>(iii) salt has a good thermal conductivity allowing efficient
dissipation of heat produced by radioactive decay.
</MENU>

<P>
In spite of the above there are still problems to be considered
with salt domes such as recently small pockets of brine have been
detected in salt domes (in one case a test bore filled with water),
and the resistance of salt domes to high temperatures has been
questioned.
<P>
There is also doubt about the durability of the glass blocks when
subjected to the high temperatures and pressures experienced while
buried deep in geological formations. High temperatures and pressures
cause devitrification of glass and with water present leaching
may occur. Because of these doubts, Britain plans to keep their
glass blocks in air cooled enclosures for at least 50 years.
<H3>Synroc</H3>

<P>
Synroc (which is being developed in Australia) is a synthetic
ceramic crystalline rock, in which it is proposed to dispose of
highly active waste. The waste will be incorporated in synrocs
crystalline structure. Waste on a large scale has not yet been
incorporated in synroc and even after successful incorporation
of the waste, a 50 year testing programme will be required to
ensure the material is secure. If successful, the synroc blocks
would be stored in a stable geological structure such as granite.
Such structures are found in Australia.
<H3>Reprocessing of Fuel</H3>

<P>
Used fuel rods are reprocessed for three main reasons:
<MENU>
<LI>(i) to recover viable fuel for further use;
<LI>(ii) to recycle plutonium for use and destruction in the fission
process of a reactor;
<LI>(iii) to remove fission waste products for final storage.
</MENU>

<P>
The alternative to reprocessing is to store used fuel rods in
intermediate storage until they are cool enough for final storage.
<H3>Nuclear Energy Cost </H3>

<P>
Currently, nuclear power stations are technology intensive, resulting
in very high capital costs. Decommissioning of these power stations
at the end of their useful life is also now being identified as
a major cost. In total, electricity produced by nuclear power
stations costs of the order of three times that of electricity
produced by NSW coal-fired stations.
<MENU>
<LI>2.10 Nuclear Fusion
<LI>The aim of nuclear fusion research is to provide a new source
of energy for the industrialised world which offers significant
advantages:
<UL>
<LI>unproblematic procurement of fuel,
<LI>high energy yield,
<LI>minimum hazard,
<LI>minimum environmental pollution.
</UL>

</MENU>

<P>
Since this type of energy represents a long-term development,
it is currently not possible to make any reliable forecasts as
to the economic viability of nuclear fusion energy.
<P>
Commercial fusion power stations are not expected to be available
before the middle of next century.
<H3>Elementary Process and Fuel</H3>

<P>
The elementary process releasing energy is the fusion of two light
atomic nuclei. Fusion is counteracted by the electrostatic repulsion
of the nuclei, which can only be overcome by making them collide
with a sufficient impact, as is the case at temperatures above
100 million degrees Celsius. The requirement, therefore, is to
heat up the fusion fuel to such temperatures and to maintain it
with adequate density for sufficiently long period.
<P>
Deuterium and tritium have the highest reaction rates for nuclear
fusion. Deuterium can be extracted from water at low cost and
is therefore available in unlimited quantities. Tritium is &quot;bred&quot;
in the reactor itself out of lithium, an element found in large
quantities and well distributed in the earth's crust.
<P>
This would provide a virtually inexhaustible fuel supply, particularly
considering the very small amount of fuel required in nuclear
fusion: generation of 1 million kWh of electricity requires approximately
400t of hard coal but only 40g of lithium and 12.5g of deuterium.
<P>
An important advantage of the fusion reactor is that it does not
pollute the environment with chemically toxic substances. Rather,
the reaction product of the fusion process is helium, a chemically
inactive rare gas. None of the other processes in the fuel cycle
results in the emission of chemical contaminants either. In particular,
there is no emission of sulphur dioxide, nitrogen oxides or carbon
dioxide.
<MENU>
<LI>2.11 Dry Cooling In Power Stations
</MENU>

<H3>Future Power Station Sites in NSW</H3>

<P>
New South Wales power stations have in the past been sited close
to large coal reserves, and water supplies since these raw materials
strongly affect the economics of the electricity generated. Future
power stations may be required to make use of coal reserves which
are remote from sufficient water resources normally required for
cooling purposes. For this reason dry cooling technologies are
being developed such that areas which possess large quantities
of coal but little water become economically attractive as future
power generation sites.
<H3>Power Station Cooling Systems</H3>

<P>
Cooling systems are an integral part of the steam cycle of coal-fired
power stations. Their role can be described as follows:
<H3>The Basic Steam Cycle</H3>

<P>
Water is pumped into the boiler drum at high pressure and then
flows through banks of tubes into a boiler. This water is then
heated (in New South Wales the energy is provided by burning coal),
past its boiling point producing steam at a super-heat condition
of 540 degrees Celsius. When the super-heated high pressure steam
leaves the boiler, it enters an expansion turbine. The steam turns
the fan-like blades of the turbine which is, in turn connected
by a shaft to the electrical generator. This converts the rotational
mechanical power to electricity.
<P>
The spent steam exits the turbine at a low temperature (less than
50 degrees Celsius) and low pressure and is condensed using one
of the cooling systems outlined below. The resulting water is
then ready to be pumped back into the boiler drum to start the
cycle again.
<P>
Figure 2.15 - The Basic Steam Cycle.
<H3>Cooling Systems at NSW Power Stations</H3>

<P>
At present New South Wales power stations are either cooled by
using saltwater from coastal (estuarine), freshwater cooling pond
lake water or wet cooling towers, depending on the availability
of water resources at the particular site.
<P>
Limits have been placed on the maximum temperature (35 degrees
Celsius) at which cooling water can be discharged to prevent high
lake temperatures and avoiding environmental problems. Wet cooling
towers use freshwater and achieve 80% of their cooling by evaporation
of the cooling water. This evaporation represents a loss of millions
of litres of water per year. When the cost of water reaches approximately
70-90 cents/kL (depending on the location), dry cooling may become
the more attractive option for cooling. Current water costs of
Pacific Power Power Stations are of the order of 50 cents/kL.
<H3>Lake Cooling</H3>

<P>
In this system exhaust steam exiting the turbine enters the condenser.
The cooling water from the lake is pumped through a large number
of tubes which pass through the condenser box. The steam is condensed
by the cooling water and is then pumped out from the bottom of
the condenser. The cooling water is heated during this process,
and is then returned to the lake.
<H3>Wet Cooling Towers</H3>

<P>
Wet cooling towers use the same condenser system as in lake cooling,
however, the cooling water comes from a large basin at the bottom
of the cooling tower. In a natural draft cooling tower the heated
cooling water from the condenser is sprayed down the inside of
the cooling tower whilst air, under the effects of natural convection
flows up through the cooling tower. The air draft evaporates some
of the cooling water, lowering the temperature of the remaining
cooling water. The draft can also be produced by fans in an induced
draft cooling tower. A plume of pure water vapour can often be
seen exiting the top of wet cooling towers particularly when the
atmosphere has high humidity.
<H3>Figure 2.16 - Lake Cooling/ Figure 2.17 - Wet Cooling Tower
</H3>

<H3>Dry Cooling Systems</H3>

<P>
There are two main types of dry cooling technology, the direct
system and the indirect system. These systems operate similar
to car radiators, in that they use a flow of air to cool water
flowing inside finned tubes.
<H3>Indirect Dry Cooling</H3>

<P>
Indirect dry cooling towers use the same condenser system as in
lake cooling, however the cooling water is recirculated through
banks of finned tubes over which cooling air flows. The air flow
is induced in a natural draft cooling tower by convection.
<P>
If fans were used instead of the natural draft tower, a large
number of fans would be required to achieve the same heat rejection.
This is because the temperature difference between the air and
the cooling water is relatively small. The natural draft cooling
tower for dry cooling is larger than for an equivalent wet system,
since heat transfer rates are much less.
<P>
Another form of indirect cooling system is that of the 'spray'
condenser. In this system the boiler water acts also as the cooling
water and is circulated through the finned tubes for cooling.
This system is theoretically more efficient than other indirect
systems as heat transfer through tubes from the boiler water to
the cooling circuit is no longer required. In practice these condensers
have not proved to be as efficient as expected and research is
continuing. Water treatment in this case however is more critical
to maintain demineralised water quality for such a large volume.
<H3>Direct Dry Cooling</H3>

<P>
In the direct dry cooling system the turbine exhaust steam is
passed directly through finned tubes. The tubes are finned to
increase their surface area and hence cooling capability. Ambient
air is forced over these tubes with the aid of fans cooling and
condensing the steam.
<P>
The cooling system needs to be located as near as possible to
the turbine, so that the turbine operates efficiently. This also
minimises leaks which can contaminate the steam (steam pressure
is below atmospheric pressure, so leaks will allow air to flow
into the tubes). It is possible to locate a fan forced cooling
system closer to the turbine than a natural draft system. The
tube banks are located directly adjacent to the turbine hall,
minimising piping distance, and the fans are located under the
tubebanks.
<P>
Comparison of Direct vs Indirect Dry Cooling Systems. Indirect
dry cooling systems tend to have a large capital cost (due to
the large cost of the natural draft cooling tower) but low operating
cost. In comparison direct dry cooling has a low capital cost
but high operating cost (due to large power consumption of the
fans). In general, direct dry cooling is favoured at sites with
low fuel cost (the fan power is less costly), whilst indirect
dry cooling is more suitable at sites with high fuel costs.
<H3>Current Status</H3>

<P>
The largest dry cooled power stations have been constructed in
South Africa. Three power stations were built consisting of 6
units, each unit having an output in the range 660-685 MW(e):
Matimba - a direct dry cooled station, Majuba - also a direct
system and Kendal - an indirect dry cooled station. The largest
power station units in NSW are similar in size to the South African
units, hence the technology being developed for South Africa has
particular relevance to NSW developments.
<P>
Pacific Power is currently investigating the site specific nature
of corrosion and fouling of a variety of dry cooling tube types.
Because of the low heat transfer rates of dry cooling, this aspect
of their operation is critical as it may cause heat rejection
rates to vary considerably and hence affect the economics of electricity
produced.
<P>
Figure 2.18 - Indirect Dry Cooling Tower/ Figure 2.19 - Direct
Dry
<P>
Cooling Tower
<H2>CHAPTER THREE</H2>

<H3>NEW TECHNOLOGIES IN POWER GENERATION</H3>

<H4>Renewables</H4>

<H5>3.1 Wind Energy</H5>

<P>
For centuries mankind has been harnessing the power of the wind,
to propel sailing ships, pump water and, during this century,
to produce electricity. Today a major focus for wind energy is
the production of electricity for supply into the main electricity
network.
<P>
Wind turbines for producing electricity range from kilowatt sized
machines for use on yachts and at isolated homesteads to a few
machines of several megawatts that are still largely experimental.
Currently, worldwide there are more than 2000 MW(e) of installed
wind turbine capacity, roughly equivalent to about 60% of the
capacity of the Snowy Mountains Scheme. Although this is located
mainly in California, Denmark has a total installed capacity of
some 360 MW(e), comprising almost 3000 turbines and providing
about 2% of electricity demand.
<P>
Various designs of wind turbines are available.
<H3>Figure 3.1 - Typical Wind Turbine Performance Data</H3>

<P>
Several countries are operating largescale (1 to 4 MW) experimental
wind turbines. However, the most widely used machines for electricity
production are much smaller. The design concept is relatively
simple and a typical 300 kW(e) machine could have the following
features:
<P>
. three-bladed 30 metre diameter rotor rotating at 40 rpm;
<P>
. blades constructed from fibreglass or wood epoxy and which are
<P>
able to change their pitch to optimise the angle to the wind;
<P>
. hub of the rotor connected to a gearbox and induction generator,
<P>
both placed within an enclosed nacelle;
<P>
. nacelle and rotor placed on a 30 metre tower, and able to rotate
<P>
so that the wind turbine is always facing into the wind;
<P>
. able to replace the combustion of 250 tonnes of coal per year
<P>
which would supply the energy requirements of 70 NSW homes.
<P>
Today, the most economical turbines are about 300 kW - 600 kW
capacity
<P>
and could typically be located as a 'wind farm' of 3 to 6 MW(e)
total
<P>
capacity occupying approximately 2 square kilometres of land.
The wind
<P>
turbines in each farm would be operated as an integrated unit
with
<P>
connection often being into the local electricity transmission
network.
<P>
Several countries have active wind energy programs. In some countries
<P>
the cost of electricity generated by wind turbines is competitive
with
<P>
that from other forms of generation. Other countries desirous
of
<P>
achieving a portion of generation from non fossil fuel sources
have
<P>
embarked upon wind generation programs.
<P>
Proponents of wind energy claim a number of advantages in support
of
<P>
the technology in addition to the value associated with providing
<P>
energy, and some credit for capacity. These advantages include
the
<P>
following:
<P>
. the energy produced displaces combustion of fossil fuels and
hence
<P>
emissions of carbon dioxide, particulates, sulphur dioxide and
<P>
other pollutants;
<P>
. the wind is a renewable resource;
<P>
. diversification of an electricity supply system generally reduces
<P>
risk;
<P>
. some distribution systems may benefit from local generation;
<P>
. local economic and employment benefits may result.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
The relationship between wind speed, wind power and typical wind
turbine performance follows:
<P>
The power (P) available from a wind swept area (A) with wind blowing
at velocity (V) is given by the following formula.
<P>
P = 0.5 x D x A x V3
<P>
P = Wind Power (watts)
<P>
D = Air Density (kg/m3)
<P>
A = Swept Area (m2)
<P>
V = Wind Speed (m/s)
<P>
It is important to note that power is proportional to the wind
speed
<P>
cubed, and hence for relatively small increases in wind speed
large
<P>
increases in power can be observed.
<P>
Betz Limit of Wind Turbine Efficiency
<P>
There is a theoretical limit to the amount of power which can
be
<P>
extracted from the wind. This is termed the Betz limit. The Betz
<P>
limit stipulates that a perfect wind turbine can at best extract
59.3%
<P>
of the total power available. This limit was originally derived
by A.
<P>
Betz in 1927.
<P>
Modern Wind Turbine Efficiencies
<P>
At their design wind speed, modern wind turbines can extract as
much as
<P>
40% of the available power from the wind.
<P>
The amount of energy produced by a wind turbine per year depends
<P>
strongly on the selected site and the climatic conditions associated
<P>
with that site. An annual average wind speed of above 6 m/s defines
a
<P>
good wind site.
<P>
The wind turbine energy production vs. wind speed curve shows
that most
<P>
of the electrical energy is produced at wind speeds well above
the
<P>
average wind speed.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
The cost of wind generated electricity is very sensitive to the
available wind resource. For example, wind with a velocity of
8 m/s will provide more than twice the power of 6 m/s wind. In
countries with an established wind turbine manufacturing industry,
and a good wind resource, the cost of electricity from the wind
is about 5 to 7 cents/kWh (or about twice the current cost of
producing coal-fired electricity in NSW).
<P>
Several issues must be carefully assessed when planning to install
wind turbines. Wind energy is not completely environmentally benign,
only relatively so. The choice of a suitable site involves assessment
of the wind and the availability of the necessary electricity
transmission infrastructure. However, other issues must also be
addressed which are particular to wind generation:
<UL>
<LI>visual impact of the wind farm on the local community;
<LI>local noise annoyance;
<LI>electromagnetic interference;
<LI>impact on bird life;
<LI>safety aspects.
<MENU>
<LI>It is anticipated that these issues would be resolved in NSW
with appropriate planning and community consultation. As a first
step in this process Pacific Power is funding a $220,000 study
with the CSIRO Centre for Environmental Mechanics to identify
prime wind farm sites in NSW. Figure 3.2 shows areas that may
contain suitable conditions for wind generation in NSW.
<LI>Figure 3.2 - Wind Generation Study Areas in New South Wales.
<LI>It is difficult to assess the potential for wind energy generation
in NSW other than to say that it is anticipated that it will play
a small, but important role in the future electricity supply mix.
To provide a perspective on this technology and its possible utilisation
in NSW it is interesting to note that supply of just 1% of existing
electrical needs would require the installation of more than twenty
10 MW(e) wind farms.
</MENU>

</UL>

<H5>3.2 Solar Photovoltaic</H5>

<P>
Photovoltaics (PV's) is the technology which uses thin sheets
of semiconductive material to directly transform sunlight into
electricity when illuminated.
<P>
The electricity is generated directly in the cell itself, and
so the process is virtually maintenance free except for cleaning
of the active surface as there are no moving parts in the system.
Another advantage of solar cells over concentrator type solar
thermal systems is that it is still possible for them to operate
in diffuse sunlight and in slightly overcast weather.
<P>
Production of solar photovoltaic cells began 30 years ago, with
cells of approximately 2% efficiency being developed for space
programmes. Now, cell efficiency at market level is approximately
14 - 15%. BP Solar are carrying out research here in Australia
and are now producing cells in a pilot production facility with
efficiencies of between 17 to 18%. Costs per watt have decreased
markedly, and research should see this continue whilst also providing
further increases in efficiency. The installed cost of photovoltaics
is still their major disadvantage, however, they still find practical
application for telecommunications, marine navigation, water pumping,
terrestrial applications and remote area power supplies.
<P>
Solar cells are made of 2 layers of a semiconductor material such
as silicon which is doped with minute quantities of other elements
to give n-type and p-type semiconductors. Sandwiching these together
gives what is termed a pn junction across which current flows.
This sets up an internal electric field which has a potential
difference of approximately 0.5 V.
<P>
Figure 3.3 - Construction of a Solar Photovoltaic Cell.
<P>
The electric current is then drawn by way of metal contacts which
are distributed across the negative and positive faces of the
cell. This necessary distribution of pick-ups also creates a problem
for cell efficiencies because the contacts create an area that
shades the semiconductor material. A great amount of research
goes into the practicalities of getting photons into the material,
quite apart from the movement of carriers within it.
<P>
A number of different forms of photovoltaic technology exist.
For example, there are concentrating and non-concentrating cells,
different cell materials such as silicon, gallium arsenide, and
compounds of copper with trace elements. Within the silicon cell
market, there are mono-crystalline, poly-crystalline and amorphous
silicon cells. Each type is being continually refined, and hence
efficiencies improved.
<P>
Professor Martin Green and his team at the University of NSW presently
hold the world record with a non-concentrating silicon cell at
an efficiency of 24.2%. Theoretically the maximum conceivable
efficiency would be of the order of 30%.
<P>
Professor Green also heads up the 'Centre for Photovoltaic Devices
and Systems'. One of the aims of this centre is to further research
into thin film silicon devices. This presently appears to be the
most promising of cells under research for the future. As well
as continuing with other cell research, part of the aim of the
centre is to look for specific sites within the electricity supply
network where PV's might best be used. Some examples are, preventing
the need for re-conductoring of heavily loaded lines approaching
thermal limits, reducing voltage drop at the end of single wire
earth return lines, and offsetting capital costs for upgrading
of thermally overloaded transformers.
<P>
The second largest application of solar cells in Australia provides
power for water pumping. This represents very good matching of
solar energy with water requirements because, usually, most water
is required when agricultural evaporation is high due to sunny
and hot conditions.
<P>
Solar cells are also being more widely used as Remote Area Power
Supplies (RAPS) where they can be economic in offsetting the cost
of diesel fuel for small communities, or single dwellings not
connected to the main electricity supply grid. PV cells can be
seen providing electricity for navigational aids on waterways,
lighting, electric fencing in remote areas, cathodic protection,
and outback telephone systems.
<P>
Presently, in Australia, solar cells would cost approximately
$6000/kW in large scale use. However, at least this much again
would be required for the balance of system costs, which includes
such items as power conditioning equipment and site installation
costs. By comparison, a coal-fired power station would cost around
$1200/kW for a coastal power station with access to lake or sea
water cooling, plus the cost of developing a coal mine to supply
the power station and bulk transmission cost.
<P>
Even given the dramatic reduction in cell costs over the years,
and the fact that photovoltaic generation would probably be connected
at distribution voltage level, some time would be required before
cells could compete on a large scale grid connected basis. The
availability of electricity would only correspond to the availability
of sunlight, and thus, could not directly compete as a reliable
alternative, without the added expense of storage such as a battery.
<P>
This in no way negates the goal of improving the viability of
solar cells. Specific site application has shown them to be viable,
and their generality of use will only increase as research continues
to reduce costs.
<H3>Types of Cells</H3>

<P>
Silicon is the second most abundant material on earth, and is
the most common material used in solar cells.
<P>
There are three major types of silicon solar cells.
<P>
Amorphous: These cells do not possess a regular crystal structure.
They can be produced in films of 0.3 microns and their production
is relatively simple and cheap. Mass production of these cells
is quite easy, with small amounts of material being deposited
on to a substrate such as glass or aluminium, and can even be
made flexible.
<P>
Their major drawback is their low efficiency and short lifespan.
Presently, efficiencies are only 5-7%, however this drops to 3-4%
in operation due to amorphous silicon instabilities. It is generally
used for small scale applications such as calculators and watches.
<P>
Poly-crystalline: These cells consist of a number of silicon crystals
grown as an ingot from which wafers are cut. Their maximum efficiency
is generally 15% and is standard material for high output applications.
Its layers are of the order of 250-400 microns thick.
<P>
Mono-crystalline: These are the highest efficiency silicon cells
available, however in the past their expense has generally precluded
them from anything except &quot;space&quot; applications where
the sun shines nearly all day. Recent developments in mono-crystalline
cell technology has seen their cost reduced to around that of
the poly-crystalline cell. Mono-crystalline cells consist only
of a single crystal.
<P>
Cells other than silicon are available, and some, such as gallium
arsenide, have efficiencies higher than that of silicon. They
are more efficient because their particular band-gap energies
are closer to the theoretical optimum than silicon. They do however
use materials which are more expensive, less abundant, and can
be environmentally hazardous.
<P>
Because different semi-conductor materials absorb different portions
of the solar spectrum, the possiblility of piggy-backing them
to produce a tandem cell has been investigated. These then absorb
much more of the incident radiation than either material would
alone. Once again, however, their cost is much greater than silicon
cells, even on a unit energy delivered basis.
<H5>3.3 Solar Thermal</H5>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
Solar thermal does not create electricity directly as does photovoltaic
technology but rather uses solar collectors to heat a fluid, usually
water. The resulting heat may then be used either directly, as
hot water (e.g. domestic hot water system), or process heat, which
is when solar energy systems are at their most efficient (e.g.
domestic hot water system), or may supply preheating, or indeed
steam, for turning a heat engine and generator.
<P>
The solar collectors are the heart of the system and their design
determines the final application and efficiency. The critical
factors are the amount and temperature of solar energy collection
that they provide.
<P>
Flat plate solar collectors are commonly used for heating water
or air for a range of domestic and industrial applications. This
collector provides no concentration and its maximum operating
temperature is generally around 80 degrees Celsius.
<P>
To reach higher temperatures efficiently, some concentration needs
to be employed. Concentration to give high temperatures offers
advantages of more efficient heat transfer, higher theoretical
steam cycle efficiencies, and subsequently a much wider range
of applications. However higher temperatures require greater emphasis
upon reducing thermal losses. As well as this, the greater the
concentration, the greater can be the detrimental effect of cloud
cover or hazy days.
<H3>Solar Thermal Systems</H3>

<P>
Residential flat plate collectors are presently installed on about
5% of NSW homes. The Pacific Power and Sydney University are collaborating
in the testing of a system using a mildly concentrating trough
with an evacuated tube collector. It can supply not only hot water
but space heating and cooking requirements as well. Investigations
show that with one day's storage, solar collection could supply
up to 90% of the thermal loads of a household. The reason for
this and its inherent advantages over other solar systems, is
that it can be designed to give a winter bias, which is when thermal
energy is most needed. A home in the Sydney region has been retrofitted
with such a system and data is now being collected. In keeping
with the whole concept of energy efficiency, a 12-star equivalent
refrigerator, insulation, and compact fluorescent lighting have
also been installed for evaluation.
<P>
Solar Cogeneration: In terms of solar cogeneration, a practical
study was co-funded by Pacific Power in 1991 to look at the provision
of electrical energy and process heat for applications such as
hospitals and process industries. The energy for the production
of steam would be supplied by high temperature collectors. Though
technically viable, none of the sites studied would presently
be economically viable against gas-fired systems or grid electricity.
<P>
Industrial process heat is the largest single energy sector in
Australia, amounting to some 900 PJ annually. Of this, 15% is
below 200 degrees Celsius and 50% below 500 degrees Celsius. Present
solar collector technology could provide the former, and higher
temperature collectors under refinement could provide much of
the latter. Some estimates predict that low temperature steam
could be provided by mass-produced solar collectors at around
2 c/kWh.
<P>
In terms of solar cogeneration, a practical study was co-funded
by Pacific Power in 1991 to look at the provision of electrical
energy and process heat for applications such as hospitals and
process industries. The energy for the production of steam would
be supplied by high temperature collectors. Though technically
viable, none of the sites studied would presently be economically
viable against gas-fired systems or grid electricity.
<P>
Large-Scale Grid Connection: Electricity generation can be provided
24 hours per day by using a solar and gas system, with the gas
providing super-heat or backup to that steam provided by solar
energy. Sites in NSW such as Cobar could be ideal for this technology
since there is a gas supply available and the number of hours
of sunshine per year are high. The largest solar installations
in the world are the 275 MW solar thermal electricity plants installed
by LUZ in Southern Calfornia.
<P>
The solar array is composed of parabolic trough reflectors which
individually track the sun's movement with microprocessors and
light sensing instruments. The light is concentrated on to evacuated
tubes through which a synthetic oil, heat transfer fluid flows.
Temperatures of nearly 400 degrees Celsius are possible. This
is used to produce super-heated steam via a heat exchanger, with
natural gas fuel as a supplement. The power plant produces electricity
with a peak solar to electric efficiency of approximately 25%.
<P>
Average solar radiation at these LUZ sites is similar to that
at Broken Hill in NSW. SEGS VIII, LUZ's largest project so far,
sized at 80 MW(e), is designed for an annual output of 252.7 GWh.
It has 464 000 square metres of collecting surface area, and occupies
an area of some 300 hectares.
<P>
A small-scale demonstration plant was installed at White Cliffs,
Western New South Wales, using 14 parabolic dishes. The dishes
themselves performed extremely well, however, there were problems
with the steam engine and oil separation system. Larger systems
(greater than 5 MW(e)) which can use steam turbines rather than
engines are expected to give greater overall performance, and
also cost reductions due to economies of scale.
<P>
Central Receiver Systems: These use the heliostats in a reflective
arrangement to generate very high temperatures at a single point.
Though this offers greater turbine efficiency, their capital cost
is higher.
<P>
Solar Ponds: Such a system is most attractive for arid regions
of Australia where there is accompanying high salinity. Technically,
this process is quite feasible. A 250,000 square metres, 5 MW(e)
pond in Israel collects heat at an efficiency of 16%. A demonstration
pond at Curtin Springs in the Northern Territory quotes costs
of around $10,800/kW with energy supplied at 16.6 c/kWh. Further
development is required to make this system viable in the future.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<H3>Evacuated Tube Solar Water Heaters</H3>

<P>
Convection and conduction losses become more serious as high temperature
applications are attempted, and it became apparent very early
on in research, that evacuating the space between the glass cover
and the absorber surface would yield much improved performance.
<P>
Figure 3.4 - Solar House Retrofit Project.
<P>
Evacuated flat plate collectors have been investigated, however
are unable to withstand atmospheric pressure without costly mechanical
reinforcement. Tubes have been shown that they can withstand such
pressures.
<P>
The combination of the vacuum (which reduces convection and conduction
losses) and a selective surface (which reduces radiation losses)
means that while evacuated tubes do not offer efficiency improvements
over flat plates at temperatures around 80 degrees Celsius, they
do allow higher temperatures to be reached, up to 350 degrees
Celsius.
<P>
Evacuated tubes have solar energy concentrated on them by a reflective
surface. These surfaces range from flat white painted diffuse
reflectors with no concentration and optical efficiencies of 53%
to highly reflective, concentrating, parabolic troughs with optical
efficiencies of greater than 90%.
<H3>Selective Surfaces</H3>

<P>
Solar energy is a form of electromagnetic radiation whose wavelength
ranges from about 0.3 to 2.5 microns. When this strikes a surface,
some is reflected, some absorbed, and the remainder transmitted
through. Materials are then chosen to suit the application. For
example, in the hot, arid regions of the world, houses are usually
painted white to reflect as much of the radiation as possible.
However, in a solar collector, black coatings are used to absorb
as much of the heat as possible. A problem arises here, however,
in that the more heat that is absorbed, the hotter the surface
gets, and thus the more radiation that the surface emits back
to its environment as a loss. This is what prevents standard flat
plate collectors reaching temperatures much above 80 degrees Celsius.
Loss of heat through emittance is especially a problem in areas
with cold, clear nights. It explains for example, why pools are
often warmer after a cloudy night.
<P>
The emittance from a hot surface is at a higher wavelength than
the solar radiation which heats it initially, and this is why
a selective black surface is a more efficient means of collection
than conventional black surfaces. A selective surface uses a specially
selected combination of materials to allow the sunlight portion
of the spectrum in, but which has very low emissivity in the infra-red
range, and therefore lose very little heat through re-radiation.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<H5>3.4 Wave Energy</H5>

<P>
Waves are not regarded as a large energy source in NSW, as wave
energy is reduced significantly by the existence of the continental
shelf along the coastline. Suitably sited, however, wave energy
may be beneficial to coastal communities remote from the electricity
supply network.
<H3>Wave Formation</H3>

<P>
Energy is transmitted to the ocean from the winds through friction
between the air and the surface of the seas across which they
blow. As winds derive their energy from solar gradients, wave
energy is an indirect by-product of solar energy. Contrary to
popular belief the water in a wave does not actually travel but
merely oscillates while the energy of the wave is translated across
the surface of the ocean.
<P>
The power in a wave is equal to the product of the potential energy
per unit area and the phase velocity of the wave train. The average
power flux in kW/m can be calculated from the expression P = 0.5H2T
(approx) where H is the significant wave height at the location
and T is the dominant wave period.
<P>
Preliminary estimates of some NSW sites yields wave energies of
approximately 12 kW/m of coastline. Thus a 120 kW device would
need to be 10m wide at this location. Ideal on-shore sites yield
wave energies of 25 kW/m.
<P>
A study commissioned by Pacific Power and completed in 1991 investigated
suitability of sites along the New South Wales coastline. The
NSW coast wave power is not high enough for long enough to be
presently viable.
<P>
Costs for a prototype device are estimated to be of the order
of $3000/kW.
<P>
It is estimated that some 1 000 000 GWh of wave energy is dissipated
each year along the southern shores of Australia.
<P>
A number of attempts have been made to harness the perennial motion
of the ocean. These include such devices as the Nodding Duck,
Cockerell Raft, Circular Sea Clam, Bristol Cylinder, the Frog,
and a Swedish Wave Rotor. However the two devices which have shown
the most promise are the Tapchan and the oscillating water chamber:
<P>
Tapchan: The principle here is capital intensive yet very simple.
Waves moving forward through a tapered channel rise and spill
over the sides into an elevated reservoir, from which water can
be released through a turbine as in a hydro system. The advantages
here lie in the buffer storage which dampens the irregularity
of the waves.
<P>
Oscillating Water Chamber: A number of versions of this technology
exist, however essentially as the wave rolls in a column of water
is forced upwards through a cylinder, the pocket of air trapped
above being blown through an air turbine which in turn drives
a generator. As the wave rolls out, air is drawn back through
the air turbine. The profile of the turbine blades are designed
so that they continue to spin the turbine in the same direction
no matter what the direction of airflow. This allows energy to
be extracted from the air as the wave rolls in and also as it
recedes.
<P>
Figure 3.5 - Wave Resonance Power Generation.
<P>
Installation of a number of different sized chambers allows maximum
use to be made of different period waves in resonating chambers.
<H3>Data Collection</H3>

<P>
Wave data is collected using wave-rider buoys. These are large
spherical steel floats which house the electronic processing equipment.
The heart of this equipment, is an accelerometer which responds
to the vertical movements of the buoy. Integration of wave movement
via a microprocessor calculates wave velocities in the vertical
direction, and as a result can calculate wave displacement data.
A solar cell powered transmitter sitting atop the buoy then relays
the data to a shore based receiver. This data is compiled on computer
for processing and assessment.
<P>
Eight wave rider buoys have been deployed along the NSW coast,
and are constantly compiling data which is useful for investigating
wave power potential. This data is used for a variety of engineering
projects along the coast including wharves and jetties, foreshore
developments, storm damage, etc.
<P>
A New Zealand device for wave energy measurement consists of a
seismograph on the shore, monitoring the energy of breaking waves
and correlating this data to wave height.
<H5>3.5 Biomass</H5>

<P>
The extraction of energy from biomass is understood to mean two
processes: first, large-scale production of liquid or gaseous
fuel from plants or crops specially cultivated for this purpose;
second, biological recovery of combustible gas from organic waste
commonly known as biogas.
<P>
The potential and economics of these two processes are clearly
different. The utilization of crops and plants for energy production
purposes is, in general, not practicable on a large scale. In
addition to this, it still has to be proved whether the substantial
input of energy by way of manuring, sowing, tilling the fields,
harvesting and transport can be recovered anyway. Last but certainly
not least, the harmful effect of monocultures on the environment
with large amounts of fertilisers, insecticides, pesticides and
herbicides would be difficult to justify.
<P>
So far, most of the emphasis has been on the useful energy obtained
from organic waste which is considered to be zero cost. The waste
may be used for energy production in many ways. The direct combustion
of such waste for process heat and electricity generation is finding
increasing application. However, such waste must be used within
reasonably close proximity to its point of origin to compensate
for its high collection cost and to avoid the high cost of transportation
to the point of use.
<P>
In principle, many farms could provide themselves with the energy
they need from their own organic waste. One of the main advantages
of biogas is that the gas which is generated is produced where
biomass accumulates as a waste material.
<P>
Biogas systems have been in widespread use for more than 30 years,
especially in Third World countries. India has a few hundred thousand
simple facilities of this kind, whilst in China about 7 million
operate.
<P>
Compared with other energy generation facilities, construction
and operation of a biogas facility is a simple and straightforward
task. Animal excrements and plant waste are the source of energy
used. They are reduced in size and mixed before being placed in
a fermentation tank. The organic waste decomposes under anaerobic
(ie. without oxygen) conditions as a result of its exposure to
microbes naturally present, generating combustible gases in the
process. The only prerequisite for proper fermentation is correct
acidity and operating in a specific temperature range so that
the microbes thrive. Pesticides, disinfectants and antibiotics
must be avoided as they are likely to bring the fermentation process
to a halt.
<P>
Figure 3.6 - Floating Bell Biogas Producer Schematic Diagram.
<P>
The biogas generated in this way consists primarily of 40-70%
methane and 30-60% carbon dioxide. If the gas contains 60% methane,
it has a calorific value of 70% of natural gas. The yield generated
by a biogas facility depends above all on the composition of the
waste material to be fermented and the ambient temperature. If
this temperature is low, up to 50% of the gas generated can be
required afterwards for heating the biomass.
<P>
The other product generated by the process is odourless and hygienic
compost which is ideally suited for use as a fertiliser, provided
the biomass was free of toxic substances such as heavy metals.
<P>
Biogas generation facilities are used mainly by family operated
farms and, in particular, by farms keeping their own livestock.
Using fermentation tanks with a capacity of 6-25 cubed metres,
small and medium-sized farms mainly generate their own energy
for cooking and lighting. The following figures provide basic
orientation on the capacities available. Using the dung of four
head of cattle or 10 pigs, a farm can produce approximately 2
cubed metres of gas and 100 L of sludge manure a day in a 10 cubed
metres facility. This gas is sufficient for:
<P>
. cooking three meals for a family of eight, or
<P>
. running a refrigerator all day and burning a lamp for
<P>
three hours, or
<P>
. generating electricity for one hour with a 3 kW motor
<P>
generator.
<P>
The bright light of gas lamps is generated by incandescent mantles.
Gas operated refrigerators are ammonia absorption refrigerators,
biogas serving merely as the external heating supply. The gas
motors for driving power generators, in turn, are modified diesel
or petrol engines. Any corrosion caused by the hydrogen sulphide
in biogas is kept within limits by changing the oil regularly.
<P>
The production and use of biogas for energy generation has significant
environmental implications. The biogas as it is produced contains
major greenhouse gases, such as methane and carbon dioxide. It
is estimated that methane is 8 times more potent a greenhouse
gas than is carbon dioxide. Therefore by burning the methane gas
produced, which would otherwise have escaped to atmosphere, carbon
dioxide is formed and the overall addition of greenhouse gases
to the atmosphere is less. The environmental benefit is further
enhanced by using the biogas to generate energy, thus reducing
the amount of fossil fuel required to match energy demand. The
utilization of biogas is not only of benefit to the environment,
but has the potential to provide economic returns as well.
<H5>3.6 Waste Incineration</H5>

<P>
In 1989 there were 3.75 million tonnes of solid waste disposed
of in the Sydney region. The quantity of waste being disposed
of is increasing both in total and on a per capita basis. It is
estimated that at these rates, annual waste quantities would increase
to some 5.5 million tonnes by 2001 and by as much as 7.1 million
tonnes by 2011.
<P>
Waste analysis programs carried out by the then Waste Management
Authority (WMA) indicate the average composition of council collected
garbage are those shown in the following table:
<H3>Figure 3.7 - Average composition of council collected garbage
</H3>

<P>
Component of Waste Weight % (as received)
<P>
----------------------------------------------------------
<P>
paper products 20.9
<P>
food waste 27.5
<P>
garden waste 20.5
<P>
plastics 7.6
<P>
wood, rubber, textiles 4.3
<P>
metals 6.3
<P>
glass 9.3
<P>
fines 3.6
<P>
It is important to note that solid wastes are not homogeneous
in nature but are a mixture of both combustible and non-combustible
materials which vary from location to location and over time.
<P>
Apart from avoiding waste from the very beginning and recycling
the waste produced, one of the best methods of waste management
for the future is to burn it in a refuse fuelled power station.
<P>
An international comparison shows that countries with little space
for waste disposal sites make greater use of incineration technologies.
While the incineration of household waste in the European Community
member countries averages only 20%, the corresponding figures
for Japan and Switzerland are 65% and 80% respectively.
<P>
The energy content of household waste varies greatly. This energy
can be recovered in waste incineration. The relative contribution
of waste incineration to the overall generation of energy is small,
hardly exceeding 1% of the national consumption of primary energy
in any country. However, considered from the perspective of plant
technology, conventional waste incineration is a well-developed
process.
<P>
The technology of waste incineration provides two distinct advantages.
The first is the reduction in volume of disposed wastes to about
5% of the original volume (or about 20-30% of the original weight)
and the second is the utilization of the energy produced for the
generation of electricity.
<P>
The scarcity of landfill sites and the increasing difficulty in
obtaining approval for future disposal sites, particularly in
built-up areas such as the Sydney Basin, is forcing other disposal
options to be considered. Waste incineration whilst it is not
necessarily the whole answer, will be an important consideration
in the assessment of options for future disposal.
<P>
The WMA Strategic Plan has included the use of incineration as
an alternative to the long distance transfer of waste away from
the metropolitan area. The WMA also indicate that a strategy of
progressive implementation of three incinerators (1000 tonnes/day)
during the planning period of 2001 to 2011 would require an investment
of the order of $450 million in 1988 values.
<H3>Technologies</H3>

<P>
The technologies for the incineration of wastes can be divided
in two distinct categories. The first has been developed for the
incineration of domestic refuse and sewage sludge, whilst the
second has been developed for the incineration of industrial refuse
and sludge.
<P>
Domestic incinerators consist of a moving grate, of which there
are numerous designs and onto which the garbage is dumped (some
of the more common designs are known as the roller grate, tilting
grate, step type travelling grate and the inclined grate). Combustion
air is passed from beneath the grate through the burning garbage.
The heat produced is used for the production of steam. Residence
time in the incinerator can be strictly controlled by varying
the grate speed and hence avoiding emission problems caused by
incomplete combustion.
<P>
There are two types of industrial refuse and sludge incineration
plant, namely the rotary kiln and the fluidised bed.
<P>
Both domestic and industrial waste disposal methods rely on the
concept of complete 'burnout' of the waste. This is done to minimise
the pollutants contained in combustion gases. Complete 'burnout'
is best achieved by high temperatures, long residence times and
by good mixing of the combustion gases.
<P>
The heat produced from the combustion of waste material is transferred
to banks of water wall tubes for the production of steam which
in turn is used to drive a steam turbine and electrical generator.
This process of steam raising is similar in design to some of
the other technologies discussed throughout this document, for
instance fluidised bed combustion technologies and combined cycle.
<P>
Once the heat contained in the combustion gases is transferred
to the steam circuit, pollution control equipment is used to reduce
harmful pollutants. Burning of domestic and industrial refuse,
leads to emissions of pollutants such as sulphur dioxide, nitrogen
oxides, carbon monoxide and particulate matter. Depending on the
nature of refuse, it is expected that the refuse residue should
only contain low levels of organic compounds and heavy metals.
Waste incineration plants can operate with minimum impact on the
environment by employing emission control equipment such as flue
gas desulphurisation for the control of sulphur dioxide and acid
gases, a thermal nitrogen oxides removal system for control of
nitrogen oxides and a high efficiency particulate collection device
such as a fabric filter for removal of solids and heavy metals
carried along by the exhaust gases.
<P>
The size of waste incineration plants is often quoted in terms
of the mass of refuse consumed per hour rather than the maximum
electrical output. This is useful because the energy contained
in the refuse feed can vary substantially with time and hence
the maximum electrical energy generated also varies. Common incinerator
sizes are between 5 and 30 tonnes per hour. Plant sizes are generally
between 15 and 30 MW of electrical output. For waste tonnages
greater than this, it is usual to install a number of these units
in a single facility.
<P>
The energy contained in domestic garbage is approximately 8-10
MJ/kg or 30-40% of the energy content of black coal.
<P>
Industrial refuse incineration generally excludes the burning
of scrap tyres. Because of the nature of manufacture of tyres,
the tyre combustion process releases a significant amount of potentially
toxic air pollutants such as arsenic, cadmium, dioxins, furans
and other trace heavy metals.
<P>
Therefore, tyre combustion requires &quot;Best Available Control
Technology&quot; (BACT) for the control of emissions. To achieve
this level of environmental control a significant amount of expenditure
is required which adds significantly to the total cost of the
incineration plant. For this reason, the current practice of waste
disposal is to separate scrap tyres from other wastes.
<P>
Tyre combustion technology has already proven to be clean, safe,
odourless and virtually pollution free at a power plant constructed
at Modesto, California, U.S.A. The plant can burn up to 6 million
tyres per year. Whole scrap tyres are fed into two identical incineration
plants at a rate of about 6.5 tonnes/hour and burned under carefully
controlled conditions. Combustion is carried out at a temperature
of 1100 degrees Celsius to produce 14 MW of electric power. This
relatively high temperature combustion process ensures the complete
burnout of the tyres. Together with complete air quality control,
the operation of this facility has been claimed to be environmentally
safe.
<H5>3.7 Landfill Gas</H5>

<P>
Landfill gas refers to the formation of combustible gases from
garbage dumps through primarily anaerobic decomposition of organic
wastes (mostly food, garden and paper wastes). The gas produced
consists predominantly of methane and carbon dioxide and contains
40-60% of the energy content of natural gas.
<P>
Some 3.75 million tonnes of solid waste were disposed of in the
Sydney region in 1989, and as much as 7.1 million tonnes annually
are projected by the year 2011. These wastes not only represent
a significant problem in terms of disposal urban areas such as
Sydney but also a large potential energy resource.
<P>
Driven by environmental concerns during the 1950's investigations
were carried out around the world into the characteristics of
landfills over their lifetime and the constituents of the odorous
gases produced. It was found that the wastes decomposed in the
presence of moisture and the action of anaerobic bacteria, producing
methane and carbon dioxide. As well as these gases being produced,
other gases were released including nitrogen, oxygen, hydrogen
and traces of hydrogen sulphide (rotten egg gas) resulting in
the foul odours normally associated with garbage dumps.
<P>
Methane as a gas contributes significantly to the greenhouse effect
and contributes 6 times more to global warming than does carbon
dioxide on a molecule for molecule basis. For this reason there
is an advantage in burning this methane to produce energy, which
although producing carbon dioxide has less impact on the greenhouse
effect.
<P>
The decomposition of garbage commences soon after collection with
the initial process being aerobically activated and the gases
produced consisting mainly of carbon dioxide. Once the garbage
has been compacted into the landfill the remaining oxygen is consumed
and anaerobic conditions prevail. This is then suitable, providing
moisture is present, for the production of methane.
<P>
The technology for using landfill gas as a fuel source for power
generation, using gas turbines or engines is well established.
In 1975, the USA started utilising landfill gas at Palos Verdes
in southern California and since then more than 70 sites have
been developed. In Germany more than 50 sites now exploit this
gas and in Britain there are 24 commercial schemes drawing gas
from 18 locations with a further 26 schemes either in advanced
planning stages or under construction.
<P>
In the Sydney region there are two projects presently underway.
The first located at Merrylands was originally the site of an
old brickworks excavation which was filled with approximately
700,000 tonnes of garbage between 1979 and 1985 and now produces
about 700 cubed metres per hour of landfill gas. Most of this
site has now been dressed with soil and landscaped. About 7 years
ago the then Waste Management Authority began selling this gas
to the local brick works for firing its kilns. More recently,
however, the brickworks have ceased operation and a 165kW engine
and generator have now been installed to utilise the gas for generating
electricity. This project has been a joint effort between Prospect
Electricity, Waste Management Authority and Pacific Power and
will provide valuable operating experience for future use of this
technology.
<P>
The second project located at Lucas Heights, south-west of Sydney,
is planned to be larger than the Merrylands project and will be
built, owned and operated by a private company as a commercial
venture. There is estimated to be at least 0.5 PJ per annum (initially
some 3000 cubed metres per hour) of gas at this location which
is sufficient to generate on average 5 MW of electricity over
the next 15 years.
<H2>CHAPTER FOUR</H2>

<H3>ENERGY STORAGE SYSTEMS</H3>

<H4>4.1 Compressed Air Energy Storage (CAES)</H4>

<P>
Compressed air energy storage (CAES) offers a means of storing
excess electrical energy available during 'offpeak' periods, usually
during the night, for recovery during the 'peak' demand periods
of early morning and evenings. By storing energy, utilities can
avoid the installation of more power stations to cover the peak
electricity demand.
<P>
There are five above-ground components required by the basic CAES
installation.
<MENU>
<LI>1. The motor/generator which employs clutches to provide for
alternate engagement to the compressor or turbine trains.
<LI>2. The air compressor which may require two or more stages,
intercoolers and aftercoolers to achieve economy of compression,
and reduce the moisture content.
<LI>3. The turbine train, high and low pressure turbines.
<LI>4. Equipment control centre for operating the combustion turbine,
compressor, and auxiliaries and to regulate and control changeover
from generation mode to storage mode.
<LI>5. Auxiliary equipment consisting of fuel storage and handling,
and mechanical and electrical systems to support various heat
exchangers required to support the operation of the facility.
</MENU>

<H3>Figure 4.1 - Compressed Air Energy Storage</H3>

<P>
In the power generation mode, compressed air is mixed with fuel
and expanded through a modified gas turbine driving the electrical
machine as a generator. In storage mode the electrical machine
is used to drive the compressor which compresses the air into
the underground storage for later use.
<P>
The introduction of natural gas in the generating mode of the
CAES cycle allows increased 'peak' power production, than would
otherwise be available from the recovery of compressed air.
<P>
The CAES system is similar in principle to a 'pumped' hydro scheme.
A pumped hydro scheme is basically conventional hydro where by
the water is passed through a water turbine to produce electricity.
During 'offpeak' times, however, the water can be pumped back
to a high elevation in preparation for the next 'peak' period.
<H3>Siting of CAES Plants</H3>

<P>
Compressed air for CAES plant is stored underground either in
man made excavations or in naturally occurring porous rock media.
Plant siting requires favourable geology for the air storage reservoir
as well as suitable location near transmission lines and fuel
supplies.
<P>
Geological/Geotechnical criteria in the selection of potential
sites for underground storage are grouped into three categories.
<UL>
<LI>Underground rock caverns created by excavating comparatively
hard and impervious rock formations.
<LI>Salt caverns created by solution or dry mining of salt formations.
<MENU>
<LI>There are no potential locations in NSW where large salt caverns
could be created.
</MENU>

<LI>Porous media reservoirs made by water bearing aquifers or
depleted gas or oil fields e.g., sandstone, fissured limestone.
</UL>

<P>
In a gas turbine 50-60% of the energy produced by the power turbine
is consumed by the compressor. If compression is carried out at
a different time to when power generation is needed, ie, by CAES,
the peak power which the gas turbine can generate is increased
by this amount, and hence additional plant is not required to
be installed.
<P>
Rock caverns may be operated either with 'hydraulic compensation'
(an interconnected surface reservoir) which provides constant
pressure as the water level and hence volume of the cavern varies
as air is released or stored, or, dry where the pressure varies
because the cavern maintains the same volume. Water curtains surrounding
the caverns may be used to control air leakage. The principal
geotechnical criteria for rock caverns are rock mass, strength
and stability, depth, and structure such that they will contain
air with minimal losses.
<P>
Principal requirements for an aquifer to be a candidate for CAES
include:
<UL>
<LI>Structure which entraps the air. Strata is porous enough to
contain sufficient air at the desired pressure and permeable enough
to allow the flow of air which is required by the facility.
<LI>Overlain by an impermeable rock strata which will prevent
vertical movement of the fluid from the storage zone.
<LI>Mineralogy which will not result in oxidation reactions and
reaction products which would consume the oxygen contained in
the stored air.
<LI>Be located at sufficient depths to allow safe operation at
required pressures.
</UL>

<P>
Future developments of CAES include the addition of recuperators
to extract heat from the compressed air during the charging cycle
and to heat the air on discharge. This will substantially improve
efficiency of the CAES system but still requires advances in materials
of construction for recuperators.
<P>
The Huntorf plant in West Germany rated at 290 MW(e) operated
from 1978 and over 10 years showed 90% availability and 99% starting
reliability. In Alabama USA a 110 MW(e) plant is scheduled for
operation in 1991 and a 1050 MW(e) plant is being proposed for
the Donbass region in the USSR.
<P>
Italy has operated a small 25 MW(e) CAES research facility based
on aquifer storage. It is also understood that Israel is interested
in building a 3 x 100 MW(e) CAES facility using fractured hard
rock aquifers.
<H4>4.2 Batteries</H4>

<P>
Demand for electricity varies according to time of day, leading
to corresponding peaks and troughs in the amount of electricity
being generated. Load levelling by matching customer needs to
system capability can be achieved by a variety of means. Through
'demand-side' planning and management, load patterns can be controlled
by influencing the electricity demands of customers. Although
this planning is very effective, removing the peaks and troughs
totally from energy demand is not feasible. For this reason energy
storage facilities find application in the storing of 'offpeak'
energy during periods of low demand (for example overnight) for
use during 'peak' periods (morning and evenings) as the customer
requires. One energy storage technology receiving a great deal
of attention worldwide is that of the so-called 'giant' battery.
<P>
As well as providing an excellent source of energy storage, batteries
can also provide a number of other significant benefits to the
electricity industry. They have been found useful for assisting
in maintaining the stability of electricity transmission networks,
particularly during fault conditions, whilst also providing instantaneous
replacement power, should a power generating unit trip off line
for any reason.
<P>
Batteries are generally named after the chemical components which
in combination produce the electrical energy. Typical battery
systems being investigated worldwide are included in the Table
below:
<P>
Figure 4.2 - Typical Battery Systems.
<P>
The conversion of chemical energy into electrical energy is a
well established science and in some cases has been performed
with energy conversion efficiencies quoted at greater than 90%.
Whilst not all battery systems can claim such high energy conversion
efficiency, it is not unusual for efficiencies to exceed 70%.
Power conversion to convert DC to AC would typically be around
95% for large convertors.
<P>
In 1988, in the United States, Southern California Edison installed
a 10 MW(e), 4 hour capacity lead/acid battery. Known as the Chino
plant it was constructed for demonstration purposes and to investigate
operational and maintenance characteristics. As a grid connected
power station this battery has been quoted as being the largest
in the world, although it actually consists of more than 8200
individual battery units.
<P>
With continued investigations and development of battery construction,
materials and electrolytes, batteries may play an increasing role
in the supply of electricity and electricity supply management.
<H2>CHAPTER FIVE</H2>

<H3>TRANSMISSION TECHNOLOGIES</H3>

<H4>5.1 Superconductivity</H4>

<P>
The prospect of obtaining &quot;zero loss&quot; electrical conductors
has produced a great deal of interest since superconductivity
was discovered by Onnes in 1911 and for which in 1913, he received
the Nobel prize for physics.
<P>
The transmission of electricity to load centres ultimately leads
to energy losses and hence reduces the overall efficiency of electricity
supplied to consumers. Superconductivity refers to the transmission
of electricity with no losses.
<P>
Until recently superconductivity was only possible at temperatures
approaching absolute zero (-273 degrees Celsius) and in the case
of metallic elements the highest temperature achievable has been
for niobium at -266 degrees Celsius. Recent discoveries using
complex chemical compounds has increased this temperature to -148
degrees Celsius and has led to new speculations about the potential
impact on the operation of the electricity supply industry.
<P>
It is useful to note some limitations of superconducting materials.
<MENU>
<LI>(i) They have some losses for alternating current applications.
<LI>(ii) They maintain their superconductivity only while operated
below certain temperature limits, current density and magnetic
field.
<LI>(iii) The cost of cooling is considerable.
<LI>(iv) The new, high temperature superconductors are made from
ceramic materials, not easily formed into wires.
</MENU>

<P>
Helium-cooled (&quot;low temperature&quot;) superconducting materials
have been widely used, particularly in large magnets. Of more
direct relevance to the electricity supply industry are demonstration
models of high voltage cables, generators and magnetic energy
storage devices which have been developed, but of which none are
in regular service.
<P>
With lower refrigeration requirements, the new liquid nitrogen
cooled high temperature superconductors may find a number of applications,
but much development work is still required.
<H4>5.2 High Voltage Direct Current (HVDC)</H4>

<P>
Some very early power supply systems used direct current (DC).
Now, throughout the world, electricity supply is almost always
done with alternating current (AC) systems. This is because AC
allows simple transformers to be used to change the supply voltage
from the very high levels required for bulk transmission, to the
lower levels required for distribution systems and the even lower
levels at which power is supplied to consumers.
<P>
In the past few decades, High Voltage Direct Current (HVDC) connections
have been built in some countries between AC supply systems. HVDC
systems can be used to transmit large amounts of power over long
distances more economically than AC transmission. However, the
relatively high cost of AC to DC converter equipment has meant
that it has not yet been applied in Australia.
<P>
One consideration with very large AC systems (such as that which
connects New South Wales, Victoria and South Australia) is that
all the generators connected must rotate at exactly the same rate
for the whole system to &quot;remain in synchronism&quot;. The
connection of separate systems via a HVDC link avoids this necessity
and the power that it transmits can be rapidly regulated to enhance
the stability of the connected systems.
<P>
A HVDC link is being considered for a possible interconnection
between the New South Wales, Victorian and South Australian systems
and the Queensland system. Options being considered include the
conversion of existing 330 kV AC transmission lines to HVDC lines.
<H2>CHAPTER SIX</H2>

<H3>TECHNOLOGY FOR ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL</H3>

<P>
Pacific Power is highly committed to the development and implementation
of technologies which improve the environmental acceptability
of power stations. To date Pacific Power's concern for the environment
has seen significant firsts in emission control and in the reduction
to the point of 'zero discharges' of waste water from power station
sites.
<P>
Combustion of fossil fuels inevitably generates carbon dioxide
which is a highly significant greenhouse gas and there are no
reasonable procedures or technologies for retaining carbon dioxide
within the power station. There are, however, new power station
technologies which help to provide an improvement through higher
efficiency and hence smaller output of carbon dioxide per unit
of energy generated.
<P>
In addition to this, fuel selection can influence the amount of
carbon dioxide produced. Carbon dioxide emissions decrease with
decreasing carbon to hydrogen ratio in the fuel; accordingly from
coal to oil to gas and ultimately hydrogen. Consequently, moisture
in the combustion gases is increased for higher hydrogen content
fuels. Naturally this is one factor which favours the use of natural
gas as a replacement fuel for coal and oil and the development
of hydrogen as a fuel for transport.
<P>
Another serious but technically manageable factor is the emission
of pollutants into the atmosphere. Each year consumption of fossil
fuels worldwide releases an estimated 80 million tonnes of nitrogen
oxides, 140 million tonnes of sulphur dioxide, 300 million tonnes
of dust and similarly large amounts of hydrocarbons.
<P>
With the burden on the environment, industrialised countries are
implementing counter measures and it is the introduction of new
technologies, improved efficiencies and government policies that
the problem is now being addressed.
<H4>6.1 Flue Gas Desulphurisation</H4>

<P>
Acid rain is the subject of considerable concern throughout the
world, particularly in Europe where it is now regarded as fact
that pollutants play a major part in the current damage to lakes
and forests. In New South Wales, however, the low sulphur content
of locally mined coal, which the Commission uses, significantly
reduces missions of sulphur dioxide in flue gases. Pacific Power
has participated in a study under the National, Energy, Research,
Development and Demonstration programme to analyse the acidity
of precipitation in the Hunter region. The study concluded that
precipitation acidity was equivalent to or slightly greater than
background.
<P>
Pacific Power maintains a watching brief on technologies for sulphur
control as well as the associated capital and operating costs
of such facilities. The most common flue gas desulphurisation
technology available (scrubbing devices) can add up to 40% to
the investment value of a conventional coal fired power station.
A brief description of the more relevant technologies follows.
<MENU>
<LI>6.1.1 Wet Scrubbing
<LI>Perhaps the most widely used technology for the desulphurisation
of flue gases is 'Wet Scrubbing'. The technology employs an alkaline
sorbent slurry which is predominantly lime or limestone based.
A 'scrubbing vessel' or scrubber is located downstream of the
boiler in which intimate contact between gas and sorbent is carried
out, a process which readily removes over 90% of sulphur dioxide
from the flue gases. The resulting solid is predominantly calcium
sulphite which can be further oxidised to be sold as a by-product
to the building industry where it finds application as plaster
board. Wet scrubbing technology is currently in place in over
300 coal-fired installations worldwide with at least another 100
units planned to be constructed in the foreseeable future.
</MENU>

<H3>Figure 6.1 - Flue Gas Desulphurisation Wet Scrubbing</H3>

<P>
The capital cost of new ($250/kW) or retrofitted ($400/kW) equipment
is considerable and is a function of the sulphur content of the
fuel source, chlorine levels (which may require an additional
pre-scrubber) and often land space available. Design considerations
which lead to such high costs include:
<P>
. size of equipment (e.g. 'scrubber') in order to handle voluminous
<P>
quantities of flue gas;
<P>
. material selection to handle the wet and corrosive nature of
<P>
material;
<P>
. incorporation of equipment into the boiler flue gas path;
<P>
. ancillary equipment which must also be of high quality to handle
<P>
corrosive sorbent and by-product;
<P>
Operating cost components include:
<UL>
<LI>purchase of sorbent materials
<LI>maintenance
<LI>disposal of wastes
<LI>additional cost of fuel to account for reduced overall plant
efficiency by 3.8% of total electrical output
</UL>

<P>
Modern 'wet scrubbers' use sorbents efficiently which they purchase
for reasonably low prices. The by-product produced is potentially
saleable although it is expected that in European countries the
construction/building industry may become flooded with gypsum
reducing its saleable value. Finally, recent developments in this
technology for example, regenerative flue gas reheating and natural
draft cooling towers are looking at increasing overall efficiency
to minimise operating costs.
<MENU>
<LI>6.1.2 Spray Dry Scrubbing
<LI>This technology as with 'wet scrubbing' employs a sorbent
slurry or solution, however, the by-product produced is 'dry'.
The slurry of sorbent, again alkaline based, is sprayed into the
scrubbing vessel in very fine droplets and dries as it contacts
the flue gas. At this point the sorbent reacts with the sulphur
dioxide.
<LI>The dry sorbent is picked up by the gas stream and carried
into the dust collection plant (e.g. fabric filters) for removal.
<LI>Spray dry scrubbing has been installed in over 80 power station
installations worldwide making it the second most popular flue
gas desulphurisation technology available. Currently capital costs
are only slightly less than for wet scrubbing systems, whilst
removal efficiencies of up to 90% have been quoted.
<LI>Operating costs are noticeably higher than for 'wet scrubbers'
because of the reduced contact between sorbent and gas. Lime rather
than limestone is the preferred sorbent although more costly.
Because of the cost structure of this technology it is more suited
when burning low to medium sulphur coals. Another disadvantage
with 'spray dry scrubbing' is that there is no commercial use
for the by-product produced, since it is mixed with the dust originating
in the coal and collected in the dust collecting plant. Of course
this may also prevent the sale of fly ash to existing markets
such as for concrete.
<LI>6.1.3 Sorbent Injection
<LI>The technology of calcium sorbent injection is a more recently
developed technology and is the lowest in terms of capital outlay
of all the available sulphur dioxide removal technologies.
<LI>The sorbent can be added dry into one of three locations;
</MENU>

<UL>
<LI>with the fuel, thus into the furnace (gas temperature 850-1250
degrees Celsius)
<LI>into the economiser region (gas temperature 950-550 degrees
Celsius)
<LI>after the air heaters (gas temperature close to saturation).
<MENU>
<LI>However, because of relatively poor contact between the sorbent
and sulphur dioxide, efficiency is generally in the range 30-60%
and hence, sorbent use is much higher. The residual sorbent and
ash mixture is not a commercial product as with 'wet scrubbing'.
<LI>The technology has found a niche market for small boilers
with less stringent environmental controls than are imposed on
large utilities, or where the ash content of the coal is sufficiently
alkaline in itself to assist in the sulphur dioxide removal process.
<LI>Considerable research of the technology is underway with efficiencies
expected to reach as high as 80% should techniques like humidification
of the flue gas or other additives into the gas stream prove successful.
<LI>Due to Pacific Power's commitment to the use of fabric filter
technology for particulate control on coal-fired power stations,
direct sorbent injection was identified as being an attractive
alternative to more complex wet flue gas desulphurisation systems.
A study is currently deing conducted by Pacific Power to investigate
the feasibility of the large scale use of direct sorbent injection
upstream of fabric filter plant for sulphur dioxide reduction.
<LI>A pilot has been constructed which utilises flue gas diverted
from an operating 660 MW(e) power station boiler into a 160 bag
fabric filter pilot test plant. The plant consists of a sorbent
storage silo, volumetric feeder, pneumatic conveying and injection
equipment along with oxygen and sulphur dioxide monitoring equipment
upstream of the sorbent injector, immediately prior to the bags
and downstream of the filter bags.
<LI>Preliminary testing has been conducted using industrial grade
Calcium Hydroxide as the sorbent material, no flue gas humidification
and 'as-found' inlet sulphur dioxide concentrations. The results
have demonstrated removal efficiencies in excess of 60% at high
dosing rates are possible.
<LI>Although the previously discussed sulphur removal technologies
are proven, new technologies such as pressurised fluidised bed
combustors as well as integrated gasification and combined cycle
plants (as discussed earlier in sections 2.1.4 and 2.3.2 respectively)
provide similarly clean exhaust gases by reducing sulphur dioxide
formation prior to or during the combustion process.
</MENU>

</UL>

<H4>6.2 Control Of Gaseous Oxides Of Nitrogen</H4>

<P>
In coal and oil-fired power stations with conventional combustion
systems, the measures to reduce emissions must be taken largely
by cleaning the flue gas. Environmental measures for removing
pollutants from the flue gas can be very expensive and depending
on the quality of the coal and location of the plant can increase
overall investment by up to 40%. The principal measures carried
out to control nitrogen oxides in the combustion chamber of a
power station involves strict control of air and fuel supply to
the burners. Up to a 50% reduction in nitrogen oxides emissions
can be achieved in this way and at relatively low cost.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
There are as many as five stable gaseous oxides of nitrogen but
of these the only ones present in the atmosphere in significant
amounts are nitrous oxide, nitric oxide and nitrogen dioxide.
These three gases are potential atmospheric pollutants.
<P>
Nitric oxide is a colourless gas. Its ambient concentration is
usually much less than that which leads to biological toxicity
in terms of human health. Nitric oxide is, however, a precursor
to an active gaseous compound in the formation of photochemical
smog, nitrogen dioxide. Nitrogen dioxide is a reddish-brown gas
and in sufficient concentration visible to the eye. The toxicological
and epidemiological effects of nitrogen dioxide are not fully
understood and unless present in extremely high concentrations
does not affect human health. Environmental emission standards
for this gas are often based on visibility effects.
<P>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
<P>
Where environmental limits cannot be achieved using this method,
DENOX units are required as secondary measures. The only process
applied so far on a large scale, has been selective catalytic
reduction (SCR) using ammonia or ammonia compounds in the presence
of a catalyst. A schematic of this process is shown in Figure
6.2.
<P>
Figure 6.2 - Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR) for Reduction
of
<P>
Oxides of Nitrogen Emissions
<P>
The ammonia is injected at about 450 degrees celsius in the presence
of a vanadium pentoxide catalyst (titanium dioxide catalysts have
also been used successfully). Reduction of nitrogen oxides in
the flue gas of more than 80% is possible and in conjunction with
burner management systems can be increased to over 90% removal.
The cost of employing this technology can be up to 10 times greater
than burner control and efficiency management systems however
removal efficiency is much higher.
<P>
The amount of nitrogen oxides produced from the combustion of
two different fuel types can vary significantly if the nitrogen
content of the raw fuel is different. As shown in Figure 6.3,
fuel oil which contains nitrogen chemically bound into its molecular
structure gives rise to higher levels of nitrogen oxides emissions
than does natural gas which contains none.
<H3>Figure 6.3 - Gas Turbines - Oxides of Nitrogen Emissions</H3>

<P>
SCR has been applied in Japan and throughout Europe and is fast
gaining acceptance in industrialised countries worldwide. In Germany
alone, over 25 000 MW of coal-fired power stations are expected
to be using this technology by the early 1990's.
<H4>6.3 Fabric Filter Gas Cleaning</H4>

<P>
The flue gas discharged from a power plant boiler carries fly
ash (residue from the coal burned in the boiler). The amount of
this residue (in the form of solid particles which can be discharged
in to the atmosphere) with the flue gas is limited by the Regulations
of The Clean Air Act.
<P>
The Clean Air Act makes it necessary to provide plant between
the boiler and the stack to remove the fly ash from the flue gas
so that the total mass of solid particles actually passing into
the atmosphere is not greater than the amount permitted by the
Act.
<P>
Flue gas cleaning plant may consist of either fabric filters or
precipitators. The plant extends from the boiler discharge flanges
(located after the air heaters), to the inlet flange on the stack.
The fabric filter or bag house operates in a similar manner to
a domestic vaccuum cleaner.
<P>
There are three basic types of fabric filters designated by the
cleaning mode adopted. They are:
<MENU>
<LI>(i) Mechanical Shaker
<LI>(ii) Reverse Gas
<LI>(iii) Pulse Jet
</MENU>

<P>
For all of these types, the fabric is installed in the form of
tube like bags.
<H5>6.3.1 Mechanical Shaker Fabric Filters</H5>

<P>
Mechanical Shaker cleaned units operate on the principle of the
bags being suspended from a shaker frame with the open end of
the bags facing down. These are attached to a cell plate which
separates the 'dirty' gas side from the 'clean' gas side of the
fabric filter compartment.
<P>
As dirty gas is filtered in the bags, the differential pressure
across the plant will gradually rise, requiring the bags to be
cleaned. This is accomplished by sequentially isolating the individual
cells and energising the associated shaker mechanisms, shaking
the bags and causing the ash to fall into the hoppers. The ash
is continually discharged from the hoppers into the disposal system.
<P>
The gas enters from below the cell plate, (through thimbles protruding
through the cell plate) passes up through the centre of the bags
and deposits fly ash on the inside of the bags. The clean gas
passes through the bags and discharges through outlet dampers
at the top of the cell. The filtered flue gas enters an outlet
manifold that joins other similar ducts and is discharged through
induced draft fans to the stack.
<P>
Fabrics used in shaker plants are normally woven from synthetic
polymer fibres such as acrylics, polyesters, etc. Pacific Power
plant of this design characteristically have between 47 360 and
52 480 bags per (660 MW) unit divided into 40 individual cells.
<P>
The bags are 5.5 m long and 165 mm diameter and handle between
890 and 1090 m cubed metres per second of flue gas. Inlet burdens
average 25 g per cubed metre while outlet emissions range from
20 to 30 mg per cubed metre.
<P>
This type of plant is often described as a low-ratio filter as
it has a relatively large fabric area compared to the amount of
gas being cleaned.
<H5>6.3.2 Reverse Gas Fabric Filters</H5>

<P>
Reverse Gas cleaned fabric filters are very similar to mechanical
shaker plant. The cleaning method differs when a cell is taken
off line for cleaning. Instead of activating a mechanical shaker
mechanism, 'clean' gas from the discharge side of the filter is
drawn into the clean side of the cell undergoing cleaning. This
gas passes from the 'clean' to the 'dirty' side of the bags, dislodging
the collected fly ash in a 'back washing' operation. This type
of filter is also known as a low-ratio filter and is usually designed
along similar sizing parameters to shaker plant. The cleaning
operation is much more gentle relative to shaker plant. The fabric
traditionally used in reverse gas units is woven fibreglass.
<P>
Reverse gas plants are widely used in American power stations
as the fibreglass bags are suitable for gas at a higher temperature
than generally expected in New South Wales power stations. This
is due to the high sulphur coal in the USA and the necessity to
reduce corrosion caused by the formation of acid if condensation
occurs.
<H5>6.3.3 Pulse Jet Cleaned Plant</H5>

<P>
Pulse jet plants have a cell plate located above the bags and
the gas passes through the bags from outside to inside. The fly
ash is deposited on the outside of the bag.
<P>
Cleaning of the bags is carried out by passing a short burst of
compressed air down the centre of the bags which causes them to
flex, dislodging the fly ash from the outside of the bag.
<P>
As this plant cleans bags on-line it is not necessary to provide
equipment for cell isolation to clean the bags.
<P>
Pacific Power plant of the pulse jet design are characteristically
equipped with between 9120 and 14664 bags, varying in length from
6 m to 8 m, and a nominal diameter of 130 mm. Gas volumes range
from 480 cubed metres per second to 550 cubed metres per second
with similar inlet burdens and emission figures to low-ratio plants.
<P>
Because of the much smaller amount of fabric area required to
clean a given amount of gas, these plants are known as high-ratio
and are significantly cheaper to build and to run.
<P>
All power stations which have been commissioned in NSW since 1981
have fabric filters installed for particulate emission control.
Retrofitting of fabric filters to a number of older boilers in
our system is currently taking place. In all of the fabric filters
currently used by Pacific Power, the concept of Best Available
Control Technology has been vital. All of the installations to
date and those in progress have been very effective in the elimination
of visible emissions from power station chimneys. This is a significant
factor in the public acceptance of power stations as part of this
local community.
<P></P>
<A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/shared/images/back.gif">Return to
Home Page</A>
<P></P>
</BODY>
