<H2>Kosova Daily Report #1035, 96-12-18</H2>
<H5><A HREF="/news/balkans/kosova">Kosovo Information Center: Kosova Daily Report</A> Directory - <A HREF="96-12-17.ksv.html">Previous Article</A> - <A HREF="96-12-19.ksv.html">Next Article</A></H5>
<H4>From: Kosova Information Center &lt;<A HREF="mailto:kic_pr@zana-pr.ztn.apc.org">kic_pr@zana-pr.ztn.apc.org</A>&gt;</H4>
<H4>Kosova Information Center</H4>
<H4>KOSOVA DAILY REPORT #1035</H4>
<H4>Prishtina, 18 December 1996</H4>
<HR>
<H3>CONTENTS</H3>
<H4>
<DIR>
 <LI><A HREF="#01">[01]</A> President Rugova Meets Senior French Officials in Paris
 <LI><A HREF="#02">[02]</A> Albanians Schoolchildren Protest the Killing of Albanian Teacher
 <LI><A HREF="#03">[03]</A> Serbian Authorities Deny Four Albanians Entry to Kosova
 <LI><A HREF="#04">[04]</A> Educational Activist to Appear before Serb Supreme Court
 <LI><A HREF="#05">[05]</A> Serbian Police Oppresses Albanian Village in Skenderaj
</DIR>
</H4>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="01">[01]</A> President Rugova Meets Senior French Officials in Paris</H3>
President of the Republic of Kosova, Dr. Ibrahim Rugova, had yesterday
(Wednesday) on Paris separate meetings with Bertrand Dufour, General
Secretary of the French Ministry of Foreign Affairs, and Jean-David Levy,
special advisor of President Jacques Chirac of France.
<P>President Rugova said the situation in Kosova is very grave as a result of
the systematic repression and violence of the Serbian regime. The people of
Kosova have responded to this by building up its independent democratic
institutions, he pointed out, noting that peaceful and political means have
been resorted to. Kosova has for seven years now suffered Serbian
domination, but an institutional life, a pluralistic society, has been
maintained, the President said.
<P>President Rugova recalled that in the aftermath of the disintegration of
the former Yugoslav Federation, Kosova, just like other federal units,
opted to go its own way, declaring independence which was confirmed in a
national referendum. This political will has been verified by other acts of
democratic expression, too, such as the free parliamentary and
presidential elections of four years ago.
<P>During the meeting in Quai d'Orseille as well as the discussions with
President Chirac's aide, President Rugova of Kosova expounded on the modes
for the resolution of the question of Kosova issue. An independent and
neutral state, open to both Albania and Serbia, is the optimal solution, he
said, pressing for an interim international civil administration in Kosova,
which would create the conditions for a negotiated settlement to the Kosova
issue. The General Secretary of the French Foreign Ministry, Mr. Dufour,
said his government is concerned about the developments in Kosova. He said
the French government supports a solution, &quot;compatible with the
aspirations of the people of Kosova&quot;.
<P>President Chirac's advisor for diplomacy, Mr. Jean-David Levy expressed his
appreciation for the non-violent policies being pursued in Kosova. The
French President follows closely the situation in Kosova, he said, adding
that France stands for a negotiated settlement to the Kosova issue, which
would be acceptable by the people of Kosova.
<P>Dr. Ibrahim Rugova, who received a Doctor Honoris Cause by the University
of Paris-XVIII on Monday, thanked President Chirac of France for his
concern over and preoccupation with Kosova. Meanwhile, President Rugova
met Tuesday in Paris with the President of the &quot;France-Libert=82&quot;
foundation, Danielle Mitterrand, to discuss the situation in Kosova.
<H3><A NAME="02">[02]</A> Albanians Schoolchildren Protest the Killing of Albanian Teacher</H3>
Albanian schoolchildren and teachers of all levels of education in Kosova -
elementary, secondary and university - protested today (Wednesday) the
killing by the Serbian police of a Kosova Albanian teacher Feriz Blak^ori.
In all the Kosova schools, a minute of the silence was held.
Teachers and students deplored the Serbian regime violence against the
Albanian people of Kosova, expressing their commitment for Kosova's
independence with peaceful means. The entire fist class in all the Kosova
schools was dedicated to Feriz Blak^ori and other victims of the Serbian
regime.
<P>Sources said that a particularly sad atmosphere was at the &quot;Zenel Hajdini&quot;
elementary school in Kosova's capital Prishtina, the late Feriz Blak^ori
taught. Feriz Blak^ori (34), teacher with a Prishtina elementary school
and LDK activist, died last Tuesday in the Prishtina hospital after
having been tortured in a Serbian police station.
<H3><A NAME="03">[03]</A> Serbian Authorities Deny Four Albanians Entry to Kosova</H3>
Four young Albanians from Opoja, southern Kosova - Vaidin B. Krasniqi,
Senat A. Krasniqi, Samidin Kryeziu, and Muharrem T&amp;rsnjaku - were
held up and ill-treated at the Prishtina airport upon their arrival from
Germany, today's Albanian-language Bujku newspaper reported.
<P>Family members told Bujku correspondent that the four Albanians have been
held up at the airport since 14 December. The intention of the Serbian-
installed authorities is to return them back to Germany, Bujku said,
quoting family members.
<H3><A NAME="04">[04]</A> Educational Activist to Appear before Serb Supreme Court</H3>
Zehadin Shemsedini, chairman of the Municipal Educational Council in
Prizren, was summoned to appear before Serbian Supreme Court, &quot;Bujku&quot;
reported today. Dr. Shemsedini was sentences to two years in prison in
1994 und6er the alleged charges of being member of a so-called &quot;defence
ministry&quot; of the Republic of Kosova. He was released pending appeal.
<H3><A NAME="05">[05]</A> Serbian Police Oppresses Albanian Village in Skenderaj</H3>
The Prishtina-based Council for the Defence of Human Rights and Freedoms
(CDHRF) reported yesterday that the Serbian police has been constantly
oppressing an Albanian neighborhood, Zenelaj, at Prekaz i Ep&amp;rm village of
Sk&amp;nderaj. The Serbian police, under the pretext of being in possession
of arms, arrested Ekrem Sejdiu. He was held at the police station for
nine hours, and was ordered him to report again today. Muhamet Ahmeti,
Halit Ukshini and his son Nuredin Ukshini, were also arrested. The Serbian
police summoned for interrogation Bedri Bilalli and Veli Salihu
from Tic&amp; village, too.
<P>The CDHRF says that several detained persons refused to disclose their
identity, fearing of further police persecution.
<HR>
