<center><a href="/info"><IMG SRC="/gifs/hrnet.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="[HR-Net Banner]"></a><BR></center>

<H2>Kosova Daily Report #1036, 96-12-19</H2>
<H5><A HREF="/news/balkans/kosova">Kosovo Information Center: Kosova Daily Report</A> Directory - <A HREF="96-12-18.ksv.html">Previous Article</A> - <A HREF="96-12-20.ksv.html">Next Article</A></H5>
<H4>From: Kosova Information Center &lt;<A HREF="mailto:kic_pr@zana-pr.ztn.apc.org">kic_pr@zana-pr.ztn.apc.org</A>&gt;</H4>
<H4>Kosova Information Center</H4>
<H4>KOSOVA DAILY REPORT #1036</H4>
<H4>Prishtina, 19 December 1996</H4>
<HR>
<H3>CONTENTS</H3>
<H4>
<DIR>
 <LI><A HREF="#01">[01]</A> President Rugova Ends Diplomatic Trip, Arrives in Tirana
 <LI><A HREF="#02">[02]</A> Alarming Environmental Situation in Mitrovica
 <LI><A HREF="#03">[03]</A> Repatriated Albanians Being Held at Prishtina Airport
</DIR>
</H4>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="01">[01]</A> President Rugova Ends Diplomatic Trip, Arrives in Tirana</H3>
President of the Republic of Kosova, Dr. Ibrahim Rugova, said Wednesday his
trip to several European capitals and the U.S.A was successful.
<P>Dr. Ibrahim Rugova told the Albanian TV, upon his arrival in the Albanian
capital Tirana, that the discussions he had with U.S. Secretary of State
Christopher and other administration officials, as well as Norwegian and
French officials, were important.
<P>The U.S. assured us on their continued support for Kosova and the
commitment to the resolution of the issue, President Rugova said.
<P>Norway pledged concrete support for Kosova, he said, noting the experience
of the Scandinavian countries in assisting towards resolution of problems
in peaceful ways.
<P>&quot;I pressed France and other countries of the European Union to establish a
direct presence in Kosova and work on the resolution of this flash-point&quot;,
the Kosova President said.
<H3><A NAME="02">[02]</A> Alarming Environmental Situation in Mitrovica</H3>
The environmental situation in Mitrovica is alarming, with catastrophic
consequences to the health of a 200.000 population.
<P>The Belgrade-based &quot;Dnevni Telegraf&quot; said today.
<P>The newspaper says that in a meeting of experts on ecology held Thursday in
Mitrovica it was said that the presence of lead in the air in the are is 60
times higher than the permitted maximum. None of the chimneys of the
&quot;Trep^a&quot; mining and industrial company have filters, while the Serb-
installed director, Novak Bijelic, had been preventing doctors from
conducting analysis on the intoxication of workers.
<P>The newspaper quoted a serb gynecologist, Dr. Radisa Vlaskovic, as telling
the conference that the number of persons suffering from cancerous diseased
and children's anemia has been drastically increasing in Mitrovica. While,
a Serbian high-ranking official Ferid Hamidovic, referred to &quot;Trep^a&quot; as a
&quot;black ecological spot&quot;.
<P>Dr. Momcilo Mikic, director of the Bureau for Health Protection in Zve^an,
a mine within the &quot;Trep^a&quot; company, is quoted to have stated that his teams
have been prevented to conduct analyses in &quot;Trep^a&quot; plants and mines,
notwithstanding the fact there has been an ever-increasing incidence of
workers' intoxication. As many as 7 tons of lead, 6 tons of zinc, as well
as other dangerous minerals such as mercury, indium, arsine and cadmium,
come out of &quot;Trep^a&quot; chimneys every year, Dr. Mikic is quoted to have
said.
<P>School Term in Kosova Ends Saturday without Progress on Implementation of
Education Accord In two days' time, on Saturday, will end the first
(winter) school term of the 1996/97 school year, the Ministry of Education
of the Republic of Kosova said.
<P>The school holidays for some 350.000 pupils and students in 840 elementary
schools and 66 secondary schools will last till 13 January 1993, when
classes resume in the second (summer) term.
<P>The University of Prishtina will have completed the first term by mid-
January.
<P>The Albanian students and teachers are about to complete yet another school
term in compellingly hard conditions amidst the Serbian regime's crackdown.
This is the sixth year in a row that the mainstream Kosova education system
has to operate in private homes and community centers, as a system which
some have mistakenly called a 'parallel' system, others 'underground'. The
local Serbs in Kosova, sponsored by the Belgrade regime, have in fact
established a parallel system of education in Kosova and, with the help of
Serb police, took over the public school buildings, the libraries, the
students dormitories, and canteens.
<P>There were hopes early in September that the Albanians will eventually be
able to go back to their own school buildings and the University of
Prishtina campus. Such hopes and expectations were raised by an educational
accord reached by the Kosovar and Serbian sides, confirmed by presidents
Rugova and Milosevic, which envisaged an unconditional return of Albanian
students and teachers back to their premises.
<P>The Serbs reneged on their promises, they failed to deliver. The signing of
the Accord served Milosevic boost his image before the world in the run-up
to the lifting of the international sanctions.
<P>The Albanians in Kosova will have to look for ways to restore some
normality to their educational life. Going back to the school buildings is
the first, necessary step. Some political forces have called for a tougher
stance, arguing that the schools will have to be 'recaptured' in the face
of the continued Serbian regime's intransigence.
<H3><A NAME="03">[03]</A> Repatriated Albanians Being Held at Prishtina Airport</H3>
Since last Saturday, several Kosova Albanians, repatriated from Germany,
have been held at the Prishtina airport.
<P>The Prishtina-based Bujku said today that the Serbian police at Prishtina
airport have not so far provided any explanation as to the reason or the
number of people being held there.
<P>Referring to unofficial sources, Bujku said that seven person are still
being held at the airport since last Saturday.
<P>Meanwhile, the Prishtina-based Council for the Defence of Human Rights and
Freedoms (CDHRF) said earlier this week that 16 Albanians, including a
mother with two children were being held in Prishtina airport since 7
December 1996, under the pretext they were not in possession of valid
travel papers.
<P><H4>Kosova Information Center</H4>
<HR>
