<H2>Kosova Daily Report #1037, 96-12-20</H2>
<H5><A HREF="/news/balkans/kosova">Kosovo Information Center: Kosova Daily Report</A> Directory - <A HREF="96-12-19.ksv.html">Previous Article</A> - <A HREF="96-12-23.ksv.html">Next Article</A></H5>
<H4>From: Kosova Information Center &lt;<A HREF="mailto:kic_pr@zana-pr.ztn.apc.org">kic_pr@zana-pr.ztn.apc.org</A>&gt;</H4>
<H4>Kosova Information Center</H4>
<H4>KOSOVA DAILY REPORT #1037</H4>
<H4>Prishtina, 20 December 1996</H4>
<HR>
<H3>CONTENTS</H3>
<H4>
<DIR>
 <LI><A HREF="#01">[01]</A> LDK Press Conference
 <LI><A HREF="#02">[02]</A> Liberal Party of Kosova Marks Fifth Anniversary of Founding
 <LI><A HREF="#03">[03]</A> LDK Activist to Serve 6 Month in Prison
 <LI><A HREF="#04">[04]</A> Dozen of Albanians Being Held at Prishtina Airport Fear Deportation
 <LI><A HREF="#05">[05]</A> Serbian Police Interrogates Repatriated Kosova Albanians
 <LI><A HREF="#06">[06]</A> Repression Chronicle
</DIR>
</H4>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="01">[01]</A> LDK Press Conference</H3>
Vice-chairman of the Democratic League of Kosova (LDK), Dr. Fehmi Agani,
hailed today (Friday) the meeting President of the Republic of Kosova Dr.
Ibrahim Rugova had with French and Albanian officials.
<P>Granting Dr. Rugova the Doctor Honoris Causa degree by the University of
Paris-VIII means honoring not only Rugova himself, as an intellectual and
politician, but also the non-violent policies he has advocated in the
pursuit of the legitimate rights of the people of Kosova, the LDK vice-
chairman said, highlighting the reported position of the French officials
supportive of a solution to the Kosova issue &quot;compatible with the
aspirations&quot; of the people.
<P>The meeting President Rugova of Kosova had Thursday in Tirana with
President Berisha of Albania reconfirmed the unrelenting support of Albania
to the Kosova issue, Dr. Fehmi said during a press conference. He hailed in
this context the adoption of a resolution on Kosova by the U.N. General
Assembly and the role of the Albanian delegation to the U.N. in its
promotion.
<P>The LDK vice-chairman deplored the silence with which the Serbian regime
have surrounded the killing of the Albanian teacher, Feriz Blak^ori, &quot;a
victim of the Serbian chauvinist terror&quot;.
<P>The Serbia state-sponsored terror in Kosova has been continuing, Dr. Agani
said, referring to reports of persecution by the Serbian security and
police of Albanian citizens and activists alike. &quot;A fresh check-point for
the ill-treatment and harassment of Albanians is in the making, a the
Prishtina airport&quot;, the LDK official told reporters, adding that the Serb
regime authorities have been holding up Albanian returnees, although
possessing all the due valid documentation. Such people, under trumped up
excuses, are being held up and threatened with deportation to third
countries, he said. &quot;The goal is clear: to create the feeling amongst the
Albanians abroad that they cannot return back home in Kosova&quot;, Dr. Fehmi
Agani said, pointing out that this is in keeping with the genocidal
policies of the Serbian regime which is after seeing as many Albanians out
of Kosova.
<P>Commenting on the current developments in Serbia, the opposition rallies
and the regime's reaction, the LDK vice-chairman noted that the gist of the
Milosevic's regime is to restore the 1987-like situation, resorting to the
same rhetoric - &quot;xenophobia, pseudo- patriotism and primitive anti-Albanian
drive&quot;. The alleged (non- existing) collaboration of the opposition with
the Albanians is being used by the Serb regime to accuse the political
opposition, the LDK vice-chairman said.
<P>While we have been trying to maintain a distanced stance, being sympathetic
of all democratic efforts, the instigation of an anti- Albanian hysteria
and the efforts to stage pro-regime rallies in Kosova on the basis of a
hegemonist triumphalism, may result in unprecedented and dangerous
implications, Dr. Fehmi Agani said.
<P>The opposition movement in Serbia is quite heterogeneous, he remarked,
adding that the support the Albanians in Kosova and Albania may give, is
&quot;support for the democratic streak&quot;, that is against the electoral frauds
of the totalitarian regime. This is positive, but this does not mean
standing fully behind the opposition. The support should be commensurate
with the democratic streak in it, Dr. Fehmi Agani stressed, commenting on
the qualified support for what the Serb opposition.
<H3><A NAME="02">[02]</A> Liberal Party of Kosova Marks Fifth Anniversary of Founding</H3>
The Liberal Party of Kosova (Partia Liberale e Kosov&amp;s - PLK) marked today
in a solemn gathering five years of its activity.
<P>Numerous representatives of institutions of the Republic of Kosova,
political parties and associations attended the solemnity.
<P>Addressing the solemnity, Mr. Gjergj Dedaj, PLK chairman, said that the
Liberal Party of Kosova from it outset has been endeavoring in
internationalizing the Kosova issue, and has pressing for a just solution
of the Kosova issue in compliance with the will of the people. The PLK will
never give up its struggle for an independent Kosova, he said.
<P>The PLK has been traditionally awarding domestic and foreign institutions
and public figures with the &quot;Marie Shllaku&quot; Reward.
<P>This year's recipients of the Award were U.S. Congressman Eliot Engel, Co-
chairman of the Albanian Issues Caucus at the U.S. House of Representatives,
Dr. Michael Weninger, Ambassador of Austria in Belgrade, British MP Sir
Richard Moore, and the Prishtina-based Kosova Information Center (KIC).
<P>In a letter sent to the PLK, Sir Richard Moore said he could not attend the
manifestation for he had been refused a visa by the &quot;FRY&quot; authorities. &quot;It
is with both sadness and anger that I have to tell you that no visa has so
far been forthcoming from Belgrade regime, although it was applied for
three weeks ago&quot;, he said.
<P>Wishing PLK s successful manifestation Sir Richard Moore notes that &quot;as
long as the extreme injustice, to which you are subjected by the Belgrade
regime, continues, peace is in peril and it is the duty of all Liberals and
Democrats to insist that freedom should reign in Kosova&quot;.
<P>Rep. Eliot Engel, regretting he could not personally be in Prishtina to
accept the reward said that he was deeply honored. &quot;As you know, my
feelings about Kosova are as strong as ever. I firmly believe that the full
spectrum of internationally guaranteed human and political right must be
immediately and unconditionally restored to the people of Kosova. Until all
the Kosovars are able to determine their own future, the United States and
the international community must keep real pressure on Serbian dictator
Slobodan Milosevic and must not lift the outer wall of sanctions against
Belgrade&quot;, Engel said in his letter.
<P>CDHRF Monthly Report on Serbian Regime Repression in Kosova In a monthly
report [November 1996] on human rights situation in Kosova, the Prishtina-
based Council for the Defence of Human Rights and Freedoms (CDHRF) said the
Serbian regime and police repression against Kosova Albanians has continued
with impunity.
<P>All strata of population, including children and women, were subjected to
various Serbian regime practices during the last month.
<P>One ethnic Albanian, Gani Bilall Memqaj (43), was killed by the Serbian
army at Pashtriku mountainside, at the Kosova-Albania border zone, while
the Serbian-installed authorities have so far produced no explanation as to
the incident, the report said.
<P>During November this year, the CDHRF has registered 129 cases of physical
ill-treatment of Albanians by the Serbia police, of whom 84 under the
pretext of arms searches. 4 persons suffered heavy body injuries, 67 were
arbitrary arrested, 50 persons were summoned to report at the Serbian
police stations, 30 political, sports and trade-unions activists ill-
treated.
<P>The Serbian police raided on Albanian-language school on three occasions,
said the report. In addition, Albanian schoolchildren were harassed and
threatened by armed Serb civilians, said the report illustrating it with
the occurrence of 19 November, when a Serb civilian named Slobo Kastratovic,
opened arms fire near the elementary school &quot;Emin Duraku&quot;, in Gjakova. He
fired shots on the air and threatened he would &quot;kill all Albanians&quot;.
<P>The CDHRF notes that the Serbian court authorities have resumed court
proceedings against 13 Albanians from Peja, accused for having protested
the closing down of Albanian schools by the Serbian regime. 28 trade-union
activists were summoned to appear on 26 December before the Supreme Court
in Belgrade.
<P>The Council offers over a dozen dozens of illustrative case of Serbian
police harassment of Albanians having occurred in November this year.
<H3><A NAME="03">[03]</A> LDK Activist to Serve 6 Month in Prison</H3>
As reported earlier, on 13 December the Serbian police arrested Muhamet
Latifi, chairman of the LDK sub-branch at Pollata village of Podujeva.
<P>Today's Prishtina-based &quot;Bujku&quot; said that Mr. Latifi was initially held at
the police station in K&amp;rpimeh and later Podujeva. He was then sent to
prison in Leskovac (Serbia) to serve a six month prison sentence.
<P>In late 1994, during a raid on his house at Pollata village, Muhamet Latifi
was beaten up severely both in front of his family members and at the
police station. Although in very difficult health conditions he was
transferred to the Serbian police HQ in Prishtina, and from there he was
immediately sent to prison in Prokuple (Serbia). He was held then in prison
for 25 days, and while in prison, under the charges that he had been in
possession of arms, was sentenced by the Serbian Court in Prokuple to 6
month in prison.
<H3><A NAME="04">[04]</A> Dozen of Albanians Being Held at Prishtina Airport Fear Deportation</H3>
A dozen of Kosova Albanians, repatriated from Western Europe, have been
held at the Prishtina airport since 7 December.
<P>Bujku said today that the Serbian police has been preventing family members
and reporters from having any contact with the persons who are being held
in the airport. Bujku failed to obtain names of the detained persons. Yet,
it quotes police authorities at the airport as saying that some Albanians
have been held under the pretext of not being in possession of valid
travelling papers.
<P>The newspaper said that many people have been going every day to the
Prishtina airport in order to try find out whether their family members are
amongst those being held there. Referring to unofficial sources and various
speculations, Bujku says that the returnees may be deported to other
countries, Turkey mentioned as one of the most possible countries.
<H3><A NAME="05">[05]</A> Serbian Police Interrogates Repatriated Kosova Albanians</H3>
On 13 and 16 December, an Albanian couple Rexhep and Fiz&amp; Krasniqi from
Kishnareka village of Gllogovc, recently repatriated from Germany, were
interrogated by the Serbian state security in Gllogovc.
<P>LDK sourcesin Gllogovc said Mr. and Mrs. Krasniqi have been living in
Germany since 1993 and were repatraied after the agreement signed between
Germany and &quot;FRY&quot; authorities. They were both interrogated about their
whereabouts in Germany and whether they had been involved in any political
activity while there.
<P>Meanwhile sources in Suhareka said that Mejtim Sh. Byty^i from Reshtan
village, as well as several other Albanians from Suhareka who were returned
from Germany last month have been interrogated several times by the
Serebian police.
<P>LDK information commission in Suhareka said that Mejtim Byty^i was
threatened by the police that penal proceedings would be inistituted
against him.
<H3><A NAME="06">[06]</A> Repression Chronicle</H3>
Prishtina: On 17 December, the Serbian police raided on the home of Salih
Krasniqi in Prishtina. As Mr. Krasniqi was not at home, to police arrested
as hostage his son Naim Salihu.
<P>Salih Krasniqi appeared later himself at the Serbian police station where
he was told to hand over a rifle and a revolver. They were released the
same day but ordered to report back the next day.
<P>Kamenica: On 10 December, the Serbian police searched for arms the
household of Mufail Tha^i at Mu^iv&amp;rca village. Mr. Thaqi was later taken
to the police station and was interogated for several hours.
<P>Hani i Elezit: From 22 to 24 December, Fasli Axhami, from Hani i Elezit,
has been summoned to the socalled &quot;informative conversations&quot;. Sources
reported that Serbian police ordered him to hand over a revolver on which
occassions he had also been subjected to severe physical torture though he
had warned the police he sufferes heart disease. He had to seek medical
assistance at the Prishtina hospital.
<P><H4>Kosova Information Center</H4>
<HR>
