<HEAD>
<TITLE>Srpska Republika News Agency (SRNA), 96-12-22</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<center><a href="/info"><IMG SRC="/gifs/hrnet.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="[HR-Net Banner]"></a><BR></center>

<H2>Srpska Republika News Agency (SRNA), 96-12-22</H2>
<H5><A HREF="/news/balkans/srna">Srpska Republica News Agency (SRNA)</A> Directory - <A HREF="96-12-22.srna.html">Previous Article</A> - <A HREF="96-12-23.srna.html">Next Article</A></H5>
<H4>From: The Serbian Unity Congress Server at <A HREF="http://www.suc.org">http://www.suc.org</A></H4>
<HR>
<H3>DEC. 22, 1996 DAY</H3>
<H3>NEWS REVIEW, REPUBLIKA SRPSKA</H3>
<STRONG>LONDON</STRONG> - Humanitarian aid, which has been flowing into the Dayton B-H
during the war, contained &quot;hundreds of tonnes of unusable medicines &quot;,
reveals Sunday Times. The majoror portion of aid, according to the
Medicines Sans Frontieres, arrived from the USA, according to the paper.
<P><STRONG>BEOGRAD</STRONG> - The OSCE delegation found out that the results of the second
round of municipal elections were &quot;modified to the detriment of opposition
in 14 municipalities, i.e. major Serbia's cities&quot;, claim diplomatic sources,
close to the delegation.
<P><STRONG>BEOGRAD</STRONG> - The Serbian Radical Party (SRS) believes that it is sad that the
election results in Serbia are being verified by foreigners. &quot;We think that
a statement of OSCE delegation chief, Philippe Gonzales, that the available
data provide the right decision about the elections in Serbia, represents
the best proof of a brutal involvement in interior matters of our country&quot;,
writes SRS announcement.
<P><STRONG>BEOGRAD</STRONG> - The power hand-over would be carried out by 1997, stated
president of the Democratic Party (DS), Zoran Djindjic, who said in front
of 100,000 gathered demonstrators that, &quot;it is known who won in Serbia,
which will, as early as the first week of 1997, enter the 21 century.
&quot;
<P><STRONG>TRAVNIK</STRONG> - The Croatian Municipal Council of Travnik, asked for help and
protection from the latest Muslim terror against Croats in central Bosnia,
especially in Travnik and Zenica. In a communique, transmitted by Croat
media, the Council said that Muslim extremists removed all signs of the up-
coming Christmas celebration.
<H4>/end/</H4>
<FONT SIZE=-1>Copyright &copy; Srpska Novinska Agencija - SRNA Republika Srpska</FONT>
